window.STUDY_DATA = [{"chapter": 1, "title": "The values and principles of the UK", "sections": [{"id": "1.1", "title": "Chapter 1: The values and principles of the UK", "summary": "- This chapter covers the fundamental rights and responsibilities which apply to **everyone who lives in the UK, citizen or not**, plus information about the format of the Life in the UK Test and the requirements for becoming a permanent resident.\n- **Important:** questions in the real test are based on the **whole book, including this introductory chapter** — be familiar with the application process for permanent residence and the rights and responsibilities of UK residents.\n- In this chapter there is information about:\n  - The fundamental principles of British life\n  - Responsibilities and freedoms of all UK residents\n  - Becoming a permanent resident\n  - Taking the Life in the UK test\n  - The testable sections of the book\n- Britain is described as a fantastic place to live: a modern, thriving society with a long and illustrious history; its people have been at the heart of the world's political, scientific, industrial and cultural development. The UK is proud of its record of welcoming new migrants who add to the diversity and dynamism of national life.\n- Applying to become a permanent resident or citizen is an important decision and commitment: you agree to accept the responsibilities that go with permanent residence and to respect the laws, values and traditions of the UK.\n- Passing the Life in the UK test is part of demonstrating that you are ready to become a permanent migrant to the UK. The handbook helps you integrate into society, play a full role in your local community, and gain a broad general knowledge of the culture, laws and history of the UK.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "1.2", "title": "Becoming a permanent resident", "summary": "- To apply to become a permanent resident or citizen of the UK you need to:\n  - **speak and read English**\n  - **have a good understanding of life in the UK**\n- Currently (as of January 2013) there are **two ways** to be tested on these requirements:\n  1. **Take the Life in the UK test.** Questions are written to require English at **ESOL Entry Level 3**, so no separate English language test is needed. People on work visas (including Tier 1 and Tier 2 of the points-based system) normally must pass this test to become permanent residents.\n  2. **Pass an ESOL course in English with Citizenship.** Required if your English is **below ESOL Entry Level 3**; the course helps improve your English and teaches about life in the UK, with a test at the end.\n- Once you have passed one of these tests, you can apply for permanent residence or British citizenship. The form and evidence required depend on your personal circumstances; there is a **fee** for submitting an application, which differs by application type. Forms and fees are on the UK Border Agency website, www.ukba.homeoffice.gov.uk.\n- **From October 2013** the requirements change: for settlement or permanent residence you will need to:\n  - **Pass the Life in the UK test, AND**\n  - **Produce acceptable evidence of speaking and listening skills in English at B1 of the Common European Framework of Reference** (equivalent to ESOL Entry Level 3).\n- Requirements for citizenship applications may also change in the future — check the UK Border Agency website for current requirements before applying for settlement or citizenship.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "1.3", "title": "The values and principles of the UK", "summary": "- British society is founded on fundamental values and principles which all those living in the UK should respect and support. These values are reflected in the responsibilities, rights and privileges of being a British citizen or permanent resident. They are **based on history and traditions** and are **protected by law, customs and expectations**.\n- **There is no place in British society for extremism or intolerance.**\n- The **fundamental principles of British life** include:\n  - Democracy\n  - The rule of law\n  - Individual liberty\n  - Tolerance of those with different faiths and beliefs\n  - Participation in community life\n- As part of the **citizenship ceremony**, new citizens pledge to uphold these values. The pledge is: *'I will give my loyalty to the United Kingdom and respect its rights and freedoms. I will uphold its democratic values. I will observe its laws faithfully and fulfil my duties and obligations as a British citizen.'*\n- Flowing from the fundamental principles are responsibilities and freedoms shared by all those living in the UK. If you wish to be a permanent resident or citizen, you should:\n  - respect and obey the law\n  - respect the rights of others, including their right to their own opinions\n  - treat others with fairness\n  - look after yourself and your family\n  - look after the area in which you live and the environment\n- In return, the UK offers:\n  - freedom of belief and religion\n  - freedom of speech\n  - freedom from unfair discrimination\n  - a right to a fair trial\n  - a right to join in the election of a government", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "1.4", "title": "Taking the Life in the UK test", "summary": "- The test consists of **24 questions** about important aspects of life in the UK, based on **ALL parts of the handbook**. The 24 questions will be **different for each person** taking the test at that test session.\n- The test is usually taken in **English**, though special arrangements can be made to take it in **Welsh or Scottish Gaelic**.\n- You can only take the test at a **registered and approved Life in the UK test centre** — there are about **60 test centres** around the UK. The UK Border Agency will only accept certificates from registered test centres.\n- You can **only book your test online**, at www.lifeintheuktest.gov.uk.\n- If you live on the **Isle of Man or in the Channel Islands**, there are different arrangements for taking the test.\n- When booking, read the instructions carefully and enter your details correctly. You must take **some identification and proof of your address** to the test — without these you will not be able to take the test.\n- **How to use the handbook:**\n  - Everything you need to know to pass the test is in the handbook; questions are based on the whole book, including the introduction, so study the entire book thoroughly.\n  - The handbook is written so anyone who can read English at **ESOL Entry Level 3 or above** should have no difficulty with the language.\n  - A **glossary** at the back contains key words and phrases.\n  - The **'Check that you understand' boxes are for guidance** — knowing only the things highlighted in these boxes will **not** be enough to pass the test; you need to understand everything in the book.\n- **Where to find more information:**\n  - UK Border Agency website (www.ukba.homeoffice.gov.uk) — application process and forms\n  - Life in the UK test website (www.lifeintheuktest.gov.uk) — the test and how to book\n  - Gov.uk (www.gov.uk) — ESOL courses and how to find one in your area", "checkUnderstand": ["The origin of the values underlying British society", "The fundamental principles of British life", "The responsibilities and freedoms which come with permanent residence", "The process of becoming a permanent resident or citizen."]}], "flashcards": [{"q": "Who do the fundamental rights and responsibilities described in the handbook apply to?", "a": "Everyone who lives in the UK, citizen or not.", "section": "1.1", "page": 4, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "Are the questions in the Life in the UK test based only on some chapters of the handbook?", "a": "No — questions are based on the whole book, including the introductory chapter.", "section": "1.1", "page": 4, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "What do you agree to when applying to become a permanent resident or citizen of the UK?", "a": "To accept the responsibilities which go with permanent residence and to respect the laws, values and traditions of the UK.", "section": "1.1", "page": 4, "tags": ["values", "process"]}, {"q": "What does passing the Life in the UK test demonstrate?", "a": "It is part of demonstrating that you are ready to become a permanent migrant to the UK.", "section": "1.1", "page": 4, "tags": ["test", "process"]}, {"q": "What two requirements must you meet to apply to become a permanent resident or citizen of the UK?", "a": "You must speak and read English, and have a good understanding of life in the UK.", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "As of January 2013, what are the two ways you can be tested on the requirements for permanent residence or citizenship?", "a": "1) Take the Life in the UK test; 2) Pass an ESOL course in English with Citizenship.", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "Why is there no need to take a separate English language test if you take the Life in the UK test?", "a": "Because the questions are written in a way that requires an understanding of English at ESOL Entry Level 3.", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process", "test"]}, {"q": "Who normally must pass the Life in the UK test to become permanent residents?", "a": "People here on work visas, including those on Tier 1 and Tier 2 of the points-based system.", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "Who needs to take an ESOL course in English with Citizenship instead of the Life in the UK test?", "a": "People whose standard of English is below ESOL Entry Level 3. At the end of the course they take a test.", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "Is there a fee for submitting an application for permanent residence or British citizenship?", "a": "Yes — the fee is different for the various types of application. All forms and a list of fees can be found on the UK Border Agency website (www.ukba.homeoffice.gov.uk).", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "From October 2013, what will you need for settlement or permanent residence?", "a": "Pass the Life in the UK test AND produce acceptable evidence of speaking and listening skills in English at B1 of the Common European Framework of Reference (equivalent to ESOL Entry Level 3).", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "Where should you check for the current requirements before applying for settlement or citizenship?", "a": "The UK Border Agency website (www.ukba.homeoffice.gov.uk).", "section": "1.2", "page": 5, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "What are the fundamental values and principles of British society based on, and how are they protected?", "a": "They are based on history and traditions, and are protected by law, customs and expectations.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "What is there no place for in British society?", "a": "Extremism or intolerance.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "What are the fundamental principles of British life?", "a": "Democracy; the rule of law; individual liberty; tolerance of those with different faiths and beliefs; participation in community life.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "At which ceremony do new citizens pledge to uphold the fundamental values of British life?", "a": "The citizenship ceremony.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values", "process"]}, {"q": "What is the pledge made by new citizens at the citizenship ceremony?", "a": "'I will give my loyalty to the United Kingdom and respect its rights and freedoms. I will uphold its democratic values. I will observe its laws faithfully and fulfil my duties and obligations as a British citizen.'", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "What responsibilities should you respect if you wish to be a permanent resident or citizen of the UK?", "a": "Respect and obey the law; respect the rights of others, including their right to their own opinions; treat others with fairness; look after yourself and your family; look after the area in which you live and the environment.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "What freedoms and rights does the UK offer in return for residents fulfilling their responsibilities?", "a": "Freedom of belief and religion; freedom of speech; freedom from unfair discrimination; a right to a fair trial; a right to join in the election of a government.", "section": "1.3", "page": 6, "tags": ["values"]}, {"q": "How many questions are there in the Life in the UK test?", "a": "24 questions about important aspects of life in the UK.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "Are the Life in the UK test questions the same for everyone at a test session?", "a": "No — the 24 questions will be different for each person taking the test at that test session.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "In which languages can the Life in the UK test be taken?", "a": "It is usually taken in English, but special arrangements can be made to take it in Welsh or Scottish Gaelic.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "Where can you take the Life in the UK test?", "a": "Only at a registered and approved Life in the UK test centre — the UK Border Agency will only accept certificates from registered test centres.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "About how many Life in the UK test centres are there around the UK?", "a": "About 60.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "How do you book the Life in the UK test?", "a": "You can only book online, at www.lifeintheuktest.gov.uk.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "What special situation applies if you live on the Isle of Man or in the Channel Islands?", "a": "There are different arrangements for taking the Life in the UK test.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "What must you bring with you to the Life in the UK test?", "a": "Some identification and proof of your address. If you don't take these, you will not be able to take the test.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "At what English reading level is the Life in the UK handbook written?", "a": "It is written so that anyone who can read English at ESOL Entry Level 3 or above should have no difficulty with the language.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "What does the glossary at the back of the handbook contain?", "a": "Some key words and phrases which you might find helpful.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "Is knowing only the content of the 'Check that you understand' boxes enough to pass the Life in the UK test?", "a": "No — the boxes are for guidance only; you need to understand everything in the book.", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "Where can you find more information about the application process and the forms you need to complete?", "a": "The UK Border Agency website (www.ukba.homeoffice.gov.uk).", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["process"]}, {"q": "Where can you find more information about the Life in the UK test and how to book a place?", "a": "The Life in the UK test website (www.lifeintheuktest.gov.uk).", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["test"]}, {"q": "Where can you find information about ESOL courses and how to find one in your area?", "a": "Gov.uk (www.gov.uk).", "section": "1.4", "page": 7, "tags": ["process"]}]}, {"chapter": 2, "title": "What is the UK?", "sections": [{"id": "2.1", "title": "Chapter 2: What is the UK?", "summary": "This chapter is about **the countries that make up the Union** and the **various phrases used to describe them**. Although the chapter is very short, you should read and understand all the facts presented. The book notes it is *very likely* there will be test questions about:\n\n- The differences between **Great Britain**, **the British Isles** and **Britain**\n- What the **Crown Dependencies** are\n\n**In this chapter there is information about:**\n\n- The different countries that make up the UK", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "2.2", "title": "What is the UK?", "summary": "**The countries of the UK.** The UK is made up of **England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland**. The rest of Ireland is an **independent country**.\n\n**Names and terms.** The official name of the country is the **United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland**. **'Great Britain'** refers only to **England, Scotland and Wales** — not to Northern Ireland. The book uses the words **'Britain'** and **'British'** to refer to everyone in the UK.\n\n**Crown dependencies.** Several islands are **closely linked with the UK but are not part of it**: the **Channel Islands** and the **Isle of Man**. These have their **own governments** and are called **'Crown dependencies'**.\n\n**British overseas territories.** There are also several British overseas territories in other parts of the world, such as **St Helena** and the **Falkland Islands**. They are also **linked to the UK but are not a part of it**.\n\n**Government.** The UK is governed by the **parliament sitting in Westminster**. **Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland** also have **parliaments or assemblies of their own**, with **devolved powers in defined areas**.", "checkUnderstand": ["The different countries that make up the UK"]}], "flashcards": [{"q": "Which four countries make up the UK?", "a": "England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["geography", "countries"]}, {"q": "What is the official name of the country?", "a": "The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["terminology"]}, {"q": "What does 'Great Britain' refer to?", "a": "Only England, Scotland and Wales — not Northern Ireland.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["terminology", "geography"]}, {"q": "Is the rest of Ireland (outside Northern Ireland) part of the UK?", "a": "No. The rest of Ireland is an independent country.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["geography", "countries"]}, {"q": "How are the words 'Britain' and 'British' used in the handbook?", "a": "They are used in the book to refer to everyone in the UK.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["terminology"]}, {"q": "Which islands are the Crown dependencies?", "a": "The Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["geography", "crown-dependencies"]}, {"q": "What are 'Crown dependencies'?", "a": "Islands that are closely linked with the UK but are not part of it — the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man. They have their own governments.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["terminology", "crown-dependencies"]}, {"q": "Are the Crown dependencies part of the UK?", "a": "No. They are closely linked with the UK but are not part of it, and have their own governments.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["crown-dependencies"]}, {"q": "Name two examples of British overseas territories.", "a": "St Helena and the Falkland Islands.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["geography", "overseas-territories"]}, {"q": "Are British overseas territories part of the UK?", "a": "No. They are linked to the UK but are not a part of it.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["overseas-territories"]}, {"q": "Where is the UK governed from?", "a": "The UK is governed by the parliament sitting in Westminster.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "Which countries of the UK have their own parliaments or assemblies?", "a": "Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland — with devolved powers in defined areas.", "section": "2.2", "page": 9, "tags": ["government", "devolution"]}]}, {"chapter": 3, "title": "A long and illustrious history", "sections": [{"id": "3.2", "title": "Britain since 1945", "summary": "## The welfare state\n- In **1945** the British people elected a **Labour** government; the new Prime Minister was **Clement Attlee**, who promised to introduce the welfare state outlined in the **Beveridge Report**.\n- In **1948**, **Aneurin (Nye) Bevan**, the Minister for Health, led the establishment of the **National Health Service (NHS)** — a minimum standard of health care for all, free at the point of use. A national system of benefits ('social security') protected people from the 'cradle to the grave'.\n- The government **nationalised** the railways, coal mines and gas, water and electricity supplies.\n- In **1947**, independence was granted to **nine countries**, including **India, Pakistan and Ceylon (now Sri Lanka)**; other colonies in Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific followed over the next 20 years.\n- The UK developed its own **atomic bomb** and joined **NATO**, an alliance set up to resist the perceived threat of invasion by the Soviet Union and its allies.\n- Britain had a **Conservative government from 1951 to 1964**; the 1950s were a period of economic recovery. PM **Harold Macmillan** was famous for his **'wind of change'** speech about decolonisation.\n\n## Key people\n- **Clement Attlee (1883–1967)**: barrister turned Labour MP; Churchill's Deputy Prime Minister in the wartime coalition; PM **1945–51**; led Labour for 20 years; nationalised major industries, created the NHS and implemented Beveridge's plans.\n- **William Beveridge (1879–1963)**: economist and social reformer; briefly a Liberal MP; best known for the **1942 report 'Social Insurance and Allied Services' (Beveridge Report)**, commissioned in 1941, which targeted the five 'Giant Evils' of **Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness**.\n- **R A Butler (1902–82)**: Conservative MP from 1923; responsible for education from 1941; oversaw the **Education Act 1944 ('The Butler Act')** — free secondary education in England and Wales.\n- **Dylan Thomas (1914–53)**: Welsh poet and writer — *Under Milk Wood* (first performed 1954) and *Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night*; memorials in his birthplace, Swansea.\n\n## Migration in post-war Britain\n- Labour shortages: workers encouraged from **Ireland and other parts of Europe**; in **1948** people from the **West Indies** were invited to come and work.\n- In the 1950s, centres were set up in the West Indies to recruit **bus drivers**; textile and engineering firms sent agents to **India and Pakistan**. For about 25 years people came from the West Indies, India, Pakistan and (later) Bangladesh.\n\n## Social change in the 1960s\n- The **'Swinging Sixties'**: growth in British fashion, cinema and pop music — **The Beatles** and **The Rolling Stones**.\n- Social laws liberalised (divorce; abortion in England, Wales and Scotland); Parliament gave women the right to **equal pay** and outlawed discrimination against women because of their gender.\n- Britain and France developed **Concorde**, the world's only supersonic commercial airliner.\n- In the late 1960s immigration was restricted (a strong connection to Britain through birth or ancestry was required); in the early 1970s Britain admitted **28,000 people of Indian origin** forced to leave Uganda.\n\n## Great British inventions of the 20th century\n- **Television** — **John Logie Baird** (Scottish), 1920s; first broadcast between London and Glasgow in **1932**.\n- **Radar** — **Sir Robert Watson-Watt** (Scottish); first successful test **1935**.\n- **Sir Bernard Lovell** — built the radio telescope at **Jodrell Bank**, Cheshire.\n- **Turing machine** — **Alan Turing**, 1930s; influential in computer science.\n- **John MacLeod** (Scottish physician) — co-discoverer of **insulin**.\n- **DNA structure** discovered in **1953** (London and Cambridge); **Francis Crick** awarded the Nobel Prize.\n- **Jet engine** — **Sir Frank Whittle** (RAF engineer officer), 1930s.\n- **Hovercraft** — **Sir Christopher Cockerell**, 1950s.\n- **Harrier jump jet** — vertical take-off aircraft, designed and developed in the UK.\n- **Concorde** — first flew **1969**, carried passengers from **1976**, retired **2003**.\n- **ATM ('cashpoint')** — **James Goodfellow**, 1960s; first used by Barclays Bank in Enfield, north London in **1967**.\n- **IVF** — **Sir Robert Edwards** and **Patrick Steptoe**; world's first 'test-tube baby' born in Oldham, Lancashire in **1978**.\n- **Cloning of Dolly the sheep** (first cloned mammal) — **Sir Ian Wilmot** and **Keith Campbell**, **1996**.\n- **MRI scanner** — co-invented by **Sir Peter Mansfield**.\n- **World Wide Web** — **Sir Tim Berners-Lee**; information first transferred via the web on **25 December 1990**.\n\n## The 1970s\n- The post-war boom ended: rising prices, unstable exchange rate, 'balance of payments' problems, strikes and disputes between trade unions and government.\n- Serious unrest in Northern Ireland: in **1972** the Northern Ireland Parliament was **suspended** and Northern Ireland was directly ruled by the UK government; some **3,000 people** lost their lives in the decades after 1969.\n- **Mary Peters**: won an **Olympic gold medal in the pentathlon in 1972**; later team manager of the women's British Olympic team; made a **Dame** in 2000.\n\n## Europe\n- The **EEC** was formed in **1957** by West Germany, France, Belgium, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands; the UK joined in **1973**. The UK is a full member of the European Union but does not use the Euro.\n\n## Conservative government 1979–1997\n- **Margaret Thatcher (1925–2013)**: grocer's daughter from Grantham; chemist and lawyer; Conservative MP 1959; cabinet minister 1970 (Education and Science); Conservative leader 1975; became the **first woman Prime Minister in 1979** and the **longest-serving PM of the 20th century** (in office until **1990**). Privatisation of nationalised industries, legal controls on trade unions, deregulation and growth of the City of London; worked closely with US President Ronald Reagan.\n- In **1982 Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands**; a naval taskforce recovered the islands.\n- **John Major** was PM after Thatcher and helped establish the Northern Ireland peace process.\n- **Roald Dahl (1916–90)**: born in Wales to Norwegian parents; served in the RAF in WWII; children's books include *Charlie and the Chocolate Factory* and *George's Marvellous Medicine*.\n\n## Labour government 1997–2010\n- **Tony Blair** elected **1997**; introduced a **Scottish Parliament** (substantial legislative powers) and a **Welsh Assembly** (fewer legislative powers but considerable control over public services).\n- **Good Friday Agreement** signed **1998**; Northern Ireland Assembly elected **1999**, suspended **2002**, reinstated **2007**. **Gordon Brown** became PM in **2007**.\n\n## Conflicts\n- 1990s: Britain led coalition forces in the **liberation of Kuwait** (after the Iraqi invasion in **1990**) and the conflict in the Former Republic of Yugoslavia.\n- Operations in Afghanistan and Iraq since 2000; British combat troops left Iraq in **2009**; the UK operates in Afghanistan as part of the UN-mandated 50-nation **ISAF** coalition.\n\n## Governments since 2010\n- **May 2010**: no party won an overall majority (first time since **February 1974**); Conservative–Liberal Democrat **coalition**, with **David Cameron** as PM (to 2015).\n- **Conservative Government 2015–2024**: PMs **David Cameron, Theresa May, Boris Johnson, Liz Truss and Rishi Sunak**; the **2016 EU membership referendum (Brexit)** and the COVID-19 pandemic; Rishi Sunak called a general election for **4 July 2024**.\n- **Labour Government from 2024**: Labour, led by **Keir Starmer**, won the 2024 general election.", "checkUnderstand": ["The establishment of the welfare state", "How life in Britain changed in the 1960s and 1970s", "British inventions of the 20th century (you do not need to remember dates of births and deaths)", "Events since 1979"]}, {"id": "3.3", "title": "A global power", "summary": "## Constitutional monarchy — the Bill of Rights\n- At the coronation of **William and Mary**, a **Declaration of Rights** was read: the king could no longer raise taxes or administer justice without Parliament's agreement.\n- The **Bill of Rights, 1689** confirmed the rights of Parliament and the limits of the king's power; the monarch **must be a Protestant**; a new Parliament had to be elected at least every **three years** (later seven, now five); the monarch had to ask Parliament every year to renew funding for the army and navy.\n- Two main groups in Parliament — the **Whigs** and the **Tories** — the beginning of **party politics**.\n- From **1695**, newspapers were allowed to operate **without a government licence** (development of a free press).\n- These laws began **'constitutional monarchy'**, but it was not a democracy: only men owning property of a certain value could vote; no women could vote; **'pocket boroughs'** were controlled by a single wealthy family and **'rotten boroughs'** had hardly any voters.\n\n## A growing population\n- The first **Jews** since the Middle Ages settled in London in **1656**.\n- Between **1680 and 1720**, **Huguenots** (Protestant refugees persecuted in France) came to Britain — many were educated and skilled.\n\n## The Act of Union\n- Queen Anne had no surviving children, creating uncertainty over the succession. The **Act of Union** (known as the **Treaty of Union** in Scotland) was agreed in **1707**, creating the **Kingdom of Great Britain**. Scotland kept its own legal and education systems and Presbyterian Church.\n\n## The Prime Minister\n- When **Queen Anne died in 1714**, Parliament chose **George I** (a German, Anne's nearest Protestant relative). A Jacobite attempt to put James II's son on the throne was quickly defeated.\n- George I relied on his ministers; the most important became known as the **Prime Minister**. The first was **Sir Robert Walpole**, PM **1721–1742**.\n\n## The rebellion of the clans\n- In **1745**, **Charles Edward Stuart ('Bonnie Prince Charlie')**, grandson of James II, landed in Scotland to take the throne from George II; defeated at the **Battle of Culloden in 1746**; escaped to Europe.\n- The clans lost power; the **'Highland Clearances'** followed — landlords destroyed small farms ('crofts') for sheep and cattle; evictions were common in the early 19th century and many Scots left for North America.\n- **Robert Burns (1759–96)**, 'The Bard': Scottish poet; best-known work **Auld Lang Syne**, sung at New Year (Hogmanay in Scotland).\n\n## The Enlightenment\n- 18th-century new ideas in politics, philosophy and science; many great thinkers were Scottish: **Adam Smith** (economics), **David Hume** (human nature/philosophy), **James Watt** (steam power).\n- Key principle: everyone should have the right to their own political and religious beliefs — still important in the UK today.\n\n## The Industrial Revolution\n- Rapid development of industry in the **18th and 19th centuries**; Britain was the **first country to industrialise on a large scale**, driven by machinery and **steam power**.\n- The **Bessemer process** for mass production of steel led to shipbuilding and railways; manufacturing became the main source of employment.\n- **Richard Arkwright (1732–92)**: originally a barber/wig-maker; improved the carding machine; developed horse-driven spinning mills; later used steam engines; remembered for running factories efficiently and profitably.\n- **Canals** were built to link factories to towns, cities and ports.\n- Working conditions were very poor — no laws protected employees; children worked and were sometimes treated even more harshly than adults.\n- Increased colonisation: **Captain James Cook** mapped the coast of **Australia**; Britain gained control over Canada; the **East India Company** gained control of large parts of India; colonies established in southern Africa.\n- **Sake Dean Mahomet (1759–1851)**: from Bengal; served in the Bengal army; came to Britain in 1782; in **1810** opened the **Hindoostane Coffee House** in George Street, London — the **first curry house in Britain**; he and his wife introduced **'shampooing'** (Indian head massage) to Britain.\n\n## The slave trade\n- Slavery was illegal within Britain itself but a fully established overseas industry by the 18th century; slaves came primarily from **West Africa** and worked on tobacco and sugar plantations in America and the Caribbean.\n- The **Quakers** set up the first formal anti-slavery groups in the late 1700s; **William Wilberforce**, an evangelical Christian and MP, helped turn public opinion against the trade.\n- In **1807** it became illegal to trade slaves in British ships or from British ports; the **Emancipation Act 1833** abolished slavery throughout the British Empire. The Royal Navy stopped foreign slave ships.\n- After 1833, **2 million Indian and Chinese workers** were employed to replace freed slaves.\n\n## The American war of independence\n- The British government wanted to tax the colonies; colonists demanded **'no taxation without representation'**.\n- In **1776**, **13 American colonies declared their independence**; Britain recognised their independence in **1783**.\n\n## War with France\n- Revolution in France in **1789**; the new French government declared war on Britain; **Napoleon** continued the war.\n- **Battle of Trafalgar, 1805**: Britain's navy defeated combined French and Spanish fleets; **Admiral Nelson** commanded and was killed — commemorated by Nelson's Column in Trafalgar Square; his ship **HMS Victory** can be visited in Portsmouth.\n- **1815, Battle of Waterloo**: the **Duke of Wellington** ('the Iron Duke', later Prime Minister) defeated Napoleon, ending the French Wars.\n\n## The Union Flag\n- The **Act of Union of 1800** unified Ireland with England, Scotland and Wales in **1801**, creating the **United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland**.\n- The **Union Flag ('Union Jack')** combines three crosses: **St George** (England, red cross on white), **St Andrew** (Scotland, diagonal white cross on blue), **St Patrick** (Ireland, diagonal red cross on white).\n- The Welsh dragon does not appear because Wales was already united with England when the first Union Flag was created in **1606**.\n\n## The Victorian Age\n- **Queen Victoria** became queen in **1837 aged 18** and reigned until **1901** — almost 64 years, the longest reign of any British monarch at the date of writing (2013).\n- The **British Empire** grew to cover all of India, Australia and large parts of Africa — the largest empire the world has ever seen, with more than **400 million people**.\n- Between **1853 and 1913**, as many as **13 million** British citizens left the country; between **1870 and 1914** around **120,000 Russian and Polish Jews** came to Britain to escape persecution.\n- Free trade: the **Corn Laws were repealed in 1846**, allowing cheap grain imports.\n- In **1847** the working hours of women and children were limited by law to **10 hours per day**.\n- **George and Robert Stephenson** (father and son) pioneered the **railway engine**; **Isambard Kingdom Brunel (1806–59)** built tunnels, bridges, railway lines and ships, including the **Great Western Railway** — the first major railway built in Britain.\n- 19th-century UK produced **more than half of the world's iron, coal and cotton cloth** and became a centre for financial services.\n- The **Great Exhibition** opened in **1851** in Hyde Park in the **Crystal Palace**.\n\n## The Crimean War\n- **1853–1856**: Britain fought **with Turkey and France against Russia** — the first war extensively covered by the media. Queen Victoria introduced the **Victoria Cross** medal for acts of valour.\n- **Florence Nightingale (1820–1910)**: born in Italy; nursed soldiers in military hospitals in Turkey during the Crimean War (from 1854); founded the **Nightingale Training School** at St Thomas' Hospital, London in **1860**; regarded as the founder of modern nursing.\n\n## Ireland in the 19th century\n- The potato crop failed in the middle of the century — famine: **a million died** and **a million and a half left Ireland** (to the US and England). By **1861** there were large Irish populations in Liverpool, London, Manchester and Glasgow.\n- The Irish Nationalist movement grew: the **Fenians** favoured complete independence; **Charles Stuart Parnell** advocated **'Home Rule'** (Ireland in the UK with its own parliament).\n\n## The right to vote\n- The **Reform Act of 1832** greatly increased the number of voters, abolished pocket and rotten boroughs, and gave more seats to towns and cities — but voting was still based on property ownership.\n- The **Chartists** campaigned for the vote for the working classes; the **Reform Act of 1867** created more urban seats and reduced the property qualification, but most men and all women still could not vote.\n- **Universal suffrage** (the right of every adult, male or female, to vote) followed in the next century.\n- Until **1870**, a married woman's earnings, property and money automatically belonged to her husband; **Acts of Parliament in 1870 and 1882** gave wives the right to keep their own earnings and property.\n- Women campaigning for the vote formed the women's suffrage movement — the **'suffragettes'**.\n- **Emmeline Pankhurst (1858–1928)**: born in Manchester; set up the **Women's Franchise League (1889)**; helped found the **Women's Social and Political Union (WSPU) in 1903** — the first group called 'suffragettes'; used civil disobedience and hunger strikes. In **1918** women over **30** got the vote and the right to stand for Parliament; in **1928** women got the vote at **21**, the same as men.\n\n## The future of the Empire\n- The Empire continued to grow until the **1920s**, though its future was debated from the late 19th century.\n- The **Boer War, 1899–1902**: Britain fought in South Africa against the **Boers** (settlers from the Netherlands); many died in fighting and from disease; public sympathy for the Boers led people to question the Empire.\n- By the second half of the 20th century there was, for the most part, an orderly transition from **Empire to Commonwealth**.\n- **Rudyard Kipling (1865–1936)**: born in India; his writing reflected the idea that the Empire was a force for good; awarded the **Nobel Prize in Literature in 1907**; works include the *Just So Stories*, *The Jungle Book* and the poem *If*.", "checkUnderstand": ["The change in the balance of power between Parliament and the monarchy", "When and why Scotland joined England and Wales to become Great Britain", "The reasons for a rebellion in Scotland led by Bonnie Prince Charlie", "The ideas of the Enlightenment", "The importance of the Industrial Revolution and development of industry", "The slave trade and when it was abolished", "The growth of the British Empire", "How democracy developed during this period"]}, {"id": "3.4", "title": "The 20th century", "summary": "## The First World War\n- The early 20th century was a time of optimism — Britain was a global 'superpower' — and of social progress: financial help for the unemployed, **old-age pensions**, **free school meals**, workplace safety laws, town planning rules against slums, and **a salary for MPs** introduced for the first time.\n- On **28 June 1914**, **Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria was assassinated**, triggering the **First World War (1914–18)**. Underlying factors: nationalism, militarism, imperialism and the division of the major European powers into two camps.\n- Britain was part of the **Allied Powers** (with France, Russia, Japan, Belgium, Serbia — later Greece, Italy, Romania and the United States) against the **Central Powers** (Germany, the Austro-Hungarian Empire, the Ottoman Empire and later Bulgaria).\n- The whole Empire was involved: **more than a million Indians** fought for Britain and **around 40,000 were killed**; men from the West Indies, Africa, Australia, New Zealand and Canada also fought.\n- More than **2 million British casualties**; the British attack on the **Somme in July 1916** caused about **60,000 British casualties on the first day alone**.\n- The war ended at **11.00 am on 11 November 1918** with victory for Britain and its allies.\n\n## The partition of Ireland\n- In **1913** the British government promised **'Home Rule'** for Ireland; the proposal was opposed by the **Protestants in the north**, who threatened to resist by force. The outbreak of WWI postponed any changes.\n- In **1916** the **Easter Rising** against the British took place in Dublin; its leaders were executed under military law; a guerrilla war followed.\n- A peace treaty was signed in **1921**; in **1922** Ireland became two countries: the six mainly Protestant counties in the north remained in the UK as **Northern Ireland**; the rest became the **Irish Free State**, which became a **republic in 1949**.\n- The conflict between those wanting full Irish independence and those loyal to the British government is often called **'the Troubles'**.\n\n## The inter-war period\n- The 1920s brought improved living conditions and public housing; in **1929** the world entered the **'Great Depression'** and parts of the UK suffered mass unemployment.\n- Heavy industries (e.g. shipbuilding) were badly affected, but new industries (automobile, aviation) developed; **car ownership doubled from 1 million to 2 million between 1930 and 1939**.\n- Cultural blossoming: writers **Graham Greene** and **Evelyn Waugh**; economist **John Maynard Keynes** published influential theories.\n- The **BBC** started radio broadcasts in **1922** and began the **world's first regular television service in 1936**.\n\n## The Second World War\n- **Adolf Hitler** came to power in Germany in **1933**; when he **invaded Poland in 1939**, Britain and France declared war.\n- **Axis powers**: fascist Germany and Italy and the Empire of Japan; main **Allies**: UK, France, Poland, Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the Union of South Africa.\n- In **1940** German forces advanced through France; **Winston Churchill** became Prime Minister and Britain's war leader.\n- **Dunkirk**: more than **300,000 men** were rescued from the beaches by the Navy helped by civilian volunteers in small boats — 'the Dunkirk spirit'.\n- From end of June 1940 until June 1941 (the German invasion of the Soviet Union), Britain and the Empire stood almost alone against Nazi Germany.\n- The **Battle of Britain** (crucial aerial battle, **summer of 1940**) was won by the RAF with the **Spitfire** and **Hurricane**, both designed and built in Britain. German night bombing — **the Blitz** — followed: Coventry almost totally destroyed; heavy damage in London's East End; 'the Blitz spirit'.\n- **Winston Churchill (1874–1965)**: soldier and journalist; Conservative MP from 1900; PM May 1940; refused to surrender to the Nazis; lost the 1945 General Election but returned as PM in 1951; MP until 1964; state funeral on his death in 1965; voted the **greatest Briton of all time in 2002**. Famous 1940 speeches: 'blood, toil, tears and sweat'; 'we shall fight on the beaches... we shall never surrender' (after Dunkirk); 'Never in the field of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few' (Battle of Britain).\n- The Japanese defeated the British in Singapore and occupied Burma; the **US entered the war after Japan bombed Pearl Harbour in December 1941**. In 1941 Hitler attacked the Soviet Union — the largest invasion in history; German losses there proved a pivotal point.\n- On **6 June 1944** allied forces landed in Normandy (**'D-Day'**); the Allies comprehensively defeated Germany in **May 1945**.\n- The war against Japan ended in **August 1945** when the US dropped its atom bombs on **Hiroshima and Nagasaki**. Scientists led by **Ernest Rutherford** (Manchester, then Cambridge) were the first to 'split the atom' and took part in the **Manhattan Project**.\n- **Alexander Fleming (1881–1955)**: born in Scotland; discovered **penicillin in 1928** while researching influenza; it was developed into a usable drug by **Howard Florey and Ernst Chain** and mass-produced by the 1940s; Fleming won the **Nobel Prize in Medicine in 1945**.", "checkUnderstand": ["What happened during the First World War", "The partition of Ireland and the establishment of the UK as it is today", "The events of the Second World War"]}, {"id": "3.5", "title": "The Middle Ages", "summary": "## War at home and abroad\n- The **Middle Ages (medieval period)** runs from the Norman Conquest until about **1485** — a time of almost constant war.\n- **Wales**: in **1284** King **Edward I** introduced the **Statute of Rhuddlan**, which **annexed Wales to the Crown of England**; huge castles including **Conwy and Caernarvon** were built; by the middle of the 15th century the last Welsh rebellions had been defeated and English laws and language were introduced.\n- **Scotland**: in **1314** the Scottish, led by **Robert the Bruce**, defeated the English at the **Battle of Bannockburn**; Scotland remained unconquered.\n- **Ireland**: initially independent; by **1200** the English ruled an area around Dublin known as **the Pale**.\n- Abroad: many knights took part in the **Crusades** (European Christians fighting for the Holy Land); the **Hundred Years War** with France actually lasted **116 years** — at the **Battle of Agincourt in 1415** King **Henry V's** vastly outnumbered army defeated the French; the English left France in the **1450s**.\n\n## The Black Death\n- The Normans used **feudalism**: the king gave land to lords in return for help in war; most peasants were **serfs**, tied to their lord's land. In the north of Scotland and Ireland land was owned by members of the **'clans'**.\n- In **1348** the **Black Death** (probably a form of plague) came to Britain — **one third of the population of England died**, with similar proportions in Scotland and Wales.\n- Consequences: labour shortages, peasants demanding higher wages, new social classes including the **gentry**, movement to towns and a strong **middle class**. In Ireland, the Pale shrank for a time.\n\n## Legal and political changes\n- In **1215**, **King John** was forced by his noblemen to agree to the **Magna Carta** (Great Charter): even the king was **subject to the law**; it protected the rights of the nobility and restricted the king's power to collect taxes or make/change laws.\n- Parliament developed from the king's council of advisers. Two Houses emerged: the **House of Lords** (nobility, great landowners, bishops) and the **House of Commons** (knights — smaller landowners — and wealthy townspeople, elected by a small part of the population).\n- Scotland developed a Parliament of **three Houses, called Estates**: the lords, the commons and the clergy.\n- Judges began to be independent of government; in England judges developed **'common law'** by precedence and tradition; in Scotland laws were **'codified'** (written down).\n\n## A distinct identity\n- After the Norman Conquest the rulers spoke **Norman French** and the peasants **Anglo-Saxon**; the two combined into one **English language** (e.g. 'park' and 'beauty' from French; 'apple', 'cow', 'summer' from Anglo-Saxon; pairs like 'demand'/'ask').\n- By **1400** official documents were being written in English, which was the preferred language of the royal court and Parliament.\n- **Geoffrey Chaucer** wrote **The Canterbury Tales**, poems about pilgrims travelling to Canterbury — one of the first books printed by **William Caxton**, the first person in England to print books using a printing press.\n- In Scotland, many spoke Gaelic and the **Scots language** developed; the poet **John Barbour** wrote **The Bruce** about the Battle of Bannockburn.\n- **Castles** (e.g. **Windsor and Edinburgh**, still in use) and great **cathedrals** (e.g. **Lincoln Cathedral**) were built; the stained glass of **York Minster** is famous.\n- England was an important trading nation: **wool** was a major export; skilled workers came from abroad (weavers from France, engineers from Germany, glass manufacturers from Italy, canal builders from Holland).\n\n## The Wars of the Roses\n- In **1455** a civil war began over who should be king of England, between the **House of Lancaster** (symbol: **red rose**) and the **House of York** (symbol: **white rose**) — the **Wars of the Roses**.\n- It ended at the **Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485**: **King Richard III** (York) was killed; **Henry Tudor** (Lancaster) became **King Henry VII** and married Richard's niece, **Elizabeth of York**, uniting the two families.\n- Henry VII was the first king of the **House of Tudor**, whose symbol was a **red rose with a white rose inside it**.", "checkUnderstand": ["The wars that took place in the Middle Ages", "How Parliament began to develop", "The way that land ownership worked", "The effect of the Black Death", "The development of English language and culture", "The Wars of the Roses and the founding of the House of Tudor"]}, {"id": "3.6", "title": "The Tudors and Stuarts", "summary": "## Religious conflicts\n- **Henry VII** strengthened central administration, reduced the power of the nobles and built up the monarchy's financial reserves.\n- **Henry VIII** continued centralising power; most famous for **breaking away from the Church of Rome** and **marrying six times**.\n- **The six wives**: **Catherine of Aragon** (Spanish princess; daughter Mary; divorced), **Anne Boleyn** (English; daughter Elizabeth; executed at the Tower of London), **Jane Seymour** (gave Henry his son Edward; died shortly after the birth), **Anne of Cleves** (German princess; married for political reasons, divorced soon after), **Catherine Howard** (Anne Boleyn's cousin; executed), **Catherine Parr** (widow; survived him).\n- When the Pope refused to approve his divorce, Henry established the **Church of England**, in which the king, not the Pope, had power to appoint bishops and order how people should worship.\n- The **Reformation** across Europe: a movement against the Pope's authority and the Roman Catholic Church. **Protestants** read the Bible in their own languages, did not pray to saints or at shrines, and believed a person's own relationship with God was most important.\n- In Ireland, attempts to impose Protestantism led to rebellion by the Irish chieftains and much brutal fighting.\n- Under Henry VIII, Wales became formally united with England by the **Act for the Government of Wales**; the Welsh sent representatives to the House of Commons.\n- **Edward VI**, strongly Protestant: the **Book of Common Prayer** was written for the Church of England; he died aged 15 after ruling just over six years.\n- **Mary** ('Bloody Mary'): devout Catholic who persecuted Protestants; died after a short reign; succeeded by her half-sister **Elizabeth** (daughter of Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn).\n\n## Queen Elizabeth I\n- A Protestant who **re-established the Church of England** as the official Church; balanced the views of Catholics and more extreme Protestants and avoided serious religious conflict.\n- Became one of the most popular monarchs, especially after **1588**, when the English **defeated the Spanish Armada** (sent by Spain to conquer England and restore Catholicism).\n\n## The Reformation in Scotland and Mary, Queen of Scots\n- In **1560** the predominantly Protestant **Scottish Parliament abolished the authority of the Pope** in Scotland; Roman Catholic services became illegal; a Protestant Church of Scotland was established but, unlike in England, it was **not a state Church**.\n- **Mary Stuart ('Mary, Queen of Scots')**: Catholic; became queen when only a week old; spent much of her childhood in France; suspected of involvement when her husband was murdered; fled to England, giving her throne to her Protestant son **James VI of Scotland**; Elizabeth I kept her prisoner for **20 years**; eventually **executed**, accused of plotting against Elizabeth.\n\n## Exploration, poetry and drama\n- The Elizabethan period saw growing patriotism. **Sir Francis Drake**, a commander in the defeat of the Spanish Armada, was a founder of England's naval tradition; his ship, the **Golden Hind**, was one of the first to **circumnavigate the world**.\n- English settlers first began to colonise the eastern coast of America in Elizabeth I's time.\n- **William Shakespeare (1564–1616)**: born in Stratford-upon-Avon; playwright and actor; plays include *A Midsummer Night's Dream*, *Hamlet*, *Macbeth*, *Romeo and Juliet*; one of the first to portray ordinary Englishmen and women; invented many words still common today; famous lines include 'Once more unto the breach' (Henry V), 'To be or not to be' (Hamlet), 'All the world's a stage' (As You Like It). The **Globe Theatre** in London is a modern copy of the theatres where his plays were first performed.\n\n## James VI and I\n- Elizabeth I never married; when she died in **1603** her heir was her cousin **James VI of Scotland**, who became **King James I of England, Wales and Ireland** (Scotland remained a separate country).\n- The **King James Bible ('Authorised Version')**: a new English translation of the Bible produced in his reign, still used in many Protestant churches today.\n\n## Ireland\n- Ireland was almost completely Catholic. Henry VII and Henry VIII extended English control outside the Pale; **Henry VIII took the title 'King of Ireland'**.\n- Under Elizabeth I and James I there were rebellions; the English government encouraged Scottish and English Protestants to settle in **Ulster**, taking land from Catholic landholders — settlements known as **plantations**, with serious long-term consequences.\n\n## The rise of Parliament and the civil war\n- Elizabeth I was skilled at managing Parliament; **James I and Charles I** believed in the **'Divine Right of Kings'** — that the king was directly appointed by God to rule.\n- Charles I ruled for **11 years without Parliament**; trouble in Scotland (his attempt to impose a revised Prayer Book on the Presbyterian Church) forced him to recall Parliament in **1640**. Many MPs were **Puritans** — Protestants advocating strict, simple religious doctrine and worship — and Parliament refused him funds.\n- After a rebellion in Ireland, Parliament demanded control of the English army; Charles I entered the House of Commons and tried to arrest **five parliamentary leaders** — they were not there, and **no monarch has set foot in the Commons since**.\n- **Civil war began in 1642**: the king's supporters (**Cavaliers**) against Parliament's supporters (**Roundheads**).\n\n## Oliver Cromwell and the English Republic\n- The king's army was defeated at the **Battles of Marston Moor and Naseby**; by **1646** Parliament had won. Charles I refused agreement and was **executed in 1649**.\n- England declared itself a **republic, called the Commonwealth**. **Oliver Cromwell** established the authority of the English Parliament in Ireland with such violence that he remains a controversial figure there today.\n- The Scots declared **Charles II** king and he led a Scottish army into England; Cromwell defeated it at the **Battles of Dunbar and Worcester**; Charles II famously hid in an oak tree and fled to Europe.\n- Cromwell became **Lord Protector** and ruled until his death in **1658**; his son **Richard** could not control the army or government. Britain was a republic for **11 years**.\n\n## The Restoration\n- In **May 1660** Parliament invited **Charles II** to return from exile in the Netherlands; he was crowned king of England, Wales, Scotland and Ireland. The Church of England again became the established Church; Roman Catholics and Puritans were kept out of power.\n- **1665**: major outbreak of **plague** in London; **the following year a great fire** destroyed much of the city including St Paul's Cathedral — the new St Paul's was designed by **Sir Christopher Wren**. **Samuel Pepys** recorded these events in his famous diary.\n- The **Habeas Corpus Act, 1679**: 'you must present the person in court' — no one could be held prisoner unlawfully; every prisoner has a right to a court hearing.\n- The **Royal Society**, formed to promote 'natural knowledge', is the **oldest surviving scientific society in the world**; early members included **Sir Edmund Halley** (predicted the return of Halley's Comet) and **Sir Isaac Newton (1643–1727)** — born in Lincolnshire; famous for *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (showing how gravity applied to the whole universe) and for discovering that white light is made up of the colours of the rainbow.\n\n## A Catholic king and the Glorious Revolution\n- Charles II had no legitimate children; he died in **1685** and his Roman Catholic brother became **King James II** (of England, Wales and Ireland) and **James VII of Scotland**. He favoured Catholics, allowed them to be army officers (forbidden by an Act of Parliament) and arrested bishops of the Church of England. When his wife had a son, a Catholic succession seemed likely.\n- In **1688**, important Protestants asked **William of Orange** (Protestant ruler of the Netherlands, married to James II's daughter **Mary**) to invade and proclaim himself king. There was no resistance; James fled to France; William became **William III** (William II of Scotland), ruling jointly with Mary — the **'Glorious Revolution'**, because there was no fighting in England and it guaranteed the power of Parliament, ending the threat of a monarch ruling alone.\n- James II invaded Ireland with French help; William defeated him at the **Battle of the Boyne in 1690** — still celebrated by some in Northern Ireland. Restrictions were placed on the Roman Catholic Church in Ireland.\n- In Scotland, a rebellion for James was defeated at **Killiecrankie**; clans had to swear an oath accepting William — the **MacDonalds of Glencoe** were late in taking the oath and were all killed, a massacre that made some Scots distrust the new government.\n- James's supporters became known as **Jacobites**.", "checkUnderstand": ["How and why religion changed during this period", "The importance of poetry and drama in the Elizabethan period", "About the involvement of Britain in Ireland", "The development of Parliament and the only period in history when England was a republic", "Why there was a restoration of the monarchy", "How the Glorious Revolution happened"]}, {"id": "3.7", "title": "Early Britain", "summary": "## Stone Age, Bronze Age and Iron Age\n- The first people in Britain were **hunter-gatherers** in the **Stone Age**; for much of the Stone Age Britain was connected to the continent by a **land bridge**. Britain became permanently separated by the Channel about **10,000 years ago**.\n- The **first farmers** arrived about **6,000 years ago**; their ancestors probably came from **south-east Europe**. They built **Stonehenge** (Wiltshire), probably a gathering place for seasonal ceremonies; **Skara Brae** on Orkney is the **best preserved prehistoric village in northern Europe**.\n- Around **4,000 years ago** people learned to make bronze — the **Bronze Age**: roundhouses, burial in **round barrows**, skilled metalwork in bronze and gold.\n- The **Iron Age** followed: weapons and tools of iron; roundhouses grouped into settlements and defended **hill forts** (e.g. **Maiden Castle**, Dorset); language part of the **Celtic** family; the **first coins minted in Britain** — the beginning of British history.\n\n## The Romans\n- **Julius Caesar** led an unsuccessful Roman invasion in **55 BC**; Britain stayed outside the Roman Empire for nearly 100 years.\n- In **AD 43** the **Emperor Claudius** led a successful invasion; **Boudicca**, queen of the **Iceni** in eastern England, fought against the Romans — her statue stands on Westminster Bridge in London.\n- Areas of what is now Scotland were never conquered; the **Emperor Hadrian built a wall** to keep out the **Picts** (ancestors of the Scottish people) — forts include **Housesteads and Vindolanda**; Hadrian's Wall is a **UNESCO World Heritage Site**.\n- The Romans remained for **400 years**: roads, public buildings, a structure of law, new plants and animals. The **first Christian communities** appeared in the **3rd and 4th centuries AD**.\n\n## The Anglo-Saxons\n- The Roman army left in **AD 410** and never returned. Britain was invaded by the **Jutes, Angles and Saxons** from northern Europe; their languages are the basis of modern English.\n- By about **AD 600**, **Anglo-Saxon kingdoms** were established, mainly in what is now England. One king was buried with treasure and armour in a ship at **Sutton Hoo** (Suffolk). Much of Wales and Scotland remained free of Anglo-Saxon rule.\n- Christian missionaries: from Ireland, **St Patrick** (patron saint of Ireland) and **St Columba** (founded a monastery on **Iona**) spread Christianity in the north; **St Augustine** led missionaries from Rome to the south and became the **first Archbishop of Canterbury**.\n\n## The Vikings\n- The Vikings came from **Denmark and Norway**, first visiting in **AD 789** to raid coastal towns; later they settled in the east of England and Scotland.\n- The Anglo-Saxon kingdoms united under **King Alfred the Great**, who defeated the Vikings; many Vikings stayed in the **Danelaw** (east and north of England — place names like Grimsby and Scunthorpe come from Viking languages).\n- There was a short period of **Danish kings**, the first being **Cnut (Canute)**.\n- In the north, the Viking threat encouraged people to unite under **Kenneth MacAlpin**; the term **Scotland** began to be used.\n\n## The Norman Conquest\n- In **1066**, **William, Duke of Normandy** defeated **Harold, the Saxon king of England**, at the **Battle of Hastings**; Harold was killed; William became king — **William the Conqueror**. The battle is commemorated in the **Bayeux Tapestry**.\n- The Norman Conquest was the **last successful foreign invasion of England**; **Norman French** influenced the development of English. The Normans initially conquered Wales (the Welsh gradually won territory back) but did not invade Scotland.\n- William had lists drawn up of all towns, villages, people, landowners and animals — the **Domesday Book**, which still exists and shows society just after the Conquest.", "checkUnderstand": ["The history of the UK before the Romans", "The impact of the Romans on British society", "The different groups that invaded after the Romans", "The importance of the Norman invasion in 1066"]}], "flashcards": [{"q": "In what year did the British people elect the Labour government that introduced the welfare state?", "a": "1945", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["dates", "voting"]}, {"q": "Who became Prime Minister after Labour won the 1945 election?", "a": "Clement Attlee", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Whose report outlined the welfare state that Attlee promised to introduce?", "a": "William Beveridge's — the Beveridge Report", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "In what year was the National Health Service (NHS) established?", "a": "1948", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who led the establishment of the NHS in 1948, and what post did he hold?", "a": "Aneurin (Nye) Bevan, the Minister for Health", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did the NHS guarantee?", "a": "A minimum standard of health care for all, free at the point of use", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Which industries and services did the post-war Labour government nationalise?", "a": "The railways, coal mines, and gas, water and electricity supplies", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "In 1947, independence was granted to nine countries. Which three are named in the handbook?", "a": "India, Pakistan and Ceylon (now Sri Lanka)", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "Why did the UK join NATO after the Second World War?", "a": "It was an alliance of nations set up to resist the perceived threat of invasion by the Soviet Union and its allies", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Which party governed Britain from 1951 to 1964?", "a": "The Conservative Party", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Which Prime Minister was famous for his 'wind of change' speech about decolonisation?", "a": "Harold Macmillan", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people", "empire"]}, {"q": "For which years was Clement Attlee Prime Minister?", "a": "1945 to 1951 (he led the Labour Party for 20 years)", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What role did Clement Attlee hold during the Second World War?", "a": "He was Winston Churchill's Deputy Prime Minister in the wartime coalition government", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What was the Beveridge Report and when was it published?", "a": "The 1942 report 'Social Insurance and Allied Services' by William Beveridge (commissioned in 1941), which provided the basis of the modern welfare state", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What were the five 'Giant Evils' identified in the Beveridge Report?", "a": "Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness", "section": "3.2", "page": 11, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did the Education Act 1944 ('The Butler Act') introduce?", "a": "Free secondary education in England and Wales", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["acts", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who oversaw the introduction of the Education Act 1944?", "a": "R A Butler (Richard Austen Butler), a Conservative MP responsible for education from 1941", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people", "acts"]}, {"q": "Who was Dylan Thomas?", "a": "A Welsh poet and writer, known for the radio play Under Milk Wood and the poem Do Not Go Gentle into That Good Night; born in Swansea", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "In what year were people from the West Indies invited to come and work in the UK?", "a": "1948", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "Why did the UK encourage immigration in the 1950s?", "a": "There was still a shortage of labour — immigration was encouraged for economic reasons (e.g. bus driver recruitment centres in the West Indies; agents sent to India and Pakistan by textile and engineering firms)", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "What was the decade of the 1960s known as?", "a": "'The Swinging Sixties' — a period of significant social change with growth in British fashion, cinema and popular music", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Name two well-known British pop music groups of the 1960s.", "a": "The Beatles and The Rolling Stones", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What new rights did Parliament give women in the 1960s?", "a": "The right to equal pay, and it became illegal for employers to discriminate against women because of their gender", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["voting", "acts"]}, {"q": "How many people of Indian origin forced to leave Uganda did Britain admit in the early 1970s?", "a": "28,000", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "Who developed the television, and when was the first broadcast between London and Glasgow?", "a": "Scotsman John Logie Baird developed it in the 1920s; the first London–Glasgow broadcast was in 1932", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who developed radar, and when did the first successful radar test take place?", "a": "Scotsman Sir Robert Watson-Watt; the first successful test was in 1935", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What is Sir Bernard Lovell known for?", "a": "He built the radio telescope at Jodrell Bank in Cheshire, for many years the biggest in the world", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is a Turing machine and who invented it?", "a": "A theoretical mathematical device invented by British mathematician Alan Turing in the 1930s, influential in the development of computer science", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is Scottish physician John MacLeod known for?", "a": "He was the co-discoverer of insulin, used to treat diabetes", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "In what year was the structure of the DNA molecule discovered?", "a": "1953, through work at British universities in London and Cambridge", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Which British scientist was awarded the Nobel Prize for the discovery of the structure of DNA?", "a": "Francis Crick", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who developed the jet engine?", "a": "Sir Frank Whittle, a British Royal Air Force engineer officer, in the 1930s", "section": "3.2", "page": 12, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who invented the hovercraft?", "a": "Sir Christopher Cockerell, a British inventor, in the 1950s", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What was the Harrier jump jet?", "a": "An aircraft capable of taking off vertically, designed and developed in the UK", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did Concorde achieve and what were its key dates?", "a": "The world's only supersonic passenger aircraft, developed by Britain and France; first flew in 1969, began carrying passengers in 1976, retired from service in 2003", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who invented the cash-dispensing ATM ('cashpoint')?", "a": "James Goodfellow, in the 1960s; the first was put into use by Barclays Bank in Enfield, north London in 1967", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who pioneered IVF therapy in Britain?", "a": "Physiologist Sir Robert Edwards and gynaecologist Patrick Steptoe; the world's first 'test-tube baby' was born in Oldham, Lancashire in 1978", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Which two British scientists led the team that first cloned a mammal (Dolly the sheep), and when?", "a": "Sir Ian Wilmot and Keith Campbell, in 1996", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What is Sir Peter Mansfield known for?", "a": "He is the co-inventor of the MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) scanner", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who invented the World Wide Web, and when was information first successfully transferred via the web?", "a": "Sir Tim Berners-Lee (British); information was first transferred via the web on 25 December 1990", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened to the Northern Ireland Parliament in 1972?", "a": "It was suspended and Northern Ireland was directly ruled by the UK government", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "About how many people lost their lives in the violence in Northern Ireland in the decades after 1969?", "a": "Some 3,000 people", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What did Mary Peters achieve in 1972?", "a": "She won an Olympic gold medal in the pentathlon; she was later made a Dame of the British Empire in 2000", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Which countries formed the European Economic Community (EEC) in 1957?", "a": "West Germany, France, Belgium, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "In what year did the UK join the EEC?", "a": "1973", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Does the UK use the Euro currency?", "a": "No — the UK is a full member of the European Union but does not use the Euro", "section": "3.2", "page": 13, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who was the first woman Prime Minister of the UK, and when did she take office?", "a": "Margaret Thatcher, following the Conservative victory in the 1979 General Election", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "For how long was Margaret Thatcher Prime Minister?", "a": "From 1979 to 1990 — the longest-serving Prime Minister of the 20th century", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened when Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands in 1982?", "a": "A naval taskforce was sent from the UK and military action led to the recovery of the islands", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who was Prime Minister after Margaret Thatcher, and what is he noted for?", "a": "John Major, who helped establish the Northern Ireland peace process", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Roald Dahl?", "a": "A children's author born in Wales to Norwegian parents; served in the RAF in WWII; wrote Charlie and the Chocolate Factory and George's Marvellous Medicine", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Which party won the 1997 election, and who led it?", "a": "The Labour Party, led by Tony Blair", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What devolved bodies did the Blair government introduce?", "a": "A Scottish Parliament (with substantial powers to legislate) and a Welsh Assembly (fewer legislative powers but considerable control over public services)", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "When was the Good Friday Agreement signed?", "a": "1998", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What happened to the Northern Ireland Assembly after it was elected in 1999?", "a": "It was suspended in 2002 and not reinstated until 2007", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who took over as Prime Minister in 2007?", "a": "Gordon Brown", "section": "3.2", "page": 14, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "In the 1990s, Britain played a leading role in which coalition action following the Iraqi invasion of 1990?", "a": "The liberation of Kuwait", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "When did British combat troops leave Iraq?", "a": "2009", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "As part of which coalition does the UK operate in Afghanistan?", "a": "The United Nations (UN) mandated 50-nation International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) coalition", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was unusual about the May 2010 General Election?", "a": "No political party won an overall majority — the first time in the UK since February 1974", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["dates", "voting"]}, {"q": "Which parties formed the coalition government in 2010, and who became Prime Minister?", "a": "The Conservative and Liberal Democrat parties; Conservative leader David Cameron became Prime Minister", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Name the Prime Ministers of the 2015–2024 Conservative Government.", "a": "David Cameron, Theresa May, Boris Johnson, Liz Truss and Rishi Sunak", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "In what year was the EU membership referendum (Brexit) held?", "a": "2016", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did Rishi Sunak call a general election?", "a": "For July 4, 2024", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who leads the Labour government formed after the 2024 general election?", "a": "Keir Starmer", "section": "3.2", "page": 15, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What was read at the coronation of William and Mary?", "a": "A Declaration of Rights — confirming the king could no longer raise taxes or administer justice without agreement from Parliament", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["monarchy", "acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Bill of Rights, 1689 confirm?", "a": "The rights of Parliament and the limits of the king's power; Parliament took control of who could be monarch and declared that the king or queen must be a Protestant", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["acts", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Under the Bill of Rights, how often did a new Parliament have to be elected?", "a": "At least every three years (later this became seven years and now it is five years)", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["acts", "voting"]}, {"q": "What did the monarch have to ask Parliament to renew every year after 1689?", "a": "Funding for the army and the navy", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What were the two main groups in Parliament at the beginning of party politics?", "a": "The Whigs and the Tories (the modern Conservative Party is still sometimes referred to as the Tories)", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "From what year were newspapers allowed to operate without a government licence?", "a": "1695", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What were 'pocket boroughs' and 'rotten boroughs'?", "a": "Pocket boroughs were constituencies controlled by a single wealthy family; rotten boroughs were constituencies with hardly any voters", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "When did the first Jews since the Middle Ages settle in Britain?", "a": "In 1656, in London", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "Who were the Huguenots?", "a": "Protestant refugees from France, persecuted for their religion, who came to Britain between 1680 and 1720; many were educated and skilled", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["religion", "dates"]}, {"q": "What did the Act of Union of 1707 create?", "a": "The Kingdom of Great Britain (the Act is known as the Treaty of Union in Scotland)", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["acts", "dates"]}, {"q": "What did Scotland keep after the Act of Union 1707?", "a": "Its own legal and education systems and Presbyterian Church", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["acts", "religion"]}, {"q": "Why was George I chosen as king when Queen Anne died in 1714?", "a": "Parliament chose him because he was Anne's nearest Protestant relative (he was German)", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "Who was the first man to be called Prime Minister, and when?", "a": "Sir Robert Walpole, Prime Minister from 1721 to 1742", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who was Bonnie Prince Charlie?", "a": "Charles Edward Stuart, grandson of James II, who landed in Scotland in 1745 to try to put a Stuart king back on the throne, supported by Highland clansmen", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["people", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "When and where was Bonnie Prince Charlie defeated?", "a": "At the Battle of Culloden in 1746, by George II's army; Charles escaped back to Europe", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What were the 'Highland Clearances'?", "a": "After Culloden, many Scottish landlords destroyed small farms ('crofts') to make space for large flocks of sheep and cattle; evictions became very common in the early 19th century and many Scots left for North America", "section": "3.3", "page": 16, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who was Robert Burns?", "a": "A Scottish poet (1759–96), known in Scotland as 'The Bard'; his best-known work is Auld Lang Syne, sung at New Year (Hogmanay)", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What was 'the Enlightenment'?", "a": "The development of new ideas about politics, philosophy and science during the 18th century; many of its great thinkers were Scottish", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What is Adam Smith known for?", "a": "He developed ideas about economics which are still referred to today", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is David Hume known for?", "a": "His ideas about human nature, which continue to influence philosophers", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is James Watt known for?", "a": "His work on steam power, which helped the progress of the Industrial Revolution", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What was one of the most important principles of the Enlightenment?", "a": "That everyone should have the right to their own political and religious beliefs and that the state should not try to dictate to them", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What was the Industrial Revolution?", "a": "The rapid development of industry in Britain in the 18th and 19th centuries; Britain was the first country to industrialise on a large scale, because of the development of machinery and the use of steam power", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What was the biggest source of employment in Britain before the 18th century?", "a": "Agriculture (with many cottage industries producing goods such as cloth and lace)", "section": "3.3", "page": 17, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What did the Bessemer process allow?", "a": "The mass production of steel, which led to the development of the shipbuilding industry and the railways", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who was Richard Arkwright?", "a": "An 18th-century industrialist (originally a barber and wig-maker) who improved the carding machine, developed horse-driven spinning mills and later used steam engines; remembered for running his factories efficiently and profitably", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Why were canals built during the Industrial Revolution?", "a": "To link the factories to towns and cities and to the ports, particularly in the new industrial areas in the middle and north of England", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "What were working conditions like during the Industrial Revolution?", "a": "Very poor — no laws protected employees, who were often forced to work long hours in dangerous situations; children worked and were sometimes treated even more harshly than adults", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who mapped the coast of Australia?", "a": "Captain James Cook — a few colonies were established there", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["people", "empire"]}, {"q": "Which company, originally set up to trade, gained control of large parts of India?", "a": "The East India Company", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who was Sake Dean Mahomet?", "a": "A man from the Bengal region of India who opened the Hindoostane Coffee House in George Street, London in 1810 — the first curry house in Britain — and, with his wife, introduced 'shampooing' (Indian head massage) to Britain", "section": "3.3", "page": 18, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "Where did slaves in the British slave trade primarily come from, and where were they taken?", "a": "Primarily from West Africa; they were taken on British ships to America and the Caribbean to work on tobacco and sugar plantations", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who set up the first formal anti-slavery groups?", "a": "The Quakers, in the late 1700s; they petitioned Parliament to ban the practice", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["religion", "empire"]}, {"q": "Who was William Wilberforce?", "a": "An evangelical Christian and member of Parliament who, with other abolitionists, played an important part in turning public opinion against the slave trade and changing the law", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["people", "empire"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1807 regarding the slave trade?", "a": "It became illegal to trade slaves in British ships or from British ports", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "What did the Emancipation Act of 1833 do?", "a": "It abolished slavery throughout the British Empire", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["acts", "dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "Who replaced the freed slaves as workers after 1833?", "a": "2 million Indian and Chinese workers — on sugar plantations in the Caribbean, in mines in South Africa, on railways in East Africa and in the army in Kenya", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "What slogan did the American colonists use against British taxation?", "a": "'No taxation without representation'", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["empire", "voting"]}, {"q": "In what year did 13 American colonies declare their independence?", "a": "1776 — stating that people had a right to establish their own governments", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "When did Britain recognise the American colonies' independence?", "a": "1783", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "What happened in France in 1789?", "a": "There was a revolution, and the new French government soon declared war on Britain", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "When was the Battle of Trafalgar, and who commanded the British fleet?", "a": "1805; Admiral Nelson, who was killed in the battle. Britain's navy defeated the combined French and Spanish fleets", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "people"]}, {"q": "Where can Admiral Nelson's ship HMS Victory be visited?", "a": "Portsmouth (Nelson's Column in Trafalgar Square, London, is a monument to him)", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "When and where was Napoleon finally defeated?", "a": "In 1815 at the Battle of Waterloo, by the Duke of Wellington — this ended the French Wars", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who was known as the Iron Duke?", "a": "The Duke of Wellington, who defeated Napoleon at Waterloo and later became Prime Minister", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did the Act of Union of 1800 do?", "a": "It unified Ireland with England, Scotland and Wales in 1801, creating the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["acts", "dates"]}, {"q": "What three crosses make up the Union Flag (Union Jack)?", "a": "The cross of St George (England, red cross on white ground); the cross of St Andrew (Scotland, diagonal white cross on blue ground); the cross of St Patrick (Ireland, diagonal red cross on white ground)", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Why does the Welsh dragon not appear on the Union Flag?", "a": "Because when the first Union Flag was created in 1606 from the flags of Scotland and England, the Principality of Wales was already united with England", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "In what year did Queen Victoria become queen, and at what age?", "a": "1837, at the age of 18", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "How long did Queen Victoria reign?", "a": "Until 1901 — almost 64 years, the longest reign of any British monarch at the handbook's date of writing (2013)", "section": "3.3", "page": 19, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "How large did the British Empire become during the Victorian period?", "a": "It grew to cover all of India, Australia and large parts of Africa — the largest empire the world has ever seen, with an estimated population of more than 400 million people", "section": "3.3", "page": 20, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "How many British citizens left the country between 1853 and 1913?", "a": "As many as 13 million", "section": "3.3", "page": 20, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "How many Russian and Polish Jews came to Britain between 1870 and 1914?", "a": "Around 120,000, to escape persecution; many settled in London's East End and in Manchester and Leeds", "section": "3.3", "page": 20, "tags": ["dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "When were the Corn Laws repealed, and what had they done?", "a": "In 1846; they had prevented the import of cheap grain. Repeal was part of the government's free trade policies", "section": "3.3", "page": 20, "tags": ["acts", "dates"]}, {"q": "What limit on working hours was introduced in 1847?", "a": "The number of hours that women and children could work was limited by law to 10 hours per day", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["dates", "acts"]}, {"q": "Who pioneered the railway engine?", "a": "The father and son George and Robert Stephenson, just before Victoria came to the throne", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Isambard Kingdom Brunel?", "a": "An engineer from Portsmouth who built tunnels, bridges, railway lines and ships; he constructed the Great Western Railway, the first major railway built in Britain (London Paddington to the south west of England, the West Midlands and Wales)", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What share of the world's iron, coal and cotton cloth did the UK produce in the 19th century?", "a": "More than half", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "What was the Great Exhibition, and when and where did it open?", "a": "An exhibition of goods from all over the world (most objects made in Britain); it opened in 1851 in Hyde Park in the Crystal Palace, a huge building of steel and glass", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who fought in the Crimean War, and when?", "a": "From 1853 to 1856, Britain fought with Turkey and France against Russia", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What was notable about media coverage of the Crimean War?", "a": "It was the first war to be extensively covered by the media through news stories and photographs", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Which medal did Queen Victoria introduce during the Crimean War?", "a": "The Victoria Cross, which honours acts of valour by soldiers", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["monarchy", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who was Florence Nightingale?", "a": "Born in Italy to English parents; she treated soldiers in military hospitals in Turkey during the Crimean War (from 1854), founded the Nightingale Training School for nurses at St Thomas' Hospital, London in 1860, and is often regarded as the founder of modern nursing", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened when the Irish potato crop failed in the middle of the 19th century?", "a": "Ireland suffered a famine: a million people died from disease and starvation and another million and a half left Ireland (some to the United States, others to England)", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Which cities had large Irish populations by 1861?", "a": "Liverpool, London, Manchester and Glasgow", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What did the Fenians want for Ireland?", "a": "Complete independence", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did Charles Stuart Parnell advocate?", "a": "'Home Rule' — Ireland would remain in the UK but have its own parliament", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did the Reform Act of 1832 do?", "a": "It greatly increased the number of people with the right to vote, abolished the old pocket and rotten boroughs, and gave more parliamentary seats to the towns and cities", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["acts", "voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who were the Chartists?", "a": "Campaigners who presented petitions to Parliament demanding the vote for the working classes and other people without property", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "What did the Reform Act of 1867 do?", "a": "It created many more urban seats in Parliament and reduced the amount of property people needed to have before they could vote — though most men still could not vote, and no women", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["acts", "voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "What is universal suffrage?", "a": "The right of every adult, male or female, to vote", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "What happened to a married woman's earnings and property before 1870?", "a": "They automatically belonged to her husband when she got married", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "What did the Acts of Parliament in 1870 and 1882 give wives?", "a": "The right to keep their own earnings and property", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["acts", "voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who were the 'suffragettes'?", "a": "Women who campaigned and demonstrated for greater rights — in particular the right to vote — forming the women's suffrage movement", "section": "3.3", "page": 21, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "What did Emmeline Pankhurst set up in 1889?", "a": "The Women's Franchise League, which fought to get the vote in local elections for married women", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["people", "voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "What organisation did Emmeline Pankhurst help found in 1903?", "a": "The Women's Social and Political Union (WSPU) — the first group whose members were called 'suffragettes'; they used civil disobedience, chained themselves to railings, smashed windows, committed arson and went on hunger strike", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["people", "voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "What voting rights did women gain in 1918?", "a": "Women over the age of 30 were given voting rights and the right to stand for Parliament, partly in recognition of women's contribution to the war effort in the First World War", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "When were women given the right to vote at 21, the same as men?", "a": "In 1928, shortly before Emmeline Pankhurst's death", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["voting", "dates"]}, {"q": "Until when did the British Empire continue to grow?", "a": "Until the 1920s, although its future direction was already being discussed in the late 19th century", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["empire", "dates"]}, {"q": "When was the Boer War, and who did Britain fight?", "a": "1899 to 1902; the British went to war in South Africa with settlers from the Netherlands called the Boers", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "What eventually happened to the Empire in the second half of the 20th century?", "a": "For the most part there was an orderly transition from Empire to Commonwealth, with countries being granted their independence", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who was Rudyard Kipling?", "a": "A writer born in India in 1865 whose poems and novels reflected the idea that the British Empire was a force for good; works include the Just So Stories, The Jungle Book and the poem If", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["people", "empire"]}, {"q": "In what year was Rudyard Kipling awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature?", "a": "1907", "section": "3.3", "page": 22, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What social measures were introduced in the early 20th century?", "a": "Financial help for the unemployed, old-age pensions, free school meals, laws to improve workplace safety, tighter town planning rules against slums, better support for mothers and children after divorce or separation, and a salary for MPs for the first time", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "What event on 28 June 1914 set off the chain of events leading to the First World War?", "a": "The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "What were the years of the First World War?", "a": "1914 to 1918", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "Which powers did the Allies fight against in the First World War?", "a": "The Central Powers — mainly Germany, the Austro-Hungarian Empire, the Ottoman Empire and later Bulgaria", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "How many Indians fought on behalf of Britain in the First World War?", "a": "More than a million, and around 40,000 were killed", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["battles", "empire"]}, {"q": "How many British casualties were there in the First World War?", "a": "More than 2 million", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened on the first day of the British attack on the Somme in July 1916?", "a": "About 60,000 British casualties on the first day alone", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "When exactly did the First World War end?", "a": "At 11.00 am on 11 November 1918, with victory for Britain and its allies", "section": "3.4", "page": 23, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "What did the British government promise Ireland in 1913?", "a": "'Home Rule' — a self-governing Ireland with its own parliament but still part of the UK; it was opposed by the Protestants in the north of Ireland", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "What was the Easter Rising?", "a": "An uprising against the British in Dublin in 1916 by Irish Nationalists; the leaders were executed under military law, and a guerrilla war followed", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened to Ireland in 1921 and 1922?", "a": "A peace treaty was signed in 1921, and in 1922 Ireland became two countries: the six mainly Protestant counties in the north remained part of the UK as Northern Ireland; the rest became the Irish Free State", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did the Irish Free State become a republic?", "a": "1949", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What is 'the Troubles'?", "a": "The conflict between those wishing for full Irish independence and those wishing to remain loyal to the British government", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "When did the world enter the 'Great Depression'?", "a": "1929 — some parts of the UK suffered mass unemployment", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "How did car ownership change between 1930 and 1939?", "a": "It doubled from 1 million to 2 million", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Which writers and economist were prominent in the 1930s?", "a": "Writers Graham Greene and Evelyn Waugh; the economist John Maynard Keynes published influential new theories of economics", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "When did the BBC start radio broadcasts and the world's first regular television service?", "a": "Radio broadcasts in 1922; the world's first regular television service in 1936", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did Adolf Hitler come to power in Germany?", "a": "1933", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates", "people"]}, {"q": "Why did Britain and France declare war on Germany in 1939?", "a": "Because Hitler invaded Poland — they declared war to stop his aggression", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who were the Axis powers in the Second World War?", "a": "Fascist Germany and Italy and the Empire of Japan", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Which were the main countries on the allied side at the start of the Second World War?", "a": "The UK, France, Poland, Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the Union of South Africa", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who became Prime Minister and Britain's war leader in 1940?", "a": "Winston Churchill, as German forces defeated allied troops and advanced through France", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened at Dunkirk?", "a": "As France fell, the Navy — helped by many civilian volunteers in small pleasure and fishing boats — rescued more than 300,000 British and French soldiers from the beaches; it gave rise to the phrase 'the Dunkirk spirit'", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Battle of Britain, and when was it won?", "a": "The crucial aerial battle in which the British resisted the German air campaign; the British won it in the summer of 1940", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "Which were the most important RAF planes in the Battle of Britain?", "a": "The Spitfire and the Hurricane, which were designed and built in Britain", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Blitz?", "a": "German night-time bombing of London and other British cities; Coventry was almost totally destroyed and great damage was done to the East End of London. 'The Blitz spirit' describes Britons pulling together in adversity", "section": "3.4", "page": 24, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Summarise Winston Churchill's career.", "a": "Son of a politician; soldier and journalist before becoming a Conservative MP in 1900; Prime Minister from May 1940; refused to surrender to the Nazis; lost the 1945 General Election but returned as PM in 1951; MP until 1964; died 1965 and was given a state funeral", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What honour did the public give Winston Churchill in 2002?", "a": "He was voted the greatest Briton of all time", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "In which 1940 speech did Churchill say 'I have nothing to offer but blood, toil, tears and sweat'?", "a": "His first speech to the House of Commons after he became Prime Minister", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "When did Churchill say 'Never in the field of human conflict was so much owed by so many to so few'?", "a": "In a speech to the House of Commons during the Battle of Britain, 1940", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "When and why did the United States enter the Second World War?", "a": "In December 1941, when the Japanese bombed its naval base at Pearl Harbour", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "What was the largest invasion in history?", "a": "Hitler's attack on the Soviet Union in 1941; German forces were ultimately repelled by the Soviets, a pivotal point in the war", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened on 6 June 1944?", "a": "Allied forces landed in Normandy — the event often referred to as 'D-Day'", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "When did the Allies comprehensively defeat Germany?", "a": "May 1945", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "How did the war against Japan end?", "a": "In August 1945, when the United States dropped its newly developed atom bombs on the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who led the scientists who were first to 'split the atom'?", "a": "Ernest Rutherford, working at Manchester and then Cambridge University; they took part in the Manhattan Project in the US, which developed the atomic bomb", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who discovered penicillin, and when?", "a": "Alexander Fleming, in 1928, while researching influenza; it was developed into a usable drug by Howard Florey and Ernst Chain and was in mass production by the 1940s", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What prize did Alexander Fleming win in 1945?", "a": "The Nobel Prize in Medicine", "section": "3.4", "page": 25, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "What period is called the Middle Ages (or the medieval period)?", "a": "The period after the Norman Conquest up until about 1485 — a time of almost constant war", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What was the Statute of Rhuddlan?", "a": "Introduced in 1284 by King Edward I of England, it annexed Wales to the Crown of England", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["acts", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Which huge castles were built to maintain English power in Wales?", "a": "Conwy and Caernarvon", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "By when had the last Welsh rebellions been defeated?", "a": "By the middle of the 15th century; English laws and the English language were introduced", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of Bannockburn in 1314?", "a": "The Scottish, led by Robert the Bruce, defeated the English — Scotland remained unconquered by the English", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "people"]}, {"q": "What was the Pale?", "a": "An area of Ireland around Dublin ruled by the English by 1200", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["dates", "empire"]}, {"q": "What were the Crusades?", "a": "Wars in which European Christians fought for control of the Holy Land; many English knights took part", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["battles", "religion"]}, {"q": "How long did the Hundred Years War actually last?", "a": "116 years — it was a long war between English kings and France", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of Agincourt in 1415?", "a": "King Henry V's vastly outnumbered English army defeated the French — one of the most famous battles of the Hundred Years War", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "people"]}, {"q": "When did the English leave France?", "a": "In the 1450s", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What was feudalism?", "a": "The Norman system of land ownership: the king gave land to his lords in return for help in war, and landowners had to send men to serve in the army; most peasants were serfs who worked their lord's land and could not move away", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who owned land in the north of Scotland and Ireland during the Middle Ages?", "a": "Members of the 'clans' (prominent families)", "section": "3.5", "page": 27, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "What was the Black Death, and when did it come to Britain?", "a": "A disease, probably a form of plague, that came to Britain in 1348; one third of the population of England died, and a similar proportion in Scotland and Wales", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What were the social effects of the Black Death?", "a": "Labour shortages meant peasants demanded higher wages; new social classes appeared, including the gentry (owners of large areas of land); people moved to towns, where growing wealth led to a strong middle class", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What was the Magna Carta, and when was it agreed?", "a": "A charter of rights that King John was forced by his noblemen to agree to in 1215; it established the idea that even the king was subject to the law, protected the rights of the nobility, and restricted the king's power to collect taxes or to make or change laws", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["acts", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who sat in the House of Lords in the Middle Ages?", "a": "The nobility, great landowners and bishops", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["monarchy", "voting"]}, {"q": "Who was elected to the House of Commons in the Middle Ages?", "a": "Knights (usually smaller landowners) and wealthy people from towns and cities — only a small part of the population could join in electing them", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "What were the three Houses (Estates) of the medieval Scottish Parliament?", "a": "The lords, the commons and the clergy", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["voting"]}, {"q": "How did the legal systems of England and Scotland develop differently in the Middle Ages?", "a": "In England judges developed 'common law' by precedence (following previous decisions) and tradition; in Scotland laws were 'codified' (written down)", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "How did the English language form after the Norman Conquest?", "a": "The Norman French of the king and noblemen and the Anglo-Saxon of the peasants gradually combined into one English language — e.g. 'park' and 'beauty' from Norman French; 'apple', 'cow' and 'summer' from Anglo-Saxon", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "By what year were official documents in England being written in English?", "a": "By 1400 — English had become the preferred language of the royal court and Parliament", "section": "3.5", "page": 28, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who wrote The Canterbury Tales?", "a": "Geoffrey Chaucer — a series of poems in English about a group of people going to Canterbury on a pilgrimage, telling each other stories on the journey", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was the first person in England to print books using a printing press?", "a": "William Caxton; The Canterbury Tales was one of the first books he printed", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who wrote The Bruce, and what was it about?", "a": "John Barbour, writing in the Scots language, about the Battle of Bannockburn", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "Which medieval castles are still in use today?", "a": "Windsor and Edinburgh (many others are in ruins)", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What is York Minster famous for?", "a": "Its stained glass windows, telling stories about the Bible and Christian saints", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What was England's very important export in the Middle Ages?", "a": "English wool", "section": "3.5", "page": 29, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "When did the Wars of the Roses begin, and who fought in them?", "a": "In 1455, a civil war began between the House of Lancaster and the House of York to decide who should be king of England", "section": "3.5", "page": 30, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Why was the civil war of 1455–1485 called the Wars of the Roses?", "a": "Because the symbol of Lancaster was a red rose and the symbol of York was a white rose", "section": "3.5", "page": 30, "tags": ["battles", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485?", "a": "King Richard III of the House of York was killed; Henry Tudor, leader of the House of Lancaster, became King Henry VII — ending the Wars of the Roses", "section": "3.5", "page": 30, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "How did Henry VII unite the Houses of York and Lancaster?", "a": "He married King Richard's niece, Elizabeth of York; the Tudor symbol was a red rose with a white rose inside it as a sign the Houses were now allies", "section": "3.5", "page": 30, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "What is Henry VIII most famous for?", "a": "Breaking away from the Church of Rome and marrying six times", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "religion"]}, {"q": "How did Henry VII secure his position after the Wars of the Roses?", "a": "He deliberately strengthened the central administration of England, reduced the power of the nobles, was thrifty and built up the monarchy's financial reserves", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who was Catherine of Aragon?", "a": "Henry VIII's first wife, a Spanish princess; only one of her children, Mary, survived. Henry divorced her when she was too old to give him another child, hoping for a son", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Who was Anne Boleyn and what happened to her?", "a": "Henry VIII's second wife (English); she and Henry had one daughter, Elizabeth. She was unpopular, accused of taking lovers, and executed at the Tower of London", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Which wife gave Henry VIII the son he wanted?", "a": "Jane Seymour — she gave him Edward but died shortly after the birth", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Who was Anne of Cleves?", "a": "Henry VIII's fourth wife, a German princess; he married her for political reasons but divorced her soon after", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "What happened to Catherine Howard?", "a": "Henry VIII's fifth wife, a cousin of Anne Boleyn — she was accused of taking lovers and executed", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Which of Henry VIII's wives survived him?", "a": "Catherine Parr, a widow who married him late in his life; she married again after his death but died soon after", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Why did Henry VIII establish the Church of England?", "a": "The Pope refused to approve his divorce from his first wife; in the new Church the king, not the Pope, had the power to appoint bishops and order how people should worship", "section": "3.6", "page": 32, "tags": ["religion", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "What was the Reformation?", "a": "A movement across Europe against the authority of the Pope and the ideas and practices of the Roman Catholic Church; Protestants formed their own churches", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What did Protestants believe and practise?", "a": "They read the Bible in their own languages instead of Latin, did not pray to saints or at shrines, and believed a person's own relationship with God was more important than submitting to the authority of the Church", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What happened when the English tried to impose Protestantism in Ireland?", "a": "It led to rebellion from the Irish chieftains and much brutal fighting", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["religion", "battles"]}, {"q": "Which Act formally united Wales with England?", "a": "The Act for the Government of Wales, during the reign of Henry VIII; the Welsh sent representatives to the House of Commons and the Welsh legal system was reformed", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["acts", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who was Edward VI?", "a": "Henry VIII's son and successor, strongly Protestant; during his reign the Book of Common Prayer was written for the Church of England. He died at 15 after ruling just over six years", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["monarchy", "religion"]}, {"q": "Why was Queen Mary known as 'Bloody Mary'?", "a": "She was a devout Catholic and persecuted Protestants; she died after a short reign", "section": "3.6", "page": 33, "tags": ["monarchy", "religion"]}, {"q": "How did Elizabeth I handle religion in England?", "a": "A Protestant, she re-established the Church of England as the official Church; everyone had to attend their local church but she did not ask about people's real beliefs — balancing Catholics and extreme Protestants and avoiding serious religious conflict", "section": "3.6", "page": 34, "tags": ["monarchy", "religion"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1588?", "a": "The English defeated the Spanish Armada, a large fleet of ships sent by Spain to conquer England and restore Catholicism", "section": "3.6", "page": 34, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "What did the Scottish Parliament do in 1560?", "a": "The predominantly Protestant Parliament abolished the authority of the Pope in Scotland and Roman Catholic religious services became illegal; a Protestant Church of Scotland was established but, unlike in England, it was not a state Church", "section": "3.6", "page": 34, "tags": ["religion", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who was Mary, Queen of Scots?", "a": "Mary Stuart, the Catholic queen of Scotland — queen when only a week old; spent much of her childhood in France; suspected of involvement in her husband's murder; fled to England, giving her throne to her Protestant son James VI", "section": "3.6", "page": 35, "tags": ["monarchy", "people", "religion"]}, {"q": "What did Elizabeth I do with Mary, Queen of Scots?", "a": "Suspecting Mary wanted to take over the English throne, Elizabeth kept her a prisoner for 20 years; Mary was eventually executed, accused of plotting against Elizabeth I", "section": "3.6", "page": 35, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Who was Sir Francis Drake?", "a": "One of the commanders in the defeat of the Spanish Armada and a founder of England's naval tradition; his ship, the Golden Hind, was one of the first to sail right around ('circumnavigate') the world", "section": "3.6", "page": 35, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "When did English settlers first begin to colonise the eastern coast of America?", "a": "In Elizabeth I's time; colonisation greatly increased in the next century, particularly by people who disagreed with the religious views of the next two kings", "section": "3.6", "page": 35, "tags": ["empire"]}, {"q": "Who was William Shakespeare?", "a": "A playwright and actor (1564–1616) born in Stratford-upon-Avon; famous plays include A Midsummer Night's Dream, Hamlet, Macbeth and Romeo and Juliet; one of the first to portray ordinary Englishmen and women; he invented many words still common today", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "From which Shakespeare plays do the lines 'To be or not to be' and 'All the world's a stage' come?", "a": "'To be or not to be' — Hamlet; 'All the world's a stage' — As You Like It", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is the Globe Theatre in London?", "a": "A modern copy of the theatres in which Shakespeare's plays were first performed", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who inherited the English throne when Elizabeth I died in 1603?", "a": "Her cousin James VI of Scotland, who became King James I of England, Wales and Ireland — though Scotland remained a separate country", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "What was the King James Version?", "a": "A new translation of the Bible into English produced during King James' reign, also known as the 'Authorised Version'; not the first English Bible, but still used in many Protestant churches today", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["religion", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "Which king took the title 'King of Ireland'?", "a": "Henry VIII; he and Henry VII had extended English control outside the Pale and established English authority over the whole country", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["monarchy", "empire"]}, {"q": "What were the plantations in Ireland?", "a": "Settlements where the English government encouraged Scottish and English Protestants to settle in Ulster (the northern province of Ireland), taking over land from Catholic landholders; James later organised similar plantations elsewhere in Ireland — with serious long-term consequences", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["religion", "empire"]}, {"q": "What was the 'Divine Right of Kings'?", "a": "The idea that the king was directly appointed by God to rule and should be able to act without seeking Parliament's approval — believed by James I and his son Charles I", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "For how long did Charles I rule without Parliament, and why did he recall it?", "a": "For 11 years he raised money without Parliament's approval; trouble in Scotland (unrest after he tried to impose a revised Prayer Book on the Presbyterian Church) forced him to recall Parliament in 1640 to ask for funds", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "Who were the Puritans?", "a": "A group of Protestants who advocated strict and simple religious doctrine and worship; many members of Parliament were Puritans who disagreed with the king's religious views", "section": "3.6", "page": 36, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What happened when Charles I entered the House of Commons?", "a": "He tried to arrest five parliamentary leaders, but they had been warned and were not there — no monarch has set foot in the Commons since", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "When did the English civil war begin, and what were the two sides called?", "a": "In 1642; those who supported the king were the Cavaliers and those who supported Parliament were the Roundheads", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "At which battles was the king's army defeated in the civil war?", "a": "The Battles of Marston Moor and Naseby; by 1646 it was clear that Parliament had won the war", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened to Charles I in 1649?", "a": "Still unwilling to reach agreement with Parliament, he was executed", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "What was the Commonwealth?", "a": "The republic that England declared itself after the execution of Charles I — it no longer had a monarch", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Why does Oliver Cromwell remain a controversial figure in Ireland?", "a": "He was sent to Ireland to establish the authority of the English Parliament and did so with great violence", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "At which battles did Cromwell defeat Charles II's Scottish army?", "a": "The Battles of Dunbar and Worcester; Charles II escaped from Worcester, famously hiding in an oak tree, and fled to Europe", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["battles", "people"]}, {"q": "What title was Oliver Cromwell given, and until when did he rule?", "a": "Lord Protector; he ruled until his death in 1658, when his son Richard became Lord Protector but could not control the army or the government", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["people", "dates"]}, {"q": "For how long was Britain a republic?", "a": "11 years — after Oliver Cromwell died there was no clear leader or system of government and people began to talk about the need for a king", "section": "3.6", "page": 37, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What happened in May 1660?", "a": "Parliament invited Charles II to come back from exile in the Netherlands; he was crowned King Charles II of England, Wales, Scotland and Ireland (the Restoration)", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened in London in 1665 and 1666?", "a": "In 1665 there was a major outbreak of plague; the following year a great fire destroyed much of the city, including many churches and St Paul's Cathedral", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who designed the new St Paul's Cathedral?", "a": "Sir Christopher Wren, a famous architect", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who wrote a famous diary about the plague and the Great Fire of London?", "a": "Samuel Pepys — his diary was later published and is still read today", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did the Habeas Corpus Act of 1679 guarantee?", "a": "That no one could be held prisoner unlawfully — every prisoner has a right to a court hearing. 'Habeas corpus' is Latin for 'you must present the person in court'", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["acts", "dates"]}, {"q": "What is the Royal Society?", "a": "A society formed during Charles II's reign to promote 'natural knowledge' — the oldest surviving scientific society in the world; early members included Sir Edmund Halley and Sir Isaac Newton", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is Sir Edmund Halley known for?", "a": "He successfully predicted the return of the comet now called Halley's Comet", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What was Isaac Newton's most famous published work?", "a": "Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica ('Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy'), which showed how gravity applied to the whole universe; he also discovered that white light is made up of the colours of the rainbow", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who became king when Charles II died in 1685?", "a": "His brother James, a Roman Catholic — King James II in England, Wales and Ireland, and King James VII of Scotland", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "Why did people worry about James II?", "a": "He favoured Roman Catholics, allowed them to be army officers (forbidden by an Act of Parliament), did not seek agreement with Parliament and arrested Church of England bishops; when his wife had a son, it seemed the next monarch would not be a Protestant", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy", "religion"]}, {"q": "What was the Glorious Revolution?", "a": "In 1688, important Protestants asked William of Orange (Protestant ruler of the Netherlands, married to James II's daughter Mary) to invade England and proclaim himself king; there was no resistance, James fled to France, and William III ruled jointly with Mary. It was 'glorious' because there was no fighting in England and it guaranteed the power of Parliament", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy", "dates", "religion"]}, {"q": "What titles did William of Orange take?", "a": "William III in England, Wales and Ireland, and William II of Scotland, ruling jointly with Mary", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of the Boyne in 1690?", "a": "William defeated James II (who had invaded Ireland with the help of a French army); the event is still celebrated by some in Northern Ireland today. William re-conquered Ireland and James fled back to France", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["battles", "dates"]}, {"q": "What happened to the MacDonalds of Glencoe?", "a": "All Scottish clans had to formally accept William as king by taking an oath; the MacDonalds of Glencoe were late in taking the oath and were all killed — the memory of this massacre made some Scots distrust the new government", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who were the Jacobites?", "a": "Supporters of James II who continued to believe he was the rightful king, particularly in Scotland; some joined him in exile in France, others were secret supporters", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Where was a rebellion in support of James II quickly defeated in Scotland?", "a": "At Killiecrankie", "section": "3.6", "page": 38, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who were the first people to live in Britain?", "a": "Hunter-gatherers, in what we call the Stone Age", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did Britain become permanently separated from the continent?", "a": "About 10,000 years ago, by the Channel; before that, Britain was connected to the continent by a land bridge for much of the Stone Age", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did the first farmers arrive in Britain, and where did their ancestors come from?", "a": "About 6,000 years ago; their ancestors probably came from south-east Europe", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What is Stonehenge, and where is it?", "a": "A Stone Age monument in what is now the English county of Wiltshire; it was probably a special gathering place for seasonal ceremonies", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What is Skara Brae?", "a": "The best preserved prehistoric village in northern Europe, on Orkney off the north coast of Scotland; it has helped archaeologists understand life near the end of the Stone Age", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did the Bronze Age begin, and how did people live?", "a": "Around 4,000 years ago, when people learned to make bronze; they lived in roundhouses, buried their dead in round barrows, and were accomplished metalworkers in bronze and gold", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What marks the beginnings of British history in the Iron Age?", "a": "The first coins to be minted in Britain, some inscribed with the names of Iron Age kings", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Where can a very impressive Iron Age hill fort still be seen?", "a": "Maiden Castle, in the English county of Dorset", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What language family did Iron Age Britons speak?", "a": "The Celtic language family; related languages are still spoken today in some parts of Wales, Scotland and Ireland", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Who led a Roman invasion of Britain in 55 BC, and what was the result?", "a": "Julius Caesar — it was unsuccessful, and Britain remained separate from the Roman Empire for nearly 100 years", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates", "battles", "people"]}, {"q": "Who led the successful Roman invasion of Britain in AD 43?", "a": "The Emperor Claudius; the Romans occupied almost all of Britain despite resistance from some British tribes", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["dates", "battles", "people"]}, {"q": "Who was Boudicca?", "a": "The queen of the Iceni in what is now eastern England, one of the tribal leaders who fought against the Romans; there is a statue of her on Westminster Bridge in London", "section": "3.7", "page": 39, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "Why did the Emperor Hadrian build a wall in the north of England?", "a": "To keep out the Picts (ancestors of the Scottish people); areas of what is now Scotland were never conquered by the Romans", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["people", "battles"]}, {"q": "Name two forts included in Hadrian's Wall that can still be seen.", "a": "Housesteads and Vindolanda; Hadrian's Wall is a UNESCO World Heritage Site", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "How long did the Romans remain in Britain, and what did they contribute?", "a": "400 years; they built roads and public buildings, created a structure of law, and introduced new plants and animals", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "When did the first Christian communities appear in Britain?", "a": "During the 3rd and 4th centuries AD", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["religion", "dates"]}, {"q": "When did the Roman army leave Britain, and why?", "a": "In AD 410, to defend other parts of the Roman Empire — they never returned", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "Which tribes invaded Britain after the Romans left?", "a": "The Jutes, the Angles and the Saxons, from northern Europe; the languages they spoke are the basis of modern-day English", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "By about what year were Anglo-Saxon kingdoms established in Britain?", "a": "By about AD 600, mainly in what is now England; parts of the west of Britain, including much of Wales, and Scotland remained free of Anglo-Saxon rule", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["dates"]}, {"q": "What is Sutton Hoo?", "a": "The burial place, in modern Suffolk, of an Anglo-Saxon king who was buried with treasure and armour in a ship covered by a mound of earth", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Which missionaries spread Christianity in the north of Britain?", "a": "Missionaries from Ireland — the most famous were St Patrick, who would become the patron saint of Ireland, and St Columba, who founded a monastery on the island of Iona off the coast of what is now Scotland", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["religion", "people"]}, {"q": "Who was St Augustine?", "a": "He led missionaries from Rome who spread Christianity in the south, and became the first Archbishop of Canterbury", "section": "3.7", "page": 40, "tags": ["religion", "people"]}, {"q": "Where did the Vikings come from, and when did they first visit Britain?", "a": "From Denmark and Norway; they first visited in AD 789 to raid coastal towns and take away goods and slaves", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "Who united the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms in England and defeated the Vikings?", "a": "King Alfred the Great", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["people", "monarchy", "battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Danelaw?", "a": "The area in the east and north of England where many Viking invaders stayed; place names such as Grimsby and Scunthorpe come from the Viking languages", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who was the first Danish king of England?", "a": "Cnut, also called Canute — Anglo-Saxon kings otherwise continued to rule except for this short period of Danish kings", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["monarchy", "people"]}, {"q": "Under which king did the people in the north unite, leading to the use of the term Scotland?", "a": "Kenneth MacAlpin — the threat of Viking attack had encouraged the people to unite under one king", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["people", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of Hastings in 1066?", "a": "William, the Duke of Normandy, defeated Harold, the Saxon king of England; Harold was killed and William became king of England — known as William the Conqueror", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["battles", "dates", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "In what year was the Battle of Hastings?", "a": "1066", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["dates", "battles"]}, {"q": "What commemorates the Battle of Hastings?", "a": "A great piece of embroidery known as the Bayeux Tapestry, which can still be seen in France today", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Why is the Norman Conquest significant?", "a": "It was the last successful foreign invasion of England and led to many changes in government and social structures; Norman French, the language of the new ruling class, influenced the development of English", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Did the Normans conquer Wales and Scotland?", "a": "They initially conquered Wales, but the Welsh gradually won territory back; they took over some land on the border with Scotland but did not invade Scotland", "section": "3.7", "page": 41, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Domesday Book?", "a": "Lists drawn up on William the Conqueror's orders of all the towns and villages, the people who lived there, who owned the land and what animals they owned; it still exists today and shows society in England just after the Norman Conquest", "section": "3.7", "page": 42, "tags": ["monarchy"]}]}, {"chapter": 4, "title": "A modern, thriving society", "sections": [{"id": "4.2", "title": "Arts and culture", "summary": "## Music\n- **The Proms**: an **eight-week summer season** of orchestral classical music in various venues including the **Royal Albert Hall, London**; organised by the **BBC since 1927**. The **Last Night of the Proms** is the most well-known concert and is broadcast on television.\n- **Henry Purcell (1659–95)**: organist at **Westminster Abbey**; wrote church music, operas and other pieces; developed a British style distinct from the rest of Europe.\n- **George Frederick Handel (1695–1759)**: German-born; became a **British citizen in 1727**; wrote the **Water Music** for **King George I** and **Music for the Royal Fireworks** for his son **George II**; also the oratorio **Messiah**, sung regularly by choirs, often at Easter.\n- **Gustav Holst (1874–1934)**: wrote **The Planets**; adapted **Jupiter** as the tune for the hymn **I vow to thee my country**.\n- **Sir Edward Elgar (1857–1934)**: born in **Worcester**; best known for the **Pomp and Circumstance Marches** — **March No 1 (Land of Hope and Glory)** is usually played at the Last Night of the Proms.\n- **Ralph Vaughan Williams (1872–1958)**: music for orchestras and choirs; strongly influenced by **traditional English folk music**.\n- **Sir William Walton (1902–83)**: marches for the coronations of **King George VI** and **Queen Elizabeth II**; best-known works **Façade** (became a ballet) and **Balthazar's Feast** (for large choir).\n- **Benjamin Britten (1913–76)**: operas **Peter Grimes** and **Billy Budd**; **A Young Person's Guide to the Orchestra** (based on music by Purcell); founded the **Aldeburgh festival** in **Suffolk**.\n- Pop: since the **1960s** British pop has made a major cultural contribution — **The Beatles** and **The Rolling Stones**; the **Punk** movement of the late 1970s; boy and girl bands in the 1990s.\n- Large venues: **Wembley Stadium**, **The O2** (Greenwich, south-east London), **SECC** (Glasgow). Summer festivals: **Glastonbury**, **Isle of Wight Festival**, **V Festival**.\n- **National Eisteddfod of Wales**: annual cultural festival largely in Welsh, with important **Welsh poetry** competitions.\n- **Mercury Music Prize**: awarded each **September** for the best album from the **UK and Ireland**. **Brit Awards**: annual awards, e.g. best British group and best British solo artist.\n\n## Theatre\n- London's **West End** is known as **'Theatreland'**. **The Mousetrap** by **Dame Agatha Christie** has run since **1952** — the **longest initial run** of any show in history.\n- **Gilbert and Sullivan** (19th century): comic operas — **HMS Pinafore**, **The Pirates of Penzance**, **The Mikado**.\n- **Andrew Lloyd Webber**: with **Tim Rice** — **Jesus Christ Superstar** and **Evita**; also **Cats** and **The Phantom of the Opera**.\n- **Pantomime**: Christmas tradition based on fairy stories; the **Dame** is a woman played by a man; pantomime horse or cow played by two actors.\n- **Edinburgh Festival** every summer; biggest part is the **Edinburgh Festival Fringe** — mainly theatre and comedy, often experimental.\n- **Laurence Olivier Awards**: annual, in London; categories include best director, best actor, best actress; named after **Sir Laurence Olivier**, famous for Shakespeare roles.\n\n## Art\n- Middle Ages art was mostly **religious**; much lost after the **Protestant Reformation**. 16th–17th century painters in Britain were often from abroad — **Hans Holbein**, **Sir Anthony Van Dyck**.\n- Major galleries: **The National Gallery, Tate Britain, Tate Modern** (London), **National Museum** (Cardiff), **National Gallery of Scotland** (Edinburgh).\n- **Turner Prize**: established **1984**, named after **Joseph Turner**; celebrates contemporary art; **four works shortlisted** yearly and shown at **Tate Britain**; winners include **Damien Hirst** and **Richard Wright**.\n- Notable artists: **Thomas Gainsborough (1727–88)** portraits in country/garden scenery; **David Allan (1744–96)** Scottish portraitist (**The Origin of Painting**); **Joseph Turner (1775–1851)** landscape pioneer; **John Constable (1776–1837)** landscapes of **Dedham Vale** (Suffolk–Essex border); the **Pre-Raphaelites** (**Holman Hunt, Dante Gabriel Rossetti, Sir John Millais**); **Sir John Lavery (1856–1941)** Northern Irish portraitist who painted the Royal Family; **Henry Moore (1898–1986)** large bronze abstract sculptures; **John Petts (1914–91)** Welsh engravings and stained glass; **Lucian Freud (1922–2011)** German-born British portraitist; **David Hockney (1937–)** 'pop art' of the 1960s.\n\n## Architecture\n- Middle Ages: cathedrals at **Durham, Lincoln, Canterbury, Salisbury**; the **White Tower** (Tower of London) is a **Norman castle keep** built on the orders of **William the Conqueror**.\n- Great country houses such as **Hardwick Hall** (Derbyshire).\n- 17th century: **Inigo Jones** — **Queen's House** (Greenwich) and **Banqueting House** (Whitehall); **Sir Christopher Wren** — the new **St Paul's Cathedral**.\n- 18th century: Scottish architect **Robert Adam** — **Dumfries House** (Scotland); influenced the **Royal Crescent** in **Bath**.\n- 19th century: 'gothic' revival — **Houses of Parliament**, **St Pancras Station**, town halls in **Manchester** and **Sheffield**.\n- 20th century: **Sir Edwin Lutyens** designed **New Delhi** and many war memorials, including the **Cenotaph** in Whitehall — site of the annual **Remembrance Day** service.\n- Modern architects: **Sir Norman Foster**, **Lord (Richard) Rogers**, **Dame Zaha Hadid**.\n- Gardens: **Lancelot 'Capability' Brown** (18th century natural-looking landscapes); **Gertrude Jekyll** (colourful gardens, often with Lutyens); annual **Chelsea Flower Show**.\n\n## Fashion and design\n- **Thomas Chippendale** (18th-century furniture), **Clarice Cliff** (Art Deco ceramics), **Sir Terence Conran** (20th-century interior designer). Fashion: **Mary Quant**, **Alexander McQueen**, **Vivienne Westwood**.\n\n## Literature\n- **Nobel Prize in Literature** winners: **Sir William Golding** (novelist), **Seamus Heaney** (poet), **Harold Pinter** (playwright).\n- **Agatha Christie**'s detective stories; **Ian Fleming** introduced **James Bond**; in **2003 The Lord of the Rings** by **JRR Tolkien** was voted the country's best-loved novel.\n- **Man Booker Prize for Fiction**: awarded annually since **1968** for the best fiction novel by an author from the **Commonwealth, Ireland or Zimbabwe**; winners include **Ian McEwan, Hilary Mantel, Julian Barnes**.\n- Authors: **Jane Austen** (Pride and Prejudice, Sense and Sensibility — marriage and family relationships); **Charles Dickens** (Oliver Twist, Great Expectations; characters Scrooge — a mean person — and Mr Micawber — always hopeful); **Robert Louis Stevenson** (Treasure Island, Kidnapped, Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde); **Thomas Hardy** (Far from the Madding Crowd, Jude the Obscure — rural society); **Sir Arthur Conan Doyle** (Scottish doctor; Sherlock Holmes, one of the first fictional detectives); **Evelyn Waugh** (Decline and Fall, Scoop, Brideshead Revisited); **Sir Kingsley Amis** (more than 20 novels; Lucky Jim); **Graham Greene** (The Heart of the Matter, The Honorary Consul, Brighton Rock, Our Man in Havana); **J K Rowling** (Harry Potter).\n\n## British poets\n- **Beowulf**: Anglo-Saxon poem about its hero's battles against monsters. Middle Ages: **Chaucer's Canterbury Tales** and **Sir Gawain and the Green Knight** (a knight at the court of King Arthur).\n- **Shakespeare** wrote many **sonnets (14 lines)**. **John Milton** wrote **Paradise Lost**.\n- **William Wordsworth** inspired by nature; **Sir Walter Scott** by Scotland (also wrote novels set in Scotland).\n- 19th century: **William Blake, John Keats, Lord Byron, Percy Shelley, Alfred Lord Tennyson, Robert and Elizabeth Browning**. First World War poets: **Wilfred Owen**, **Siegfried Sassoon**. Later: **Sir Walter de la Mare, John Masefield, Sir John Betjeman, Ted Hughes**.\n- Best-known poets are buried or commemorated in **Poet's Corner, Westminster Abbey**.\n- Famous lines quoted: **Robert Browning** — *Home Thoughts from Abroad*; **Lord Byron** — *She Walks in Beauty*; **William Wordsworth** — *The Daffodils*; **William Blake** — *The Tyger*; **Wilfred Owen** — *Anthem for Doomed Youth*.", "checkUnderstand": ["Which sports are particularly popular in the UK", "Some of the major sporting events that take place each year", "Some of the major arts and culture events that happen in the UK", "How achievements in arts and culture are formally recognised", "Important figures in British literature"]}, {"id": "4.3", "title": "Customs and traditions", "summary": "## The main Christian festivals\n- **Christmas Day, 25 December**: celebrates the birth of Jesus Christ; a **public holiday**. Many Christians go to church on **Christmas Eve (24 December)** or Christmas Day. Traditional meal: **roast turkey, Christmas pudding and mince pies**; gifts, cards, decorated trees; **Father Christmas (Santa Claus)** brings presents to young children.\n- **Boxing Day**: the day after Christmas Day; a **public holiday**.\n- **Easter** (March or April): marks the **death of Jesus Christ on Good Friday** and his **rising from the dead on Easter Sunday**. **Good Friday** and **Easter Monday** are public holidays.\n- **Lent**: the **40 days before Easter**, a time to reflect and prepare; many give something up. **Shrove Tuesday (Pancake Day)** is the day before Lent; pancakes used up eggs, fat and milk before fasting. Lent begins on **Ash Wednesday**, when Christians are marked with an ash cross as a symbol of death and sorrow for sin.\n- **Easter eggs**: chocolate eggs given as presents as a **symbol of new life**; Easter is also celebrated by non-religious people.\n\n## Other religious festivals\n- **Diwali**: normally **October or November**, lasts **five days**; the **Festival of Lights**; celebrated by **Hindus and Sikhs**; celebrates the victory of good over evil and the gaining of knowledge; famous celebration in **Leicester**.\n- **Hannukah**: **November or December**, **eight days**; remembers the **Jews' struggle for religious freedom**; a candle is lit each day on a **menorah** (stand of eight candles), recalling oil that should have lasted one day lasting eight.\n- **Eid al-Fitr**: celebrates the **end of Ramadan** after Muslims have fasted for a month; thanks to Allah for strength to complete the fast; date changes every year.\n- **Eid ul Adha**: remembers the prophet **Ibrahim's willingness to sacrifice his son** when God ordered it; many Muslims sacrifice an animal (in Britain this must be done in a slaughterhouse).\n- **Vaisakhi (Baisakhi)**: Sikh festival celebrating the founding of the **Khalsa**; celebrated on **14 April** each year with parades, dancing and singing.\n\n## Other festivals and traditions\n- **New Year, 1 January**: public holiday; celebrated on **New Year's Eve (31 December)**. In Scotland 31 December is **Hogmanay** and **2 January is also a public holiday**; for some Scots Hogmanay is bigger than Christmas.\n- **Valentine's Day, 14 February**: lovers exchange cards and gifts; anonymous cards to secret admirers.\n- **April Fool's Day, 1 April**: jokes **until midday**; TV and newspapers run joke stories.\n- **Mothering Sunday (Mother's Day)**: the **Sunday three weeks before Easter**.\n- **Father's Day**: the **third Sunday in June**.\n- **Halloween, 31 October**: ancient festival with roots in the **pagan festival marking the beginning of winter**; 'trick or treat'; pumpkin lanterns.\n- **Bonfire Night, 5 November**: fireworks; origin — in **1605** a group of Catholics led by **Guy Fawkes** failed to kill the Protestant king with a bomb in the Houses of Parliament.\n- **Remembrance Day, 11 November**: commemorates those who died fighting for the UK and its allies; originally the dead of the **First World War, which ended 11 November 1918**; people wear **poppies**; **two-minute silence at 11.00 am**; wreaths laid at the **Cenotaph** in Whitehall.\n\n## Bank holidays\n- Public holidays with **no religious significance** when banks and many businesses close: **beginning of May**, **late May or early June**, and **August**. In **Northern Ireland**, the anniversary of the **Battle of the Boyne in July** is also a public holiday.", "checkUnderstand": ["The main Christian festivals that are celebrated in the UK", "Other religious festivals that are important in the UK", "Some of the other events that are celebrated in the UK", "What a bank holiday is"]}, {"id": "4.4", "title": "Leisure", "summary": "## Gardening\n- Many people garden at home; some rent land called an **'allotment'** to grow fruit and vegetables.\n- Famous gardens: **Kew Gardens, Sissinghurst and Hidcote** (England); **Crathes Castle and Inveraray Castle** (Scotland); **Bodnant Garden** (Wales); **Mount Stewart** (Northern Ireland).\n- Each UK country has flowers particularly associated with it, sometimes worn on national saints' days.\n\n## Shopping\n- Town centres, undercover shopping centres, and markets on one or more days a week; most shops open **seven days a week** with reduced Sunday/public-holiday hours.\n\n## Cooking and food — traditional foods\n- **England**: **roast beef** with potatoes, vegetables and **Yorkshire puddings** (baked batter); **fish and chips** also popular.\n- **Wales**: **Welsh cakes** — flour, dried fruits and spices, served hot or cold.\n- **Scotland**: **Haggis** — sheep's stomach stuffed with offal, suet, onions and oatmeal.\n- **Northern Ireland**: **Ulster fry** — bacon, eggs, sausage, black pudding, white pudding, tomatoes, mushrooms, soda bread and potato bread.\n\n## Films\n- Films first shown publicly in the UK in **1896**; British film makers famous for **special effects** from the beginning.\n- **Sir Charles (Charlie) Chaplin** became famous in silent movies for his **tramp** character.\n- 1930s directors: **Sir Alexander Korda** and **Sir Alfred Hitchcock** (who later left for Hollywood; died **1980**). WWII morale films e.g. **In Which We Serve**. Later: **Sir David Lean** and **Ridley Scott**.\n- 1950s–60s high point for comedies: **Passport to Pimlico**, **The Ladykillers**, later the **Carry On** films.\n- The **two highest-grossing film franchises** — **Harry Potter** and **James Bond** — were produced in the UK. **Ealing Studios** claims to be the **oldest continuously working film studio facility in the world**.\n- **Nick Park** has won **four Oscars** for animation, including **three for Wallace and Gromit** films.\n- Famous actors: Sir Lawrence Olivier, David Niven, Sir Rex Harrison, Richard Burton; recent British Oscar winners: **Colin Firth, Sir Anthony Hopkins, Dame Judi Dench, Kate Winslet, Tilda Swinton**.\n- The **British Academy Film Awards (BAFTA)** are the **British equivalent of the Oscars**.\n- Famous British films: **The 39 Steps (1935, Hitchcock)**, **Brief Encounter (1945, David Lean)**, **The Third Man (1949, Carol Reed)**, **The Belles of St Trinian's (1954, Frank Launder)**, **Lawrence of Arabia (1962, David Lean)**, **Women in Love (1969, Ken Russell)**, **Don't Look Now (1973, Nicolas Roeg)**, **Chariots of Fire (1981, Hugh Hudson)**, **The Killing Fields (1984, Roland Joffé)**, **Four Weddings and a Funeral (1994, Mike Newell)**, **Touching the Void (2003, Kevin MacDonald)**.\n\n## British comedy\n- Medieval kings had **jesters**; Shakespeare included comic characters; 18th-century **political cartoons**; 19th-century satirical magazines — most famously **Punch**, first published in the **1840s**; today **Private Eye** continues the satire tradition.\n- **Music hall** comedians (e.g. **Morecambe and Wise**) became TV stars. TV satire: **That Was The Week That Was** (1960s), **Spitting Image** (1980s–90s). In **1969, Monty Python's Flying Circus** introduced a new progressive comedy; **stand-up** is popular again.\n\n## Television and radio\n- Popular soap operas: **Coronation Street** and **EastEnders**. Scotland has Scotland-specific programmes and a **Gaelic** channel; Wales has a **Welsh-language** channel; Northern Ireland has some programmes in **Irish Gaelic**.\n- Everyone watching TV must have a **TV licence** (one per home, except separate tenancies in shared houses). People **over 75** can apply for a free licence; **blind people can get a 50% discount**; fine up to **£1,000** for watching TV without one.\n- Licence money funds the **BBC** — the **largest broadcaster in the world** and the only wholly state-funded media organisation **independent of government**. Other channels are funded by advertisements and subscriptions; same for radio.\n\n## Social networking\n- **Facebook** and **Twitter** used to stay in touch, organise events, share photos, videos and opinions.\n\n## Pubs and night clubs\n- Pubs are a focal point of social culture; **pub quizzes**, **pool and darts** are traditional. You must be **18** to buy alcohol; at **16** you may drink wine or beer **with a meal** in a hotel or restaurant (including pub eating areas) with someone over 18.\n- Pubs usually open from **11.00 am (12 noon Sundays)**; the **licensee** decides opening hours.\n\n## Betting and gambling\n- Must be **18** to enter betting shops or gambling clubs. The **National Lottery** has draws **every week** (tickets or scratch cards); under-18s may not participate.\n\n## Pets\n- Cruelty or neglect is against the law. All dogs in public places must wear a **collar showing the name and address of the owner**; owners must keep dogs under control and clean up after them. Vets treat animals; charities may help those who cannot afford one.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "4.5", "title": "Places of interest", "summary": "- The UK has a large network of **public footpaths**; opportunities for mountain biking, mountaineering and hill walking.\n- There are **15 national parks** in **England, Wales and Scotland** — protected countryside everyone can visit, where people live, work and look after the landscape.\n- Many places are kept open by the **National Trust** (England, Wales and Northern Ireland) and the **National Trust for Scotland** — both **charities** preserving important buildings, coastline and countryside. The National Trust was **founded in 1895 by three volunteers**; today there are **more than 61,000 volunteers**.\n\n## UK landmarks\n- **Big Ben**: nickname for the **great bell of the clock at the Houses of Parliament**, London; the clock is **over 150 years old**; the clock tower was named **'Elizabeth Tower'** for **Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee in 2012**.\n- **Eden Project**: in **Cornwall** (south west England); **biomes** like giant greenhouses house plants from all over the world; also a charity running environmental and social projects internationally.\n- **Edinburgh Castle**: dominates the Edinburgh skyline; dates back to the early Middle Ages; looked after by **Historic Scotland**, a Scottish government agency.\n- **Giant's Causeway**: on the **north-east coast of Northern Ireland**; a land formation of **columns made from volcanic lava**, formed about **50 million years ago**; many legends surround it.\n- **Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park**: **720 square miles (1,865 sq km)** in the **west of Scotland**; **Loch Lomond is the largest expanse of fresh water in mainland Britain**.\n- **London Eye**: a **Ferris wheel 443 feet (135 metres) tall** on the **southern bank of the River Thames**; built as part of the UK's **millennium** celebration; part of New Year celebrations.\n- **Snowdonia**: national park in **North Wales**, **838 square miles (2,170 sq km)**; **Snowdon** is the **highest mountain in Wales**.\n- **Tower of London**: first built by **William the Conqueror after he became king in 1066**; tours by the **Yeoman Warders (Beefeaters)**; home of the **Crown Jewels**.\n- **Lake District**: **England's largest national park**, **885 square miles (2,292 sq km)**; famous for lakes and mountains; the biggest stretch of water is **Windermere**; in **2007** TV viewers voted **Wastwater** Britain's favourite view.", "checkUnderstand": ["Some of the ways in which people in the UK spend their leisure time", "The development of British cinema", "What the television licence is and how it funds the BBC", "Some of the places of interest to visit in the UK"]}, {"id": "4.6", "title": "Religion", "summary": "- The UK is **historically a Christian country**. In the **2009 Citizenship Survey**: **70% Christian**, **4% Muslim**, **2% Hindu**, **1% Sikh**, **less than 0.5% Jewish or Buddhist**, **2% other religion**, and **21% no religion**.\n- Religious buildings across the UK: Islamic **mosques**, Hindu **temples**, Jewish **synagogues**, Sikh **gurdwaras**, Buddhist **temples**. Everyone has the **legal right to choose their religion or not to practise one**.\n\n## Christian Churches\n- In **England** there is a **constitutional link between Church and state**. The official Church of the state is the **Church of England** (called the **Anglican Church** in other countries and the **Episcopal Church** in Scotland and the United States). It is a **Protestant Church** and has existed since the **Reformation in the 1530s**.\n- The **monarch is the head** of the Church of England; the **spiritual leader is the Archbishop of Canterbury**. The monarch has the right to select the Archbishop and senior officials, but usually the choice is made by the **Prime Minister and a committee appointed by the Church**. Several Church of England **bishops sit in the House of Lords**.\n- In **Scotland** the national Church is the **Church of Scotland**, a **Presbyterian** Church governed by **ministers and elders**. Its General Assembly chairperson is the **Moderator**, appointed for **one year only**, who often speaks on behalf of the Church.\n- There is **no established Church in Wales or Northern Ireland**.\n- Other Protestant groups: **Baptists, Methodists, Presbyterians and Quakers**. The biggest other denomination of Christianity is **Roman Catholic**.\n\n## Patron Saints' days\n- **1 March: St David's Day, Wales**\n- **17 March: St Patrick's Day, Northern Ireland**\n- **23 April: St George's Day, England**\n- **30 November: St Andrew's Day, Scotland**\n- Only **Scotland and Northern Ireland** have their patron saint's day as an **official holiday** (though in Scotland not all businesses and offices close). In England and Wales the days are no longer public holidays but are still celebrated with parades and small festivals.", "checkUnderstand": ["The different religions that are practised in the UK", "That the Anglican Church, also known as the Church of England, is the Church of the state in England (the ‘established Church’)", "That other branches of the Christian Church also practise their faith in the UK without being linked to the state", "That other religions are practised in the UK", "About the patron saints"]}, {"id": "4.7", "title": "Sport", "summary": "- Major stadiums: **Wembley Stadium** (London) and the **Millennium Stadium** (Cardiff). Many famous sports began in Britain: **cricket, football, lawn tennis, golf and rugby**.\n- The UK has hosted the **Olympic Games three times: 1908, 1948 and 2012**. The main 2012 site was **Stratford, East London**; the British team finished **third in the medal table**.\n- The **2012 Paralympic Games** were also hosted in London. The Paralympics originated in the work of **Dr Sir Ludwig Guttman**, a **German refugee**, at the **Stoke Mandeville hospital in Buckinghamshire**, who developed treatments for spinal injuries and encouraged patients to take part in sport.\n\n## Notable British sportsmen and women\n- **Sir Roger Bannister**: first man in the world to run a **mile in under four minutes**, in **1954**.\n- **Sir Jackie Stewart**: Scottish racing driver; won the **Formula 1 world championship three times**.\n- **Bobby Moore**: captained the English football team that **won the World Cup in 1966**.\n- **Sir Ian Botham**: captained the English cricket team; holds English Test cricket records for **batting and bowling**.\n- **Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean**: **ice dancing** gold at the **1984 Olympics** and four consecutive world championships.\n- **Sir Steve Redgrave**: **rowing** gold medals in **five consecutive Olympic Games**.\n- **Baroness Tanni-Grey Thompson**: wheelchair athlete; **16 Paralympic medals including 11 gold**; won the **London Marathon six times**; broke **30 world records**.\n- **Dame Kelly Holmes**: **two gold medals for running** at the **2004** Olympics.\n- **Dame Ellen MacArthur**: yachtswoman; in **2004** became the **fastest person to sail around the world singlehanded**.\n- **Sir Chris Hoy**: Scottish cyclist; **six gold and one silver** Olympic medals; **11 world championship titles**.\n- **David Weir**: wheelchair Paralympian; **six gold medals over two Paralympic Games**; won the **London Marathon six times**.\n- **Bradley Wiggins**: cyclist; in **2012 the first Briton to win the Tour de France**; **seven Olympic medals** including golds in 2004, 2008 and 2012.\n- **Mo Farah**: distance runner born in **Somalia**; **2012 Olympic golds in the 5,000 and 10,000 metres**; first Briton to win Olympic gold in the 10,000 metres.\n- **Jessica Ennis**: won the **2012 Olympic gold in the heptathlon** (seven track and field events).\n- **Andy Murray**: Scottish tennis player; won the **2012 US Open men's singles** — the **first British man to win a Grand Slam singles title since 1936**; also Olympic gold and silver in 2012 and Wimbledon runner-up.\n- **Ellie Simmonds**: Paralympic **swimming** golds in **2008 and 2012**; **youngest member of the British team at the 2008 Games**.\n\n## Individual sports\n- **Cricket**: originated in England; games can last up to **five days**; the most famous competition is **the Ashes** — Test matches between **England and Australia**. Cricket expressions in everyday use include 'rain stopped play' and 'it's just not cricket'.\n- **Football**: the **UK's most popular sport**; first professional clubs formed in the **late 19th century**; each UK country has its own leagues and national team; the **English Premier League** attracts a huge international audience; UK teams compete in the **UEFA Champions League**. **England's only international tournament victory was the 1966 World Cup**, hosted in the UK.\n- **Rugby**: originated in England in the **early 19th century**; two types with different rules — **union and league**; Northern Ireland plays with the Irish Republic. Most famous union competition: the **Six Nations Championship** (England, Ireland, Scotland, Wales, France, Italy); the **Super League** is the best-known rugby league (club) competition.\n- **Horse-racing**: evidence back to **Roman times**; long royal association. Famous events: **Royal Ascot** (five-day meeting in **Berkshire**), the **Grand National** at **Aintree near Liverpool**, the **Scottish Grand National** at **Ayr**. **National Horseracing Museum** in **Newmarket, Suffolk**.\n- **Golf**: traced back to **15th century Scotland**; **St Andrews** in Scotland is the **home of golf**; **The Open Championship** is the **only 'Major' held outside the United States**, hosted by a different course each year.\n- **Tennis**: evolved in England in the late 19th century; **first tennis club founded in Leamington Spa in 1872**; **Wimbledon** (All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club) is the **oldest tennis tournament in the world** and the only **Grand Slam played on grass**.\n- **Water sports**: **Sir Francis Chichester** — first to sail single-handed around the world (**1966/67**); two years later **Sir Robin Knox-Johnston** did it **without stopping**. Most famous sailing event at **Cowes, Isle of Wight**. Popular yearly **rowing race on the Thames between Oxford and Cambridge Universities**.\n- **Motor sports**: motor-car racing in the UK started in **1902**; a **Formula 1 Grand Prix** is held in the UK each year; recent British F1 world champions include **Damon Hill, Lewis Hamilton and Jensen Button**.\n- **Skiing**: dry ski slopes throughout the UK; **five ski centres in Scotland**; **Europe's longest dry ski slope near Edinburgh**.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "4.8", "title": "The UK today", "summary": "- The UK is more diverse than 100 years ago, ethnically and religiously. Post-war immigration means **nearly 10% of the population has a parent or grandparent born outside the UK**.\n\n## The nations of the UK\n- The UK is in the **north west of Europe**. The longest mainland distance is from **John O'Groats** (north coast of Scotland) to **Land's End** (south-west England) — about **870 miles (approximately 1,400 kilometres)**.\n- Cities — **England**: London, Birmingham, Liverpool, Leeds, Sheffield, Bristol, Manchester, Bradford, Newcastle Upon Tyne, Plymouth, Southampton, Norwich. **Wales**: Cardiff, Swansea, Newport. **Scotland**: Edinburgh, Glasgow, Dundee, Aberdeen. **Northern Ireland**: Belfast.\n- Capital cities: **UK — London**; **Scotland — Edinburgh**; **Wales — Cardiff**; **Northern Ireland — Belfast**.\n\n## UK currency\n- The currency is the **pound sterling (£)**; **100 pence in a pound**. Coins: **1p, 2p, 5p, 10p, 20p, 50p, £1, £2**; notes: **£5, £10, £20, £50**.\n- **Northern Ireland and Scotland have their own banknotes**, valid everywhere in the UK — but shops and businesses **do not have to accept them**.\n\n## Languages and dialects\n- English has many accents and dialects. In **Wales** many people speak **Welsh** — a completely different language, taught in schools and universities. In Scotland, **Gaelic** is spoken in parts of the **Highlands and Islands**; in Northern Ireland some people speak **Irish Gaelic**.\n\n## Population\n- Growth over time: **1600 — just over 4 million; 1700 — 5 million; 1801 — 8 million; 1851 — 20 million; 1901 — 40 million; 1951 — 50 million; 1998 — 57 million; 2005 — just under 60 million; 2010 — just over 62 million; 2022 — estimated 67.6 million** (source: National Statistics).\n- Growth has been faster in recent years, driven by **migration into the UK and longer life expectancy**.\n- Distribution: **England about 84%**, **Wales around 5%**, **Scotland just over 8%**, **Northern Ireland less than 3%**.\n- **An ageing population**: people live longer due to improved living standards and better health care; a **record number of people aged 85 and over**; this affects the **cost of pensions and health care**.\n\n## Ethnic diversity\n- The population is ethnically diverse and changing rapidly, especially in large cities such as London. The most common ethnic description chosen in surveys is **white** (including people of European, Australian, Canadian, New Zealand and American descent); other significant groups are of **Asian, black and mixed** descent.\n\n## An equal society\n- It is a **legal requirement** that men and women are not discriminated against because of gender or marital status; they have **equal rights to work, own property, marry and divorce**; married parents are **equally responsible for their children**.\n- **Women make up about half the workforce**; on average **girls leave school with better qualifications than boys**; **more women than men study at university**. There are now more women in high-level positions than ever before; in many families both partners work and share childcare and household chores.", "checkUnderstand": ["The capital cities of the UK", "What languages other than English are spoken in particular parts of the UK", "How the population of the UK has changed", "That the UK is an equal society and ethnically diverse", "The currency of the UK"]}], "flashcards": [{"q": "What is the Proms and how long does it last?", "a": "An eight-week summer season of orchestral classical music, held in various venues including the Royal Albert Hall in London.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Who has organised the Proms, and since when?", "a": "The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC), since 1927.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Who was Henry Purcell?", "a": "The organist at Westminster Abbey (1659–95); he wrote church music, operas and other pieces and developed a British style distinct from that elsewhere in Europe.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Which German-born composer became a British citizen in 1727?", "a": "George Frederick Handel.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Who did Handel write the Water Music and Music for the Royal Fireworks for?", "a": "The Water Music for King George I, and Music for the Royal Fireworks for his son, George II.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "What oratorio did Handel write that is often sung by choirs at Easter time?", "a": "Messiah.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Which composer wrote The Planets and adapted Jupiter as the tune for 'I vow to thee my country'?", "a": "Gustav Holst (1874–1934).", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Where was Sir Edward Elgar born, and what is his best-known work?", "a": "He was born in Worcester, England; his best-known work is probably the Pomp and Circumstance Marches. March No 1 (Land of Hope and Glory) is usually played at the Last Night of the Proms.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "What strongly influenced the music of Ralph Vaughan Williams?", "a": "Traditional English folk music.", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Which composer wrote marches for the coronations of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth II?", "a": "Sir William Walton — his best-known works are probably Façade (which became a ballet) and Balthazar's Feast (for a large choir).", "section": "4.2", "page": 44, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Which operas is Benjamin Britten best known for, and what festival did he found?", "a": "Peter Grimes and Billy Budd; he founded the Aldeburgh festival in Suffolk. He also wrote A Young Person's Guide to the Orchestra, based on a piece by Purcell.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Name three large venues that host music events in the UK.", "a": "Wembley Stadium; The O2 in Greenwich, south-east London; and the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) in Glasgow.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Name three famous UK summer music festivals.", "a": "Glastonbury, the Isle of Wight Festival and the V Festival.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "What is the National Eisteddfod of Wales?", "a": "An annual cultural festival including music, dance, art and original performances largely in Welsh, with a number of important competitions for Welsh poetry.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music", "traditions"]}, {"q": "What is the Mercury Music Prize and when is it awarded?", "a": "It is awarded each September for the best album from the UK and Ireland.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "What are the Brit Awards?", "a": "An annual event giving awards in a range of categories, such as best British group and best British solo artist.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "music"]}, {"q": "Which play has had the longest initial run of any show in history?", "a": "The Mousetrap, a murder-mystery play by Dame Agatha Christie, running in London's West End since 1952.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "What is London's West End also known as?", "a": "'Theatreland'.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "Name the comic operas written by Gilbert and Sullivan in the 19th century.", "a": "HMS Pinafore, The Pirates of Penzance and The Mikado — comic operas often making fun of popular culture and politics.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "Which shows did Andrew Lloyd Webber write in collaboration with Tim Rice?", "a": "Jesus Christ Superstar and Evita. He also wrote Cats and The Phantom of the Opera.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "In a traditional pantomime, who is the 'Dame'?", "a": "A woman played by a man. Pantomimes are light-hearted plays based on fairy stories, produced by many theatres at Christmas time.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre", "traditions"]}, {"q": "What is the biggest and most well-known part of the Edinburgh Festival?", "a": "The Edinburgh Festival Fringe ('the Fringe') — a showcase of mainly theatre and comedy performances, often showing experimental work.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "Who are the Laurence Olivier Awards named after?", "a": "The British actor Sir Laurence Olivier (later Lord Olivier), best known for his roles in various Shakespeare plays. The awards take place annually at different venues in London.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "theatre"]}, {"q": "Name two painters from abroad who worked in Britain in the 16th and 17th centuries.", "a": "Hans Holbein and Sir Anthony Van Dyck.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Name some of the most well-known art galleries in the UK.", "a": "The National Gallery, Tate Britain and Tate Modern in London, the National Museum in Cardiff, and the National Gallery of Scotland in Edinburgh.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "When was the Turner Prize established and who was it named after?", "a": "It was established in 1984 and named after Joseph Turner. It celebrates contemporary art and is recognised as one of the most prestigious visual art awards in Europe.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "How does the Turner Prize shortlist work, and name two previous winners.", "a": "Four works are shortlisted every year and shown at Tate Britain before the winner is announced. Previous winners include Damien Hirst and Richard Wright.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "What was Thomas Gainsborough known for?", "a": "He was a portrait painter (1727–88) who often painted people in country or garden scenery.", "section": "4.2", "page": 45, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Who painted The Origin of Painting?", "a": "David Allan (1744–96), a Scottish painter best known for portraits.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Which artist is considered to have raised the profile of landscape painting?", "a": "Joseph Turner (1775–1851), an influential landscape painter in a modern style.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "What is John Constable most famous for painting?", "a": "His works of Dedham Vale on the Suffolk–Essex border in the east of England — he was a landscape painter.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Who were the Pre-Raphaelites?", "a": "An important group of artists in the second half of the 19th century who painted detailed pictures on religious or literary themes in bright colours. The group included Holman Hunt, Dante Gabriel Rossetti and Sir John Millais.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Who was Sir John Lavery?", "a": "A very successful Northern Irish portrait painter (1856–1941) whose work included painting the Royal Family.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "What is the sculptor Henry Moore best known for?", "a": "His large bronze abstract sculptures.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "What was the Welsh artist John Petts best known for?", "a": "His engravings and stained glass.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "What is the German-born British artist Lucian Freud best known for?", "a": "His portraits.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Which artist was an important contributor to the 'pop art' movement of the 1960s?", "a": "David Hockney.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "art"]}, {"q": "Name the English cities with great medieval cathedrals mentioned in the handbook.", "a": "Durham, Lincoln, Canterbury and Salisbury.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "What is the White Tower in the Tower of London an example of?", "a": "A Norman castle keep, built on the orders of William the Conqueror.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Which buildings did Inigo Jones design in the 17th century?", "a": "The Queen's House at Greenwich and the Banqueting House in Whitehall in London, taking inspiration from classical architecture.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Which architect designed the new St Paul's Cathedral?", "a": "Sir Christopher Wren, who helped develop a British version of the ornate styles popular in Europe.", "section": "4.2", "page": 46, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Who was Robert Adam?", "a": "An 18th-century Scottish architect who influenced architecture in the UK, Europe and America. He designed the inside decoration as well as the building itself in great houses such as Dumfries House in Scotland; his ideas influenced architects in cities such as Bath, where the Royal Crescent was built.", "section": "4.2", "page": 47, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Which famous buildings were built in the 19th-century 'gothic' style?", "a": "The Houses of Parliament and St Pancras Station, as well as the town halls in cities such as Manchester and Sheffield.", "section": "4.2", "page": 47, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "What did Sir Edwin Lutyens design?", "a": "He designed New Delhi to be the seat of government in India, and after the First World War was responsible for many war memorials throughout the world, including the Cenotaph in Whitehall.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "What happens at the Cenotaph in Whitehall each year?", "a": "It is the site of the annual Remembrance Day service attended by the Queen, politicians and foreign ambassadors.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "architecture", "traditions"]}, {"q": "Name three modern British architects who work on major projects around the world.", "a": "Sir Norman Foster, Lord (Richard) Rogers and Dame Zaha Hadid.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Who was Lancelot 'Capability' Brown?", "a": "An 18th-century designer of grounds around country houses so the landscape appeared natural, with grass, trees and lakes. He often said that a place had 'capabilities'.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "Which garden designer often worked with Edwin Lutyens?", "a": "Gertrude Jekyll, who designed colourful gardens around the houses he designed.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "architecture"]}, {"q": "What does the annual Chelsea Flower Show showcase?", "a": "Garden design from Britain and around the world.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "leisure"]}, {"q": "What were Thomas Chippendale, Clarice Cliff and Sir Terence Conran famous for designing?", "a": "Thomas Chippendale designed furniture in the 18th century, Clarice Cliff designed Art Deco ceramics, and Sir Terence Conran was a 20th-century interior designer.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "fashion"]}, {"q": "Name three leading British fashion designers of recent years.", "a": "Mary Quant, Alexander McQueen and Vivienne Westwood.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "fashion"]}, {"q": "Name three British writers who have won the Nobel Prize in Literature.", "a": "The novelist Sir William Golding, the poet Seamus Heaney, and the playwright Harold Pinter.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Which writer introduced James Bond?", "a": "Ian Fleming.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Which book was voted the country's best-loved novel in 2003?", "a": "The Lord of the Rings by JRR Tolkien.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "What is the Man Booker Prize and since when has it been awarded?", "a": "It is awarded annually for the best fiction novel written by an author from the Commonwealth, Ireland or Zimbabwe, and has been awarded since 1968. Past winners include Ian McEwan, Hilary Mantel and Julian Barnes.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Which novels did Jane Austen write, and what are her novels concerned with?", "a": "Her books include Pride and Prejudice and Sense and Sensibility; her novels are concerned with marriage and family relationships.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Which famous novels did Charles Dickens write, and which of his characters are referenced in everyday talk?", "a": "Oliver Twist and Great Expectations, among others. Characters referenced include Scrooge (a mean person) and Mr Micawber (always hopeful).", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Name the most famous books of Robert Louis Stevenson.", "a": "Treasure Island, Kidnapped and Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "What do Thomas Hardy's best-known novels focus on, and what are they?", "a": "They focus on rural society and include Far from the Madding Crowd and Jude the Obscure.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Who created Sherlock Holmes?", "a": "Sir Arthur Conan Doyle (1859–1930), a Scottish doctor and writer. Sherlock Holmes was one of the first fictional detectives.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Which satirical novels did Evelyn Waugh write, and which book is he perhaps best known for?", "a": "He wrote satirical novels including Decline and Fall and Scoop; he is perhaps best known for Brideshead Revisited.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "What is Sir Kingsley Amis's most well-known novel?", "a": "Lucky Jim. He was an English novelist and poet who wrote more than 20 novels.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "What often influenced Graham Greene's novels, and what did he write?", "a": "His religious beliefs. His novels include The Heart of the Matter, The Honorary Consul, Brighton Rock and Our Man in Havana.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "Who wrote the Harry Potter series?", "a": "J K Rowling (1965–). The series of children's books has enjoyed huge international success; she now writes fiction for adults as well.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "literature"]}, {"q": "What is Beowulf?", "a": "An Anglo-Saxon poem telling of its hero's battles against monsters; it is still translated into modern English.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Name two poems that survive from the Middle Ages.", "a": "Chaucer's Canterbury Tales and Sir Gawain and the Green Knight, about one of the knights at the court of King Arthur.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "How many lines must a sonnet have?", "a": "14 lines. Shakespeare wrote many sonnets as well as plays and some longer poems.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote Paradise Lost?", "a": "John Milton, one of the poets inspired by religious views as Protestant ideas spread.", "section": "4.2", "page": 48, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "What inspired the poems of Sir Walter Scott?", "a": "Scotland and the traditional stories and songs from the area on the borders of Scotland and England. He also wrote novels, many set in Scotland.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Name two poets inspired to write about their experiences in the First World War.", "a": "Wilfred Owen and Siegfried Sassoon.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Where are some of the best-known British poets buried or commemorated?", "a": "In Poet's Corner in Westminster Abbey.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote the poem beginning 'Oh to be in England now that April's there'?", "a": "Robert Browning (1812–89) — the poem is Home Thoughts from Abroad.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote 'She walks in beauty, like the night / Of cloudless climes and starry skies'?", "a": "Lord Byron (1788–1824) — the poem is She Walks in Beauty.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote 'I wander'd lonely as a cloud... A host of golden daffodils'?", "a": "William Wordsworth (1770–1850) — the poem is The Daffodils. Wordsworth was inspired by nature.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote 'Tyger! Tyger! Burning bright / In the forests of the night'?", "a": "William Blake (1757–1827) — the poem is The Tyger.", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "Who wrote Anthem for Doomed Youth ('What passing-bells for these who die as cattle?')?", "a": "Wilfred Owen (1893–1918).", "section": "4.2", "page": 49, "tags": ["arts", "poetry"]}, {"q": "What does Christmas Day celebrate and when is it?", "a": "Christmas Day, 25 December, celebrates the birth of Jesus Christ. It is a public holiday; many Christians go to church on Christmas Eve (24 December) or Christmas Day itself.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What is a traditional Christmas meal in the UK?", "a": "A special meal often including roast turkey, Christmas pudding and mince pies.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What is Boxing Day?", "a": "The day after Christmas Day, and a public holiday.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What does Easter mark, and when does it take place?", "a": "Easter takes place in March or April. It marks the death of Jesus Christ on Good Friday and his rising from the dead on Easter Sunday. Both Good Friday and Easter Monday are public holidays.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What is Lent and when does it begin?", "a": "The 40 days before Easter, when Christians reflect and prepare for Easter; many people give something up. Lent begins on Ash Wednesday, when Christians are marked with an ash cross on the forehead as a symbol of death and sorrow for sin.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What is the day before Lent starts called, and what do people traditionally eat?", "a": "Shrove Tuesday, or Pancake Day. People eat pancakes, traditionally made to use up foods such as eggs, fat and milk before fasting.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What do Easter eggs symbolise?", "a": "New life. They are chocolate eggs often given as presents at Easter, which is also celebrated by people who are not religious.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "When is Diwali, how long does it last, and who celebrates it?", "a": "Diwali normally falls in October or November and lasts for five days. It is celebrated by Hindus and Sikhs, celebrates the victory of good over evil and the gaining of knowledge, and is often called the Festival of Lights.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "Which city has a famous celebration of Diwali?", "a": "Leicester.", "section": "4.3", "page": 51, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "What does Hannukah remember, and how is it celebrated?", "a": "It remembers the Jews' struggle for religious freedom. It falls in November or December and is celebrated for eight days; each day a candle is lit on a menorah (a stand of eight candles), remembering the story where oil that should have lasted only a day lasted eight.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "What does Eid al-Fitr celebrate?", "a": "The end of Ramadan, when Muslims have fasted for a month. They thank Allah for giving them the strength to complete the fast. The date changes every year; Muslims attend special services and meals.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "What does Eid ul Adha remember?", "a": "That the prophet Ibrahim was willing to sacrifice his son when God ordered him to. It reminds Muslims of their own commitment to God; many sacrifice an animal to eat (in Britain this must be done in a slaughterhouse).", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "What does Vaisakhi celebrate and when is it?", "a": "Vaisakhi (also spelled Baisakhi) is a Sikh festival celebrating the founding of the Sikh community known as the Khalsa. It is celebrated on 14 April each year with parades, dancing and singing.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals", "religion"]}, {"q": "What is 31 December called in Scotland, and what is special about 2 January there?", "a": "31 December is called Hogmanay, and 2 January is also a public holiday in Scotland. For some Scottish people, Hogmanay is a bigger holiday than Christmas.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "When is Valentine's Day and what happens?", "a": "14 February — lovers exchange cards and gifts, and sometimes people send anonymous cards to someone they secretly admire.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "Until what time do people play jokes on April Fool's Day?", "a": "Until midday, on 1 April. Television and newspapers often have stories that are April Fool jokes.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "When is Mothering Sunday (Mother's Day)?", "a": "The Sunday three weeks before Easter. Children send cards or buy gifts for their mothers.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "When is Father's Day?", "a": "The third Sunday in June. Children send cards or buy gifts for their fathers.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What are the origins and customs of Halloween?", "a": "Halloween, 31 October, is an ancient festival with roots in the pagan festival to mark the beginning of winter. Young people dress up in frightening costumes to play 'trick or treat', and many people carve lanterns out of pumpkins with a candle inside.", "section": "4.3", "page": 52, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What event is the origin of Bonfire Night (5 November)?", "a": "In 1605, a group of Catholics led by Guy Fawkes failed in their plan to kill the Protestant king with a bomb in the Houses of Parliament. People in Great Britain set off fireworks at home or in special displays.", "section": "4.3", "page": 53, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What does Remembrance Day commemorate and how is it observed?", "a": "Remembrance Day, 11 November, commemorates those who died fighting for the UK and its allies; originally it commemorated the dead of the First World War, which ended on 11 November 1918. People wear poppies; at 11.00 am there is a two-minute silence and wreaths are laid at the Cenotaph in Whitehall, London.", "section": "4.3", "page": 53, "tags": ["traditions", "festivals"]}, {"q": "What is a bank holiday?", "a": "A public holiday, of no religious significance, when banks and many other businesses are closed for the day. Bank holidays fall at the beginning of May, in late May or early June, and in August.", "section": "4.3", "page": 53, "tags": ["traditions"]}, {"q": "Which additional public holiday is observed in Northern Ireland in July?", "a": "The anniversary of the Battle of the Boyne.", "section": "4.3", "page": 53, "tags": ["traditions"]}, {"q": "What is 'an allotment'?", "a": "Additional land that some people rent, where they grow fruit and vegetables.", "section": "4.4", "page": 54, "tags": ["leisure"]}, {"q": "Name famous gardens to visit in each country of the UK.", "a": "Kew Gardens, Sissinghurst and Hidcote in England; Crathes Castle and Inveraray Castle in Scotland; Bodnant Garden in Wales; and Mount Stewart in Northern Ireland.", "section": "4.4", "page": 54, "tags": ["leisure", "places"]}, {"q": "What food is traditionally associated with England?", "a": "Roast beef, served with potatoes, vegetables, Yorkshire puddings (batter that is baked in the oven) and other accompaniments. Fish and chips are also popular.", "section": "4.4", "page": 55, "tags": ["leisure", "food"]}, {"q": "What are Welsh cakes?", "a": "A traditional Welsh snack made from flour, dried fruits and spices, served either hot or cold.", "section": "4.4", "page": 55, "tags": ["leisure", "food"]}, {"q": "What is haggis, the food traditionally associated with Scotland?", "a": "A sheep's stomach stuffed with offal, suet, onions and oatmeal.", "section": "4.4", "page": 55, "tags": ["leisure", "food"]}, {"q": "What is an Ulster fry?", "a": "The traditional food of Northern Ireland — a fried meal with bacon, eggs, sausage, black pudding, white pudding, tomatoes, mushrooms, soda bread and potato bread.", "section": "4.4", "page": 55, "tags": ["leisure", "food"]}, {"q": "When were films first shown publicly in the UK?", "a": "In 1896. From the beginning, British film makers became famous for clever special effects, and this continues to be an area of British expertise.", "section": "4.4", "page": 56, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "What was Sir Charles (Charlie) Chaplin famous for?", "a": "He became famous in silent movies for his tramp character, and was one of many British actors to make a career in Hollywood.", "section": "4.4", "page": 56, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Name two eminent British film directors of the 1930s.", "a": "Sir Alexander Korda and Sir Alfred Hitchcock. Hitchcock later left for Hollywood and remained an important film director until his death in 1980.", "section": "4.4", "page": 56, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Which two film franchises, the highest-grossing of all time, were produced in the UK?", "a": "Harry Potter and James Bond.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Which studio has a claim to being the oldest continuously working film studio facility in the world?", "a": "Ealing Studios.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "How many Oscars has the animator Nick Park won?", "a": "Four Oscars for his animated films, including three for films featuring Wallace and Gromit.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "What are the British equivalent of the Oscars?", "a": "The annual British Academy Film Awards, hosted by the British Academy of Film and Television Arts (BAFTA).", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Who directed Lawrence of Arabia (1962) and Brief Encounter (1945)?", "a": "David Lean directed both films.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Who directed The 39 Steps (1935)?", "a": "Alfred Hitchcock.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "film"]}, {"q": "Name some famous British comedies of the 1950s and 1960s.", "a": "Passport to Pimlico, The Ladykillers and, later, the Carry On films.", "section": "4.4", "page": 56, "tags": ["leisure", "film", "comedy"]}, {"q": "What was the most famous satirical magazine of the 19th century, and when was it first published?", "a": "Punch, published for the first time in the 1840s. Today, magazines such as Private Eye continue the tradition of satire.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "comedy"]}, {"q": "Which show introduced a new type of progressive comedy in 1969?", "a": "Monty Python's Flying Circus.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "comedy"]}, {"q": "Name two popular regular soap operas on British television.", "a": "Coronation Street and EastEnders.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "tv"]}, {"q": "What is the fine for watching TV without a TV licence?", "a": "Up to £1,000. Everyone in the UK with a TV, computer or other medium used for watching TV must have a licence; one licence covers all equipment in one home (except separate tenancies in a shared house).", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "tv"]}, {"q": "Who can get a free TV licence, and who gets a discount?", "a": "People over 75 can apply for a free TV licence, and blind people can get a 50% discount.", "section": "4.4", "page": 57, "tags": ["leisure", "tv"]}, {"q": "What is the money from TV licences used for?", "a": "It pays for the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC), a British public service broadcaster. The BBC is the largest broadcaster in the world and the only wholly state-funded media organisation independent of government.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure", "tv"]}, {"q": "At what age can you buy alcohol in a pub or night club?", "a": "18 or over. At 16, people can drink wine or beer with a meal in a hotel or restaurant (including eating areas in pubs) as long as they are with someone over 18.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure", "pubs"]}, {"q": "What time do pubs usually open, and who decides the opening hours?", "a": "Pubs are usually open during the day from 11.00 am (12 noon on Sundays). The licensee decides the hours that the pub or night club is open.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure", "pubs"]}, {"q": "What are the traditional pub games?", "a": "Pool and darts. Pub quizzes are also popular.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure", "pubs"]}, {"q": "How old must you be to go into betting shops or gambling clubs?", "a": "18. There is also a National Lottery with draws every week; people under 18 are not allowed to participate.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure"]}, {"q": "What must all dogs in public places wear?", "a": "A collar showing the name and address of the owner. The owner is responsible for keeping the dog under control and for cleaning up after the animal in a public place.", "section": "4.4", "page": 58, "tags": ["leisure", "pets"]}, {"q": "How many national parks are there, and where?", "a": "There are 15 national parks in England, Wales and Scotland. They are areas of protected countryside that everyone can visit, and where people live, work and look after the landscape.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "When was the National Trust founded and by whom?", "a": "In 1895, by three volunteers. There are now more than 61,000 volunteers. The National Trust (England, Wales and Northern Ireland) and the National Trust for Scotland are charities that preserve important buildings, coastline and countryside.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is Big Ben?", "a": "The nickname for the great bell of the clock at the Houses of Parliament in London (many people call the clock Big Ben as well). The clock is over 150 years old.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "Why was the clock tower at the Houses of Parliament named 'Elizabeth Tower'?", "a": "In honour of Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee in 2012.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "Where is the Eden Project and what does it contain?", "a": "In Cornwall, in the south west of England. Its biomes, which are like giant greenhouses, house plants from all over the world. It is also a charity running environmental and social projects internationally.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "Who looks after Edinburgh Castle?", "a": "Historic Scotland, a Scottish government agency. The Castle is a dominant feature of the Edinburgh skyline and dates back to the early Middle Ages.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is the Giant's Causeway and where is it?", "a": "A land formation of columns made from volcanic lava, located on the north-east coast of Northern Ireland. It was formed about 50 million years ago, and there are many legends about it.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is Loch Lomond famous for?", "a": "It is the largest expanse of fresh water in mainland Britain, and probably the best-known part of Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park, which covers 720 square miles (1,865 square kilometres) in the west of Scotland.", "section": "4.5", "page": 59, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is the London Eye and why was it built?", "a": "A Ferris wheel, 443 feet (135 metres) tall, situated on the southern bank of the River Thames. It was originally built as part of the UK's celebration of the new millennium and remains part of New Year celebrations.", "section": "4.5", "page": 60, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is the most well-known landmark of Snowdonia?", "a": "Snowdon, the highest mountain in Wales. Snowdonia is a national park in North Wales covering 838 square miles (2,170 square kilometres).", "section": "4.5", "page": 60, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "Who first built the Tower of London, and who gives tours there?", "a": "It was first built by William the Conqueror after he became king in 1066. Tours are given by the Yeoman Warders, also known as Beefeaters; people can also see the Crown Jewels there.", "section": "4.5", "page": 60, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is England's largest national park?", "a": "The Lake District, covering 885 square miles (2,292 square kilometres). It is famous for its lakes and mountains and popular with climbers, walkers and sailors.", "section": "4.5", "page": 61, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "What is the biggest stretch of water in the Lake District?", "a": "Windermere.", "section": "4.5", "page": 61, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "Which view was voted Britain's favourite by television viewers in 2007?", "a": "Wastwater, in the Lake District.", "section": "4.5", "page": 61, "tags": ["places"]}, {"q": "In the 2009 Citizenship Survey, what percentage of people identified themselves as Christian?", "a": "70%.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion", "population"]}, {"q": "In the 2009 Citizenship Survey, what proportions identified as Muslim, Hindu, Sikh, and Jewish or Buddhist?", "a": "Muslim 4%, Hindu 2%, Sikh 1%, Jewish or Buddhist both less than 0.5%; 2% of people followed another religion.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion", "population"]}, {"q": "In the 2009 Citizenship Survey, what percentage of people said they had no religion?", "a": "21%. Everyone has the legal right to choose their religion, or to choose not to practise a religion.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion", "population"]}, {"q": "What are the places of worship for Muslims, Hindus, Jews, Sikhs and Buddhists called?", "a": "Islamic mosques, Hindu temples, Jewish synagogues, Sikh gurdwaras and Buddhist temples.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What is the official Church of the state in England, and what is it called elsewhere?", "a": "The Church of England — called the Anglican Church in other countries and the Episcopal Church in Scotland and the United States. It is a Protestant Church that has existed since the Reformation in the 1530s.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "Who is the head of the Church of England, and who is its spiritual leader?", "a": "The monarch is the head; the spiritual leader is the Archbishop of Canterbury.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "Who usually chooses the Archbishop of Canterbury and other senior church officials?", "a": "The monarch has the right to select them, but usually the choice is made by the Prime Minister and a committee appointed by the Church. Several Church of England bishops sit in the House of Lords.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "What is the national Church of Scotland and how is it governed?", "a": "The Church of Scotland, a Presbyterian Church governed by ministers and elders. The chairperson of its General Assembly is the Moderator, appointed for one year only, who often speaks on behalf of that Church.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "Is there an established Church in Wales or Northern Ireland?", "a": "No — there is no established Church in Wales or Northern Ireland.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "Name other Protestant Christian groups in the UK, and the biggest other denomination of Christianity.", "a": "Baptists, Methodists, Presbyterians and Quakers are other Protestant groups; the biggest other denomination is Roman Catholic.", "section": "4.6", "page": 62, "tags": ["religion"]}, {"q": "When is St David's Day and whose patron saint is he?", "a": "1 March — St David is the patron saint of Wales.", "section": "4.6", "page": 63, "tags": ["religion", "saints", "traditions"]}, {"q": "When is St Patrick's Day and whose patron saint is he?", "a": "17 March — St Patrick is the patron saint of Northern Ireland.", "section": "4.6", "page": 63, "tags": ["religion", "saints", "traditions"]}, {"q": "When is St George's Day and whose patron saint is he?", "a": "23 April — St George is the patron saint of England.", "section": "4.6", "page": 63, "tags": ["religion", "saints", "traditions"]}, {"q": "When is St Andrew's Day and whose patron saint is he?", "a": "30 November — St Andrew is the patron saint of Scotland.", "section": "4.6", "page": 63, "tags": ["religion", "saints", "traditions"]}, {"q": "Which UK countries have their patron saint's day as an official holiday?", "a": "Only Scotland and Northern Ireland (although in Scotland not all businesses and offices will close). In England and Wales the days are no longer public holidays, but parades and small festivals are still held.", "section": "4.6", "page": 63, "tags": ["religion", "saints", "traditions"]}, {"q": "Name two major stadiums where sporting events take place in the UK.", "a": "Wembley Stadium in London and the Millennium Stadium in Cardiff.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Which famous sports began in Britain?", "a": "Cricket, football, lawn tennis, golf and rugby.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "In which years has the UK hosted the Olympic Games?", "a": "On three occasions: 1908, 1948 and 2012.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where was the main Olympic site for the 2012 Games, and how did the British team perform?", "a": "In Stratford, East London. The British team was very successful, finishing third in the medal table.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where do the Paralympic Games have their origin?", "a": "In the work of Dr Sir Ludwig Guttman, a German refugee, at the Stoke Mandeville hospital in Buckinghamshire. He developed new treatments for people with spinal injuries and encouraged patients to take part in exercise and sport.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Who was the first man in the world to run a mile in under four minutes?", "a": "Sir Roger Bannister, in 1954.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "How many times did Sir Jackie Stewart win the Formula 1 world championship?", "a": "Three times. He is a Scottish former racing driver.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Who captained the English football team that won the World Cup in 1966?", "a": "Bobby Moore (1941–93).", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is Sir Ian Botham known for?", "a": "He captained the English cricket team and holds a number of English Test cricket records, both for batting and for bowling.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean achieve?", "a": "They won gold medals for ice dancing at the Olympic Games in 1984 and in four consecutive world championships.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Sir Steve Redgrave achieve?", "a": "He won gold medals in rowing in five consecutive Olympic Games and is one of Britain's greatest Olympians.", "section": "4.7", "page": 64, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Baroness Tanni-Grey Thompson achieve?", "a": "An athlete who uses a wheelchair, she won 16 Paralympic medals, including 11 gold medals, over five Paralympic Games; won the London Marathon six times; and broke a total of 30 world records.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Dame Kelly Holmes win at the 2004 Olympic Games?", "a": "Two gold medals for running. She has held a number of British and European records.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Dame Ellen MacArthur achieve in 2004?", "a": "The yachtswoman became the fastest person to sail around the world singlehanded.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "How many Olympic medals and world championship titles has the cyclist Sir Chris Hoy won?", "a": "Six gold and one silver Olympic medals, and 11 world championship titles. He is Scottish.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What has the Paralympian David Weir achieved?", "a": "He uses a wheelchair and has won six gold medals over two Paralympic Games, and has won the London Marathon six times.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Who was the first Briton to win the Tour de France?", "a": "Bradley Wiggins, in 2012. He has won seven Olympic medals, including golds in the 2004, 2008 and 2012 Olympic Games.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Mo Farah win at the 2012 Olympics?", "a": "Gold medals in the 5,000 and 10,000 metres. Born in Somalia, he is the first Briton to win the Olympic gold medal in the 10,000 metres.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Which event did Jessica Ennis win gold in at the 2012 Olympics?", "a": "The heptathlon, which includes seven different track and field events. She also holds a number of British athletics records.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What did Andy Murray achieve in 2012?", "a": "He won the men's singles in the US Open — the first British man to win a singles title in a Grand Slam tournament since 1936. He also won Olympic gold and silver medals and was runner-up in the men's singles at Wimbledon that year.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What has Ellie Simmonds achieved?", "a": "She won gold medals for swimming at the 2008 and 2012 Paralympic Games, holds a number of world records, and was the youngest member of the British team at the 2008 Games.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is the most famous cricket competition, and who plays in it?", "a": "The Ashes, a series of Test matches played between England and Australia. Cricket games can last up to five days but still result in a draw.", "section": "4.7", "page": 65, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is the UK's most popular sport?", "a": "Football. The first professional football clubs were formed in the late 19th century.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What was England's only international football tournament victory?", "a": "The World Cup of 1966, hosted in the UK.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What are the two different types of rugby?", "a": "Union and league, which have different rules. Rugby originated in England in the early 19th century. In rugby, Northern Ireland plays with the Irish Republic.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is the most famous rugby union competition, and which countries take part?", "a": "The Six Nations Championship, between England, Ireland, Scotland, Wales, France and Italy. The Super League is the most well-known rugby league (club) competition.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Name three famous horse-racing events in the UK.", "a": "Royal Ascot, a five-day race meeting in Berkshire attended by members of the Royal Family; the Grand National at Aintree near Liverpool; and the Scottish Grand National at Ayr.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where is the National Horseracing Museum?", "a": "In Newmarket, Suffolk. Horse racing in Britain has evidence of events as far back as Roman times and a long association with royalty.", "section": "4.7", "page": 66, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where can the modern game of golf be traced back to, and what is known as the home of golf?", "a": "It can be traced back to 15th century Scotland; St Andrews in Scotland is known as the home of golf.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is special about The Open Championship in golf?", "a": "It is the only 'Major' tournament held outside the United States, and is hosted by a different golf course every year.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where and when was the first tennis club founded?", "a": "In Leamington Spa in 1872. Modern tennis evolved in England in the late 19th century.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What is special about the Wimbledon Championships?", "a": "It is the oldest tennis tournament in the world and the only 'Grand Slam' event played on grass. It takes place each year at the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Who was the first person to sail single-handed around the world, and when?", "a": "Sir Francis Chichester, in 1966/67. Two years later, Sir Robin Knox-Johnston became the first person to do this without stopping.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Where is the most famous sailing event in the UK held?", "a": "At Cowes on the Isle of Wight.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "Which universities compete in a popular yearly rowing race on the Thames?", "a": "Oxford and Cambridge Universities.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "When did motor-car racing start in the UK, and name recent British Formula 1 World Championship winners.", "a": "Motor-car racing in the UK started in 1902. Recent British winners include Damon Hill, Lewis Hamilton and Jensen Button. A Formula 1 Grand Prix event is held in the UK each year.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "How many ski centres are there in Scotland, and where is Europe's longest dry ski slope?", "a": "There are five ski centres in Scotland, and Europe's longest dry ski slope is near Edinburgh.", "section": "4.7", "page": 67, "tags": ["sport"]}, {"q": "What proportion of the UK population has a parent or grandparent born outside the UK?", "a": "Nearly 10%, due to post-war immigration.", "section": "4.8", "page": 68, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "What is the longest distance on the UK mainland, and between which points?", "a": "About 870 miles (approximately 1,400 kilometres), from John O'Groats on the north coast of Scotland to Land's End in the south-west corner of England.", "section": "4.8", "page": 68, "tags": ["places", "population"]}, {"q": "What is the capital city of the UK?", "a": "London.", "section": "4.8", "page": 68, "tags": ["cities"]}, {"q": "What is the capital city of Scotland?", "a": "Edinburgh.", "section": "4.8", "page": 68, "tags": ["cities"]}, {"q": "What is the capital city of Wales?", "a": "Cardiff.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["cities"]}, {"q": "What is the capital city of Northern Ireland?", "a": "Belfast.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["cities"]}, {"q": "What is the currency of the UK, and how many pence are in a pound?", "a": "The pound sterling (symbol £); there are 100 pence in a pound.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["currency"]}, {"q": "What are the denominations of UK coins and notes?", "a": "Coins: 1p, 2p, 5p, 10p, 20p, 50p, £1 and £2. Notes: £5, £10, £20, £50.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["currency"]}, {"q": "Are Northern Ireland and Scotland banknotes valid in the rest of the UK?", "a": "Yes — they are valid everywhere in the UK. However, shops and businesses do not have to accept them.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["currency"]}, {"q": "What languages other than English are spoken in parts of the UK?", "a": "In Wales, many people speak Welsh — a completely different language from English, taught in schools and universities. In Scotland, Gaelic is spoken in some parts of the Highlands and Islands, and in Northern Ireland some people speak Irish Gaelic.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["languages"]}, {"q": "What was the population of the UK in 1901 and in 1951?", "a": "40 million in 1901, and 50 million in 1951.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "What was the UK population in 2010, and what is it estimated at for 2022?", "a": "Just over 62 million in 2010, and an estimated 67.6 million in 2022 (source: National Statistics).", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "What factors have played a part in the UK's faster recent population growth?", "a": "Migration into the UK and longer life expectancy.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "How is the UK population distributed across the four nations?", "a": "England more or less consistently makes up 84% of the total population, Wales around 5%, Scotland just over 8% and Northern Ireland less than 3%.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "Why are people in the UK living longer than ever before, and what impact does this have?", "a": "Due to improved living standards and better health care. There are now a record number of people aged 85 and over, which has an impact on the cost of pensions and health care.", "section": "4.8", "page": 69, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "What is the most common ethnic description chosen in UK surveys?", "a": "White, which includes people of European, Australian, Canadian, New Zealand and American descent. Other significant groups are those of Asian, black and mixed descent.", "section": "4.8", "page": 70, "tags": ["population"]}, {"q": "What equal rights do men and women have in the UK?", "a": "It is a legal requirement that men and women should not be discriminated against because of their gender or because they are, or are not, married. They have equal rights to work, own property, marry and divorce; if married, both parents are equally responsible for their children.", "section": "4.8", "page": 70, "tags": ["population", "equality"]}, {"q": "What proportion of the UK workforce do women make up?", "a": "About half. On average, girls leave school with better qualifications than boys, and more women than men study at university.", "section": "4.8", "page": 70, "tags": ["population", "equality"]}]}, {"chapter": 5, "title": "The UK government, the law and your role", "sections": [{"id": "5.1", "title": "Chapter 5: The UK government, the law and your role", "summary": "- Introduces the chapter: how the UK is governed, the **Queen's role in government** and her powers, how people are appointed to the **two Houses of Parliament**, specific roles such as the **Speaker** and **cabinet**, and your rights to **vote** and **stand for election**.\n- Everyone should understand the **devolved administrations** — pay particular attention if taking the test in **Scotland, Wales or Northern Ireland**.\n- The UK's international role is explained through the **Commonwealth, EU** and others — focus on the differences between these bodies and their member countries.\n- Also covers common laws, **fundamental rights**, policing and the **courts** (know the differences between courts and the offences they deal with), plus **taxation, driving and community activity**.\n- The UK is a **parliamentary democracy** with the **monarch as head of state**.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.2", "title": "The development of British democracy", "summary": "- **Democracy**: a system of government where the **whole adult population gets a say**, either by direct voting or by choosing representatives to make decisions on their behalf.\n- At the turn of the **19th century**, Britain was not a democracy as we know it today: only a small group could vote — **men over 21 who owned a certain amount of property**.\n- The **franchise** (the number of people who had the right to vote) grew over the 19th century; political parties began to involve ordinary men and women as members.\n- In the **1830s and 1840s** the **Chartists** campaigned for reform. They wanted **six changes**:\n  - for every man to have the vote\n  - elections every year\n  - for all regions to be equal in the electoral system\n  - secret ballots\n  - for any man to be able to stand as an MP\n  - for MPs to be paid.\n- At the time the campaign was generally seen as a **failure**, but by **1918** most of these reforms had been adopted.\n- Voting rights timeline: **1918** — women over **30**; **1928** — men and women over **21**; **1969** — voting age reduced to **18** for men and women.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.3", "title": "The British constitution", "summary": "- A **constitution** is a set of principles by which a country is governed, including the institutions responsible for running the country and how their power is kept in check; it also includes **laws and conventions**.\n- The British constitution is **not written down in any single document** — it is '**unwritten**'. This is mainly because the UK, unlike **America or France**, has never had a revolution which led permanently to a totally new system of government. Some people believe there should be a single document; others believe an unwritten constitution allows more flexibility and better government.\n- **Constitutional institutions**: the **monarchy**, **Parliament** (House of Commons and House of Lords), the **Prime Minister**, the **cabinet**, the **judiciary** (courts), the **police**, the **civil service**, and **local government**; plus **devolved governments** in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland with power to legislate on certain issues.\n- **The monarch**: head of state of the UK (and head of state for many Commonwealth countries). The UK is a **constitutional monarchy** — the king or queen does not rule but **appoints the government** chosen by the people in a democratic election, inviting the leader of the party with the **largest number of MPs** (or a coalition leader) to become Prime Minister. The monarch has regular meetings with the PM and can **advise, warn and encourage**, but decisions are made by the PM and cabinet.\n- **Queen Elizabeth II** reigned from her father's death in **1952**; celebrated her **Diamond Jubilee (60 years)** in **2012**; died **8 September 2022**; was married to **Prince Philip**. Her eldest son **Charles (King Charles III)** is the current ruling monarch (sovereign since **2022**). **Prince Edward** became **Duke of Edinburgh** in 2023, a title formerly held by King Charles III.\n- Heir apparent: **William, Prince of Wales** (the title for the heir apparent). Next in line, in order of birth: **Prince George, Princess Charlotte, Prince Louis**.\n- Monarch's roles: ceremonial **opening of the new parliamentary session** each year (speech summarising the government's policies for the year ahead); **all Acts of Parliament are made in the Majesty's name**; represents the UK to the world (receives foreign ambassadors and high commissioners, entertains visiting heads of state, makes state visits); provides **stability, continuity** and a focus for **national identity and pride**.\n- **National anthem**: '**God Save the King (or Queen)**', played at important national occasions and events attended by the King (or Queen) or Royal Family.\n- New citizens **swear or affirm loyalty to the King** at the citizenship ceremony (**oath** or **affirmation of allegiance** to 'His Majesty King Charles the Third, his Heirs and Successors, according to law').\n- **System of government**: parliamentary democracy. The UK is divided into **parliamentary constituencies**; voters in each elect their **MP** at a **General Election**; elected MPs form the **House of Commons**; the party with the majority of MPs forms the government; without a majority, two parties can form a **coalition**.\n- **House of Commons**: the more important chamber because its members are **democratically elected**. The PM and almost all cabinet members are MPs. MPs: **represent everyone in their constituency**, help **create new laws**, **scrutinise and comment** on what the government is doing, and **debate important national issues**.\n- **House of Lords**: members are **peers** — not elected, no constituency. Until **1958** all peers were **hereditary**, **senior judges**, or **bishops of the Church of England**. Since **1958** the PM can nominate **life peers** (appointed by the monarch on the advice of the PM; also nominated by other party leaders or an independent **Appointments Commission** for non-party peers). Since **1999** hereditary peers lost the automatic right to attend and now **elect a few of their number**. The Lords is normally **more independent of the government**; it suggests amendments, proposes new laws, **checks laws passed by the Commons**, and holds the government to account. The Commons can **overrule the Lords**, but rarely does.\n- **The Speaker**: chairs debates; **chief Officer of the House of Commons**; **neutral** (no party) though still an MP with a constituency; chosen by other MPs in a **secret ballot**; keeps order, guarantees the **opposition** time to debate issues it chooses, and represents Parliament on ceremonial occasions.\n- **Elections**: General Election **at least every five years**; a **by-election** is held if an MP dies or resigns; MPs elected by '**first past the post**' (candidate with most votes in each constituency wins). **European Parliament** elections: every **five years**, members called **MEPs**, elected by **proportional representation** (seats allocated in proportion to total votes won).\n- **Contacting elected members**: details from your local library and **www.parliament.uk**; MPs, Assembly members, MSPs and MEPs listed in **The Phone Book** (BT) and **Yellow Pages**; contact by letter or telephone at their constituency Office or the House of Commons, Westminster, London **SW1A 0AA**; many hold local '**surgeries**' (often advertised in the local newspaper).", "checkUnderstand": ["How democracy has developed in the UK", "What a constitution is and how the UK's constitution is different from those of most other countries", "The role of the monarch", "The role of the House of Commons and House of Lords", "What the Speaker does", "How the UK elects MPs and MEPs"]}, {"id": "5.4", "title": "Fundamental principles", "summary": "- Britain has a long history of respecting individual rights and essential freedoms, rooted in **Magna Carta**, the **Habeas Corpus Act** and the **Bill of Rights of 1689**.\n- British diplomats and lawyers helped draft the **European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms**; the UK was one of the **first countries to sign** it in **1950**.\n- ECHR principles include: **right to life**, **prohibition of torture**, **prohibition of slavery and forced labour**, **right to liberty and security**, **right to a fair trial**, **freedom of thought, conscience and religion**, **freedom of expression (speech)**.\n- The **Human Rights Act 1998** incorporated the ECHR into UK law — the government, public bodies and courts must follow the Convention's principles.\n- **Equal opportunities**: UK laws ensure people are not treated unfairly because of **age, disability, sex, pregnancy and maternity, race, religion or belief, sexuality or marital status**. Help with discrimination: **Citizens Advice Bureau**; England and Wales — **Equality and Human Rights Commission**; Scotland — EHRC in Scotland and **Scottish Human Rights Commission**; Northern Ireland — **Equality Commission for Northern Ireland** and **Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission**.\n- **Domestic violence**: a serious crime — anyone violent towards a partner (man or woman, married or living together) can be **prosecuted**; any man who forces a woman to have sex, **including her husband**, can be charged with **rape**. Help: solicitor, Citizens Advice Bureau, **refuges or shelters**, and the 24-hour **National Domestic Violence Freephone Helpline 0808 2000 247**; the police can help find a safe place to stay.\n- **Female genital mutilation (FGM)** (also known as cutting or female circumcision) is **illegal in the UK**; practising FGM or **taking a girl or woman abroad for FGM** is a criminal offence.\n- **Forced marriage**: a marriage should be entered into with the **full and free consent** of both people. **Arranged marriages** (both parties agree) are acceptable; **forcing another person to marry is a criminal offence**.\n- **Forced Marriage Protection Orders**: introduced in **2008** for England, Wales and Northern Ireland under the **Forced Marriage (Civil Protection) Act 2007**; similar orders in **Scotland in November 2011**. A potential victim, or someone acting for them, can apply; breaching an order can mean up to **two years in jail for contempt of court**.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.4.1", "title": "Taxation", "summary": "- **Income tax** is paid on: **wages** from paid employment, **profits from self-employment**, **taxable benefits**, **pensions**, and income from **property, savings and dividends**.\n- Income tax pays for government services such as **roads, education, police and the armed forces**.\n- **HM Revenue & Customs (HMRC)** is the government department that collects taxes. For most people, tax is taken automatically from employment income by the employer — '**Pay As You Earn' (PAYE)**. Self-employed people pay through '**self-assessment**', which includes completing a **tax return**. If HMRC sends you a tax return, complete and return it as soon as you have the necessary information.\n- **National Insurance**: almost everybody in paid work, **including self-employed people**, must pay **National Insurance Contributions**. The money pays for **state benefits and services such as the state retirement pension and the National Health Service (NHS)**.\n- Employees have NICs **deducted by their employer**; the self-employed pay their own. Not paying enough NICs means you cannot receive certain **contributory benefits** such as **Jobseeker's Allowance** or a **full state retirement pension**; some workers (e.g. part-time) may not qualify for statutory payments such as **maternity pay** if they do not earn enough.\n- **National Insurance number**: a unique personal account number ensuring your contributions and tax are properly recorded. All young people in the UK are sent one **just before their 16th birthday**.\n- A non-UK national looking for work, starting work or setting up as self-employed needs an NI number, but **you can start work without one**. Telephone the **Department for Work and Pensions (DWP)** to arrange one; you may be required to attend an **interview** with documents proving identity and permission to work. An NI number **does not on its own prove the right to work** in the UK.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.4.2", "title": "Driving", "summary": "- You must be at least **17 years old** to drive a **car or motor cycle** and must have a **driving licence** to drive on public roads. You must be at least **16** to ride a **moped**; other age requirements and special tests apply for large vehicles.\n- To get a UK licence you must pass a **driving test** (knowledge and practical skills). First apply for a **provisional driving licence** and find a driving instructor, then pass: a **driving theory test** (multiple choice theory test plus a **hazard perception test**) and a **practical driving test**.\n- Licences are valid until age **70**; after that, valid **three years at a time**.\n- In **Northern Ireland**, a newly qualified driver must display an '**R**' plate (**restricted driver**) for **one year** after passing the test.\n- Licence from the **EU, Iceland, Liechtenstein or Norway**: you can drive in the UK for **as long as your licence is valid**. Licence from **any other country**: usable for **up to 12 months**, after which you must get a **UK full driving licence**.\n- If resident in the UK, your car or motor cycle must be **registered at the DVLA** (Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency). You must pay an **annual road tax** and display the **tax disc** on the windscreen, and have valid **motor insurance** — driving without insurance is a **serious criminal offence**.\n- Vehicles **over three years old** must take a **Ministry of Transport (MOT) test every year**; it is an offence not to have an MOT certificate for such a vehicle.", "checkUnderstand": ["The fundamental principles of UK law", "That domestic violence, FGM and forced marriage are illegal in the UK", "The system of income tax and National Insurance", "The requirements for driving a car"]}, {"id": "5.5", "title": "Respecting the law", "summary": "- One of the most important responsibilities of all UK residents is to **know and obey the law**. All residents, regardless of background, must comply with the law; some things allowed in other legal systems are not acceptable in the UK. Those who do not respect the law should not expect to be allowed to become **permanent residents**.\n- **Equal treatment under the law**: the law applies in the same way to everyone, no matter who they are or where they are from.\n- **Criminal law** relates to crimes, usually investigated by the **police** or another authority such as a **council**, and punished by the **courts**. **Civil law** is used to settle **disputes between individuals or groups**.\n- **Examples of criminal laws**:\n  - **Carrying a weapon** of any kind, even for self-defence (gun, knife, or anything made or adapted to cause injury)\n  - **Drugs**: selling or buying drugs such as heroin, cocaine, ecstasy and cannabis\n  - **Racial crime**: causing harassment, alarm or distress because of religion or ethnic origin\n  - **Selling tobacco** to anyone under **18**\n  - **Smoking in public places**: illegal in nearly every enclosed public place (signs displayed)\n  - **Buying alcohol**: illegal to sell alcohol to anyone under **18** or buy alcohol for people under 18 — exception: people aged **16 or over can drink alcohol with a meal in a hotel or restaurant**\n  - **Drinking in public**: some places have **alcohol-free zones**; police can confiscate alcohol or move young people on; you can be fined or arrested.\n  - Many other crimes apply in most countries, e.g. murder, theft and assault.\n- **Examples of civil laws**: **housing law** (landlord/tenant disputes over repairs and eviction), **consumer rights** (faulty goods or services), **employment law** (wages, unfair dismissal, workplace discrimination), **debt**.\n- **The police**: their job is to **protect life and property**, **prevent disturbances (keeping the peace)**, and **prevent and detect crime**. Police forces are headed by **Chief Constables** and are **independent of the government**.\n- **Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs)**: elected by the public in **November 2012** in **England and Wales** — directly elected individuals responsible for the delivery of an efficient and effective police force reflecting local needs; they **set local police priorities and the local policing budget** and **appoint the Chief Constable**.\n- Police Officers must obey the law and must not misuse authority, make false statements, be rude or abusive, or commit racial discrimination; corrupt Officers are severely punished. **Police community support Officers** support police Officers — usually patrol the streets, work with the public, and support Officers at crime scenes and major events.\n- Everyone is expected to **help the police prevent and detect crimes**. If arrested, you will be told the reason and can **seek legal advice**.\n- **Complaints** about the police: at a police station, in writing to the **Chief Constable**, or to an independent body — the **Independent Police Complaints Commission** (England and Wales), the **Police Complaints Commissioner for Scotland**, or the **Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland**.\n- **Terrorism and extremism**: the most serious terrorist threat is from **Al Qa'ida, its affiliates and like-minded organisations**; there are also threats such as **Northern Ireland-related terrorism**. Terrorist groups attract very low levels of public support. **Extremism** is vocal or active opposition to fundamental British values (including religious and far-right extremism). If someone tries to persuade you to join an extremist or terrorist cause, **notify your local police force**.", "checkUnderstand": ["The difference between civil and criminal law and some examples of each", "The duties of the police", "The possible terrorist threats facing the UK"]}, {"id": "5.5.1", "title": "The role of the courts", "summary": "- **The judiciary**: judges interpret the law and ensure trials are conducted fairly; the **government cannot interfere**. If judges find government actions illegal, the government must **change its policies or ask Parliament to change the law**. If a public body is not respecting someone's legal rights, judges can order it to change its practices and/or pay compensation. Judges also decide disputes between members of the public or organisations (contracts, property, employment rights, accidents).\n- **Criminal courts** differ between England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland:\n  - **Minor cases**: **Magistrates' Court** in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; **Justice of the Peace Court** in Scotland. Magistrates and JPs are members of the local community; in England, Wales and Scotland they usually work **unpaid** and need **no legal qualifications** (they receive training and have a legal adviser). Magistrates decide the **verdict** and, if guilty, the **sentence**. In **Northern Ireland**, cases are heard by a **District Judge or Deputy District Judge**, who is **legally qualified and paid**.\n  - **Serious offences**: tried before a **judge and jury** in a **Crown Court** (England, Wales, Northern Ireland). In Scotland, serious cases go to a **Sheriff Court** (sheriff alone or with a jury); the most serious (e.g. **murder**) go to a **High Court** with a judge and jury.\n  - **Juries**: members of the public chosen **at random from the local electoral register**. Jury size: **12** in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; **15** in Scotland. Everyone summoned must do jury service unless not eligible (e.g. criminal conviction) or excused for good reason (e.g. ill health). The jury decides '**guilty**' or '**not guilty**'; in Scotland a third verdict of '**not proven**' is possible. If guilty, the **judge decides the penalty**.\n  - **Youth Courts** (England, Wales, Northern Ireland): for accused aged **10 to 17**, heard by up to **three specially trained magistrates or a District Judge**; the most serious cases go to the **Crown Court**. Parents or carers are expected to attend; the **public are not allowed** in; the young person's **name or photographs cannot be published** in newspapers or used by the media.\n  - Scotland uses the **Children's Hearings System**; Northern Ireland has **youth conferencing**.\n- **Civil courts**:\n  - **County Courts** deal with a wide range of civil disputes: recovering money owed, **personal injury**, **family matters**, **breaches of contract**, and **divorce**. In Scotland most of these are dealt with in the **Sheriff Court**.\n  - More serious civil cases (e.g. large compensation claims) go to the **High Court** in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; in Scotland, the **Court of Session in Edinburgh**.\n- **Small claims procedure**: an informal way to settle minor disputes without spending a lot of time and money on a lawyer — for claims of **less than £10,000 in England and Wales** and **£5,000 in Scotland and Northern Ireland**. Hearing is before a judge in an ordinary room with both sides around a table. Claims can also be issued online via **Money Claims Online**. Details from your local County Court or Sheriff Court.\n- **Solicitors**: trained lawyers who give advice on legal matters, take action for clients and **represent clients in court**. Check their specialism and experience; the Citizens Advice Bureau, the **Law Society** (England and Wales), the **Law Society of Scotland** or the **Law Society of Northern Ireland** can give names of local solicitors. Charges are usually **based on time spent**, so find out at the start how much a case is likely to cost.", "checkUnderstand": ["The role of the judiciary", "About the different criminal courts in the UK", "About the different civil courts in the UK", "How you can settle a small claim"]}, {"id": "5.6", "title": "The government", "summary": "- **The Prime Minister (PM)**: leader of the political party in power; **appoints the cabinet** and controls many important public appointments. Official home: **10 Downing Street**; country house: **Chequers**. The PM can be changed if the MPs in the governing party decide so, or if he or she resigns — usually the PM **resigns if the party loses a General Election**.\n- **The cabinet**: the PM appoints **about 20 senior MPs** as ministers in charge of departments, including the **Chancellor of the Exchequer** (economy), the **Home Secretary** (crime, policing and immigration), the **Foreign Secretary** (relationships with foreign countries), and other **Secretaries of State** (e.g. education, health, defence). The cabinet usually meets **weekly** and makes important decisions on government policy, many of which must be debated or approved by Parliament. Departments also have **Ministers of State** and **Parliamentary Under-Secretaries of State**.\n- **The opposition**: the **second-largest party** in the House of Commons; its leader usually becomes PM if the party wins the next General Election. The leader points out the government's failures and weaknesses, notably at **Prime Minister's Questions** (**every week while Parliament is sitting**), and appoints **shadow ministers** who form the **shadow cabinet** to challenge the government and put forward alternative policies.\n- **The party system**: anyone aged **18 or over** can stand for election as an MP but is unlikely to win without a major party nomination — the **Conservative Party, the Labour Party, the Liberal Democrats**, or parties representing Scottish, Welsh or Northern Irish interests. '**Independents**' represent no main party, usually standing on an issue important to their constituency. Parties seek members to join debates, contribute to costs and help at elections; they have branches in most constituencies and hold **policy-making conferences** every year.\n- **Pressure and lobby groups** try to influence government policy — e.g. the **CBI** (Confederation of British Industry, representing British business), **Greenpeace** (environment), **Liberty** (human rights).\n- **The civil service**: civil servants support the government in **developing and implementing policies** and deliver public services. They are **accountable to ministers**, **chosen on merit**, and **politically neutral** (not political appointees). Core values: **integrity, honesty, objectivity and impartiality** (including political neutrality).\n- **Local government**: towns, cities and rural areas are governed by democratically elected councils ('**local authorities**'). Some areas have both **district and county councils**; most large towns and cities have a single local authority. Funded by **central government money and local taxes**. Many local authorities appoint a **mayor** (ceremonial leader of the council); in some towns a mayor is elected as effective leader. **London has 33 local authorities**, with the **Greater London Authority** and **Mayor of London** coordinating policies across the capital. Local elections for councillors are held in **May every year**; many candidates stand as members of a political party.\n- **Devolved administrations**: since **1997** some powers have been devolved to Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. A **Welsh Assembly** and **Scottish Parliament** have existed since **1999**; there is also a **Northern Ireland Assembly** (suspended on a few occasions). **Defence, foreign affairs, immigration, taxation and social security** remain under central UK government control; many other public services (e.g. education) are devolved. Each devolved administration has its **own civil service**.\n- **Welsh government**: the Welsh government and **National Assembly for Wales** are based in **Cardiff**. The Assembly has **60 Assembly members (AMs)**, elected **every four years** by a form of **proportional representation**. Members may speak **Welsh or English**; all publications are in both languages. The Assembly can make laws for Wales in **20 areas** including education and training, health and social services, economic development, and housing. Since **2011** it can pass laws on these topics **without the agreement of the UK Parliament**.\n- **Scottish Parliament**: formed in **1999**, sits in **Edinburgh**. **129 MSPs**, elected by a form of **proportional representation**. It can pass laws on all matters **not specifically reserved to the UK Parliament**, including **civil and criminal law, health, education, planning and additional tax-raising powers**.\n- **Northern Ireland Assembly**: a Northern Ireland Parliament was established in **1922** when Ireland was divided, but **abolished in 1972**, shortly after the Troubles broke out in **1969**. The Assembly was established soon after the **Belfast Agreement (Good Friday Agreement) of 1998**, with a **power-sharing agreement** distributing ministerial Offices among the main parties. It has **90 elected members (MLAs)**, elected by a form of **proportional representation**, and decides on issues such as **education, agriculture, the environment, health and social services**. The UK government can **suspend all devolved assemblies** and has done so several times in Northern Ireland; the Assembly has been running successfully since **2007**.\n- **The media and government**: proceedings in Parliament are broadcast on television and published in official reports called **Hansard** (in large libraries and at www.parliament.uk). The UK has a **free press** — newspapers are free from government control; some owners and editors hold strong political opinions and campaign to influence policy and opinion. By law, **radio and television coverage of political parties must be balanced**, with equal time for rival viewpoints.", "checkUnderstand": ["The role of the Prime Minister, cabinet, opposition and shadow cabinet", "The role of political parties in the UK system of government", "Who the main political parties are", "What pressure and lobby groups do", "The role of the civil service", "The role of local government", "The powers of the devolved governments in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland", "How proceedings in Parliament are recorded", "The role of the media in keeping people informed about political issues"]}, {"id": "5.6.1", "title": "Who can vote?", "summary": "- The UK has had a **fully democratic voting system since 1928**; the present voting age of **18** was set in **1969**. With a few exceptions, all UK-born and naturalised adult citizens have the right to vote.\n- **Adult citizens of the UK, and citizens of the Commonwealth and the Irish Republic resident in the UK**, can vote in **all public elections**. Adult citizens of **other EU states** resident in the UK can vote in all elections **except General Elections**.\n- **The electoral register**: you must be on it to vote in a parliamentary, local or European election. Register via your **local council electoral registration Office** (in Scotland it may be based elsewhere); find your local authority at **www.aboutmyvote.co.uk** by entering your postcode. Voter registration forms are available in English, Welsh and some other languages.\n- The register is **updated every year in September or October**; a registration form is sent to **every household**, to be returned with the names of all eligible residents.\n- **Northern Ireland** uses '**individual registration**': everyone entitled to vote completes their own form; once registered, people stay on the register provided their personal details do not change (see the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland).\n- Each local authority must make its electoral register **available for anyone to look at** (supervised), at the electoral registration Office (or council Office in England and Wales) and some public buildings such as libraries.\n- **Where to vote**: at **polling stations** (**polling places** in Scotland). A **poll card** is sent before the election with the location and date. On election day, polling stations are open **7.00 am to 10.00 pm**. Staff ask your name and address; in **Northern Ireland you must also show photographic identification**. Fill in the ballot paper privately in a polling booth and put it in the ballot box; no one has the right to make you vote for a particular candidate. If it is difficult to attend, you can register for a **postal ballot** (choose this when registering to vote).\n- **Standing for Office**: most citizens of the **UK, the Irish Republic or the Commonwealth aged 18 or over** can stand for public Office. Exceptions include **members of the armed forces**, **civil servants**, and **people found guilty of certain criminal offences**. **Members of the House of Lords may not stand for election to the House of Commons** but are eligible for all other public Offices.\n- **Visiting Parliament and devolved administrations**: the public can listen to debates in the **Palace of Westminster** from **public galleries** in both Houses — write to your MP for tickets or queue on the day (entrance free; Commons queues can take one to two hours; the Lords is usually easier). **MLAs** meet in the Northern Ireland Assembly at **Stormont, Belfast** (visit via the Education Service or an MLA). **MSPs** meet at the Scottish Parliament building at **Holyrood, Edinburgh**. **AMs** meet in the Welsh Assembly in the **Senedd, Cardiff Bay** — an open building with guided tours and public gallery seats bookable.", "checkUnderstand": ["Who is eligible to vote", "How you register to vote", "How to vote", "Who can stand for public Office", "How you can visit Parliament, the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Scottish Parliament and the Welsh Assembly"]}, {"id": "5.7", "title": "The UK and international institutions", "summary": "- **The Commonwealth**: an association of countries that support each other and work together towards shared goals in **democracy and development**. Most members were once part of the **British Empire**, although a few countries which were not have also joined. The **monarch (currently King Charles III)** is the **ceremonial head**. Membership is **voluntary**; the Commonwealth has **no power over its members**, although it can **suspend membership**. It is based on the core values of **democracy, good government and the rule of law**. Members span Africa, Asia, the Caribbean and Americas, Europe and the Pacific (e.g. **the UK, Australia, Canada, India, New Zealand, South Africa, Singapore, Cyprus, Malta, Jamaica**).\n- **The European Union (EU)**: originally called the **European Economic Community (EEC)**, set up by **six western European countries** (**Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands**) who signed the **Treaty of Rome on 25 March 1957**. The UK originally decided not to join and became a member in **1973**. The UK left the EU after the **Brexit** vote — Brexit officially took place at **23:00 GMT on 31 January 2020**. There are now **27 EU member states**. With effect from 2024, no general principle of EU law is part of UK law. European laws are called **directives, regulations or framework decisions**.\n- **The Council of Europe**: **separate from the EU**; has **47 member countries** including the UK; responsible for the **protection and promotion of human rights**; it has **no power to make laws** but draws up **conventions and charters**, most notably the **European Convention on Human Rights**.\n- **The United Nations (UN)**: the UK is a member; over **190 countries** belong. Set up **after the Second World War** to prevent war and promote international peace and security. The **UN Security Council** has **15 members** and recommends action in international crises; the UK is **one of five permanent members**.\n- **NATO** (North Atlantic Treaty Organization): the UK is a member. A group of **European and North American countries** that have agreed to **help each other if they come under attack**; it also aims to maintain peace between all of its members.", "checkUnderstand": ["What the Commonwealth is and its role", "Other international organisations of which the UK is a member"]}, {"id": "5.8", "title": "Your role in the community", "summary": "- Becoming a British citizen or settling in the UK brings **responsibilities and opportunities**; everyone can participate in their community.\n- **Shared values and responsibilities** include: to **obey and respect the law**; to be aware of and respect the **rights of others**; to **treat others with fairness**; to **behave responsibly**; to **help and protect your family**; to **respect and preserve the environment**; to **treat everyone equally** regardless of sex, race, religion, age, disability, class or sexual orientation; to **work to provide for yourself and your family**; to **help others**; and to **vote in local and national government elections**.\n- **Being a good neighbour**: introduce yourself when you move in; neighbours can be a good source of help (e.g. feeding pets, advice on local shops). Prevent problems by **respecting privacy**, **limiting noise**, keeping your **garden tidy**, and only putting **refuse bags and bins** out when due to be collected.\n- **Getting involved in local activities**: volunteering and helping your community are an important part of being a **good citizen** — they help you integrate, get to know people, and fulfil your duties as a citizen such as behaving responsibly and helping others.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.8.1", "title": "How you can support your community", "summary": "- **Jury service**: people on the **electoral register** aged **18 to 70** are **randomly selected** to serve on a jury.\n- **Helping in schools**: parents can help in classrooms, support activities or **listen to children read**; schools organise fund-raising events (book sales, toy sales, food sales), sometimes via **parent-teacher associations (PTAs)** — volunteering or joining is good for the school and for making friends.\n- **School governors and school boards**: school governors (or **members of the school board in Scotland**) are people from the local community who wish to contribute to children's education; they must be **aged 18 or over** at election or appointment (**no upper age limit**). Their **three key roles**: **setting the strategic direction of the school**, **ensuring accountability**, and **monitoring and evaluating school performance**. Contact your local school, or in England apply online at the **School Governors' One-Stop Shop**. In England, parents and community groups can apply to **open a free school** (Department for Education).\n- **Supporting political parties**: joining a party demonstrates support for certain views and involvement in the democratic process. At election times members go '**canvassing**' — handing out leaflets and knocking on doors asking for support; **you don't have to tell a canvasser how you intend to vote**. **British citizens** can stand for Office as a **local councillor, MP (or devolved equivalents) or MEP**; **Irish citizens, eligible Commonwealth citizens**, or citizens of another **EU country (except for standing to be an MP)** may also stand.\n- **Helping with local services**: volunteer with local hospitals, youth projects, universities, housing associations, museums and arts councils (including serving on governing bodies). You can volunteer with the **police** — become a **special constable** or a **lay (non-police) representative** — or apply to become a **magistrate**.\n- **Blood and organ donation**: giving blood takes only about **an hour**; registering as an **organ donor** makes it easier for your family to decide about donation when you die; **living people can donate a kidney**.\n- **Other volunteering**: working for good causes **without payment**. Benefits: meeting new people, making the community better, a chance to **practise your English** or develop **work skills** for your **CV**. Activities include working with animals, youth work, environmental work (e.g. litter pick-ups), helping the homeless, **mentoring** (e.g. supporting someone just out of prison), health and hospital work, and helping older people.\n- **Charities**: thousands of active charities include **Age UK** (older people), the **NSPCC** (children), **Crisis** and **Shelter** (the homeless), **Cancer Research UK** (medical research), the **National Trust** and **Friends of the Earth** (environment), the **PDSA** (animals), and the **British Red Cross**.\n- Young people can volunteer and receive accreditation, e.g. the **National Citizen Service** programme, which gives **16- and 17-year-olds** the opportunity to enjoy outdoor activities, develop their skills and take part in a **community project**.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "5.8.2", "title": "Looking after the environment", "summary": "- **Recycle** as much of your waste as you can: using recycled materials to make new products uses **less energy**, means we do not need to extract more **raw materials** from the earth, and means less rubbish goes into **landfill**.\n- **Shop for products locally** where you can: this helps businesses and farmers in your area and in Britain, and reduces your **carbon footprint** because products do not have to travel as far.\n- **Walking and using public transport** when you can is a good way to protect the environment — you create **less pollution** than when you use a car.", "checkUnderstand": ["The different ways you can help at your child's school", "The role of school governors and members of school boards, and how you can become one", "The role of members of political parties", "The different local services people can volunteer to support", "How to donate blood and organs", "The benefits of volunteering for you, other people and the community", "The types of activities that volunteers can do", "How you can look after the environment"]}], "flashcards": [{"q": "What is democracy?", "a": "A system of government where the whole adult population gets a say, either by direct voting or by choosing representatives to make decisions on their behalf.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "At the turn of the 19th century, who could vote in Britain?", "a": "Only a small group: men over 21 years of age who owned a certain amount of property.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What does 'the franchise' mean?", "a": "The number of people who had the right to vote.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Who were the Chartists?", "a": "A group that campaigned for electoral reform in the 1830s and 1840s.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What six changes did the Chartists want?", "a": "For every man to have the vote; elections every year; all regions to be equal in the electoral system; secret ballots; any man to be able to stand as an MP; MPs to be paid.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Was the Chartist campaign successful at the time?", "a": "It was generally seen as a failure at the time, but by 1918 most of the reforms had been adopted.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Which women gained the right to vote in 1918?", "a": "Women over 30.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What happened to the voting franchise in 1928?", "a": "It was extended to men and women over 21.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "When was the voting age reduced to 18 for men and women?", "a": "In 1969.", "section": "5.2", "page": 73, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What is a constitution?", "a": "A set of principles by which a country is governed. It includes all the institutions responsible for running the country and how their power is kept in check, as well as laws and conventions.", "section": "5.3", "page": 74, "tags": ["constitution"]}, {"q": "Why is the British constitution described as 'unwritten'?", "a": "Because it is not written down in any single document. This is mainly because the UK, unlike America or France, has never had a revolution which led permanently to a totally new system of government.", "section": "5.3", "page": 74, "tags": ["constitution"]}, {"q": "What are the main constitutional institutions of UK government?", "a": "The monarchy, Parliament (the House of Commons and the House of Lords), the Prime Minister, the cabinet, the judiciary (courts), the police, the civil service, and local government.", "section": "5.3", "page": 74, "tags": ["constitution"]}, {"q": "Who is the head of state of the UK?", "a": "The monarch. The monarch is also head of state for many countries in the Commonwealth.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What does it mean that the UK is a constitutional monarchy?", "a": "The king or queen does not rule the country but appoints the government, which the people have chosen in a democratic election.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy", "constitution"]}, {"q": "Whom does the monarch invite to become Prime Minister?", "a": "The leader of the party with the largest number of MPs, or the leader of a coalition between more than one party.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy", "government"]}, {"q": "What can the monarch do in regular meetings with the Prime Minister?", "a": "The monarch can advise, warn and encourage, but decisions on government policies are made by the Prime Minister and cabinet.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "When did Queen Elizabeth II become queen?", "a": "In 1952, after her father's death.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What did Queen Elizabeth II celebrate in 2012?", "a": "Her Diamond Jubilee — 60 years as queen.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "When did Queen Elizabeth II die?", "a": "On 8 September 2022.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who was Queen Elizabeth II married to?", "a": "Prince Philip.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who is the current ruling monarch of the UK?", "a": "King Charles III, who has been the sovereign since 2022.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who is the heir apparent to the throne?", "a": "William, Prince of Wales (Prince of Wales is the title for the heir apparent to the throne), King Charles III's elder son.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who is next in the line of succession after Prince William?", "a": "William's three children, in order of birth: Prince George, Princess Charlotte, and Prince Louis.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "Who became Duke of Edinburgh in 2023?", "a": "Prince Edward, given the title by King Charles III, who formerly held it.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What ceremonial role does the monarch perform for Parliament each year?", "a": "The opening of the new parliamentary session, when the King (or Queen) makes a speech summarising the government's policies for the year ahead.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy", "parliament"]}, {"q": "In whose name are all Acts of Parliament made?", "a": "In the Majesty's name (the monarch's name).", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy", "parliament"]}, {"q": "How does the monarch represent the UK to the rest of the world?", "a": "The monarch receives foreign ambassadors and high commissioners, entertains visiting heads of state, and makes state visits overseas in support of diplomatic and economic relationships.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What role does the monarch play while governments and Prime Ministers change?", "a": "The monarch provides stability and continuity as head of state, and a focus for national identity and pride.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What is the National Anthem of the UK?", "a": "'God Save the King (or Queen)'. It is played at important national occasions and at events attended by the King (or Queen) or the Royal Family.", "section": "5.3", "page": 75, "tags": ["monarchy"]}, {"q": "What do new citizens do at the citizenship ceremony?", "a": "They swear or affirm loyalty to the King — an oath or affirmation of allegiance to His Majesty King Charles the Third, his Heirs and Successors, according to law.", "section": "5.3", "page": 76, "tags": ["monarchy", "community"]}, {"q": "What system of government does the UK have?", "a": "A parliamentary democracy.", "section": "5.3", "page": 76, "tags": ["constitution", "parliament"]}, {"q": "How is the UK divided for General Elections?", "a": "Into parliamentary constituencies. Voters in each constituency elect their member of Parliament (MP), and all elected MPs form the House of Commons.", "section": "5.3", "page": 76, "tags": ["elections", "parliament"]}, {"q": "What happens if no single party wins a majority of MPs?", "a": "Two parties can join together to form a coalition.", "section": "5.3", "page": 76, "tags": ["elections", "government"]}, {"q": "Why is the House of Commons regarded as more important than the House of Lords?", "a": "Because its members are democratically elected.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Where do the Prime Minister and the cabinet mostly sit?", "a": "The Prime Minister and almost all members of the cabinet are members of the House of Commons (MPs).", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament", "government"]}, {"q": "What are the responsibilities of an MP?", "a": "To represent everyone in their constituency, help to create new laws, scrutinise and comment on what the government is doing, and debate important national issues.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What are members of the House of Lords called?", "a": "Peers. They are not elected by the people and do not represent a constituency.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Before 1958, who could be a peer in the House of Lords?", "a": "All peers were 'hereditary' (inherited their title), senior judges, or bishops of the Church of England.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What are life peers and who appoints them?", "a": "Since 1958 the Prime Minister has been able to nominate peers for their own lifetime. Life peers are appointed by the monarch on the advice of the Prime Minister; they can also be nominated by other main party leaders or by an independent Appointments Commission for non-party peers.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What changed for hereditary peers in 1999?", "a": "They lost the automatic right to attend the House of Lords. They now elect a few of their number to represent them in the House of Lords.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What is the role of the House of Lords?", "a": "It is normally more independent of the government; it can suggest amendments or propose new laws, checks laws passed by the House of Commons to ensure they are fit for purpose, and holds the government to account.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Can the House of Commons overrule the House of Lords?", "a": "Yes — the House of Commons has powers to overrule the House of Lords, but these are not used often.", "section": "5.3", "page": 77, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Who chairs debates in the House of Commons?", "a": "The Speaker, who is the chief Officer of the House of Commons.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Is the Speaker of the House of Commons politically neutral?", "a": "Yes — the Speaker is neutral and does not represent a political party, even though he or she is an MP, represents a constituency and deals with constituents' problems like any other MP.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "How is the Speaker of the House of Commons chosen?", "a": "By other MPs in a secret ballot.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What does the Speaker do during debates?", "a": "Keeps order to make sure the rules are followed, including making sure the opposition has a guaranteed amount of time to debate issues it chooses. The Speaker also represents Parliament on ceremonial occasions.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "How often must a General Election be held?", "a": "At least every five years.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What is a by-election?", "a": "A fresh election held in a constituency if its MP dies or resigns.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What electoral system is used to elect MPs?", "a": "'First past the post' — in each constituency, the candidate who gets the most votes is elected. The government is usually formed by the party that wins the majority of constituencies.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "How are members of the European Parliament (MEPs) elected?", "a": "Elections for the European Parliament are held every five years, using a system of proportional representation, where seats are allocated to each party in proportion to the total number of votes it has won.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Where can you find contact details for your elected representatives?", "a": "From your local library and from www.parliament.uk. MPs, Assembly members, MSPs and MEPs are also listed in The Phone Book (published by BT) and in Yellow Pages.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["elections", "parliament"]}, {"q": "What are MPs' 'surgeries'?", "a": "Regular local sessions held by many MPs, Assembly members, MSPs and MEPs where constituents can go in person to talk about issues of concern. They are often advertised in the local newspaper.", "section": "5.3", "page": 78, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "In which documents do British rights and freedoms have their roots?", "a": "Magna Carta, the Habeas Corpus Act and the Bill of Rights of 1689.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "What was the UK's role in the European Convention on Human Rights?", "a": "British diplomats and lawyers had an important role in drafting the European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, and the UK was one of the first countries to sign it in 1950.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "Name some principles included in the European Convention on Human Rights.", "a": "Right to life; prohibition of torture; prohibition of slavery and forced labour; right to liberty and security; right to a fair trial; freedom of thought, conscience and religion; freedom of expression (speech).", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "What did the Human Rights Act 1998 do?", "a": "It incorporated the European Convention on Human Rights into UK law. The government, public bodies and the courts must follow the principles of the Convention.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "On what grounds do UK equal opportunities laws protect people from unfair treatment?", "a": "Age, disability, sex, pregnancy and maternity, race, religion or belief, sexuality or marital status.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "Which bodies can help with discrimination problems in each part of the UK?", "a": "The Citizens Advice Bureau; in England and Wales, the Equality and Human Rights Commission; in Scotland, the Equality and Human Rights Commission in Scotland and the Scottish Human Rights Commission; in Northern Ireland, the Equality Commission for Northern Ireland and the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "How does UK law treat domestic violence?", "a": "Brutality and violence in the home is a serious crime. Anyone who is violent towards their partner — whether man or woman, married or living together — can be prosecuted. Any man who forces a woman to have sex, including a woman's husband, can be charged with rape.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "What is the National Domestic Violence Freephone Helpline number?", "a": "0808 2000 247 — a 24-hour helpline that can be phoned at any time.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights"]}, {"q": "Is female genital mutilation (FGM) legal in the UK?", "a": "No. FGM (also known as cutting or female circumcision) is illegal in the UK. Practising FGM or taking a girl or woman abroad for FGM is a criminal offence.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "What is the difference between an arranged marriage and a forced marriage in the UK?", "a": "Arranged marriages, where both parties agree to the marriage, are acceptable in the UK. Forced marriage is where one or both parties do not or cannot give their consent; forcing another person to marry is a criminal offence.", "section": "5.4", "page": 79, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "When and under what law were Forced Marriage Protection Orders introduced?", "a": "In 2008 for England, Wales and Northern Ireland under the Forced Marriage (Civil Protection) Act 2007. Similar Protection Orders were introduced in Scotland in November 2011.", "section": "5.4", "page": 80, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "What is the penalty for breaching a Forced Marriage Protection Order?", "a": "Anyone found to have breached an order can be jailed for up to two years for contempt of court.", "section": "5.4", "page": 80, "tags": ["rights", "law"]}, {"q": "What kinds of income do people in the UK pay income tax on?", "a": "Wages from paid employment, profits from self-employment, taxable benefits, pensions, and income from property, savings and dividends.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "What does money raised from income tax pay for?", "a": "Government services such as roads, education, police and the armed forces.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "Which government department collects taxes in the UK?", "a": "HM Revenue & Customs (HMRC).", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "What is 'Pay As You Earn' (PAYE)?", "a": "The system by which, for most people, the right amount of income tax is automatically taken from their employment income by their employer and paid directly to HMRC.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "How do self-employed people pay their income tax?", "a": "Through a system called 'self-assessment', which includes completing a tax return.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "Who must pay National Insurance Contributions?", "a": "Almost everybody in the UK who is in paid work, including self-employed people.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "What is money from National Insurance Contributions used for?", "a": "To pay for state benefits and services such as the state retirement pension and the National Health Service (NHS).", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "What happens if someone does not pay enough National Insurance Contributions?", "a": "They will not be able to receive certain contributory benefits such as Jobseeker's Allowance or a full state retirement pension. Some workers, such as part-time workers, may not qualify for statutory payments such as maternity pay if they do not earn enough.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "When do young people in the UK receive their National Insurance number?", "a": "All young people in the UK are sent a National Insurance number just before their 16th birthday.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "How does a non-UK national get a National Insurance number?", "a": "Telephone the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) to arrange it; you may be required to attend an interview with documents proving your identity and permission to work. You can start work without one.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "Does a National Insurance number prove the right to work in the UK?", "a": "No — a National Insurance number does not on its own prove to an employer that you have the right to work in the UK.", "section": "5.4.1", "page": 80, "tags": ["taxes"]}, {"q": "How old must you be to drive a car or motor cycle in the UK?", "a": "At least 17 years old, and you must have a driving licence to drive on public roads.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "How old must you be to ride a moped in the UK?", "a": "At least 16 years old.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "What tests must you pass to get a UK driving licence?", "a": "After applying for a provisional driving licence, you must pass a driving theory test (a multiple choice theory test and a hazard perception test) and a practical driving test.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "Until what age is a UK driving licence valid, and what happens after?", "a": "Drivers can use their driving licence until they are 70 years old. After that, the licence is valid for three years at a time.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "What must a newly qualified driver in Northern Ireland do?", "a": "Display an 'R' plate (for restricted driver) for one year after passing the test.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "How long can you drive in the UK on a licence from the EU, Iceland, Liechtenstein or Norway?", "a": "For as long as your licence is valid.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "How long can you drive in the UK on a licence from a country outside the EU, Iceland, Liechtenstein or Norway?", "a": "For up to 12 months. To continue driving after that, you must get a UK full driving licence.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 80, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "Where must UK residents register their car or motor cycle?", "a": "At the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA).", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 81, "tags": ["driving"]}, {"q": "What tax must you pay on your vehicle and how is it shown?", "a": "You must pay an annual road tax and display the tax disc, which shows that the tax has been paid, on the windscreen.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 81, "tags": ["driving", "taxes"]}, {"q": "Is it an offence to drive without motor insurance?", "a": "Yes — you must have valid motor insurance, and it is a serious criminal offence to drive without insurance.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 81, "tags": ["driving", "law"]}, {"q": "When must a vehicle take an MOT test?", "a": "If your vehicle is over three years old, you must take it for a Ministry of Transport (MOT) test every year. It is an offence not to have an MOT certificate for a vehicle more than three years old.", "section": "5.4.2", "page": 81, "tags": ["driving", "law"]}, {"q": "What is one of the most important responsibilities of all UK residents?", "a": "To know and obey the law. Those who do not respect the law should not expect to be allowed to become permanent residents in the UK.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What does equal treatment under the law mean?", "a": "The law applies in the same way to everyone, no matter who they are or where they are from.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law", "rights"]}, {"q": "What is the difference between criminal law and civil law?", "a": "Criminal law relates to crimes, which are usually investigated by the police or another authority such as a council and punished by the courts. Civil law is used to settle disputes between individuals or groups.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "Is it legal to carry a weapon for self-defence in the UK?", "a": "No — it is a criminal offence to carry a weapon of any kind, even for self-defence. This includes a gun, a knife or anything made or adapted to cause injury.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "Give examples of criminal laws in the UK.", "a": "Carrying a weapon; selling or buying drugs such as heroin, cocaine, ecstasy and cannabis; racial crime (causing harassment, alarm or distress because of religion or ethnic origin); selling tobacco to anyone under 18; smoking in enclosed public places; selling alcohol to under-18s or buying it for them; drinking in public in alcohol-free zones.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "At what age can tobacco products legally be sold to someone in the UK?", "a": "It is illegal to sell tobacco products (e.g. cigarettes, cigars, roll-up tobacco) to anyone under the age of 18.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What is the exception to the rule against alcohol for under-18s?", "a": "People aged 16 or over can drink alcohol with a meal in a hotel or restaurant.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What can police do about drinking in public?", "a": "Some places have alcohol-free zones where you cannot drink in public. The police can confiscate alcohol or move young people on from public places, and you can be fined or arrested.", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law", "police"]}, {"q": "Give examples of civil law in the UK.", "a": "Housing law (disputes between landlords and tenants over repairs and eviction); consumer rights (e.g. faulty goods or services); employment law (wages, unfair dismissal, workplace discrimination); debt (being taken to court for money owed).", "section": "5.5", "page": 82, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What is the job of the police in the UK?", "a": "To protect life and property, prevent disturbances (also known as keeping the peace), and prevent and detect crime.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police"]}, {"q": "Who heads police forces, and are they controlled by the government?", "a": "The police are organised into a number of separate forces headed by Chief Constables. They are independent of the government.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police"]}, {"q": "What are Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs)?", "a": "Directly elected individuals in England and Wales (first elected by the public in November 2012) responsible for the delivery of an efficient and effective police force reflecting local needs. They set local police priorities and the local policing budget, and appoint the Chief Constable.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police", "elections"]}, {"q": "What do police community support Officers usually do?", "a": "They support police Officers; roles vary by area but they usually patrol the streets, work with the public, and support police Officers at crime scenes and major events.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police"]}, {"q": "What happens if you are arrested and taken to a police station?", "a": "A police Officer will tell you the reason for your arrest and you will be able to seek legal advice.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police", "law"]}, {"q": "How can you complain about the police?", "a": "By going to a police station or writing to the Chief Constable of the force involved, or to an independent body: the Independent Police Complaints Commission (England and Wales), the Police Complaints Commissioner for Scotland, or the Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["police"]}, {"q": "What is the most serious terrorist threat facing the UK, according to the handbook?", "a": "The threat from Al Qa'ida, its affiliates and like-minded organisations. The UK also faces other threats such as Northern Ireland-related terrorism.", "section": "5.5", "page": 83, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What is extremism?", "a": "Vocal or active opposition to fundamental British values — including religious extremism and far-right extremism.", "section": "5.5", "page": 84, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "What should you do if someone tries to persuade you to join an extremist or terrorist cause?", "a": "Notify your local police force.", "section": "5.5", "page": 84, "tags": ["law", "police"]}, {"q": "What is the role of the judiciary?", "a": "Judges (together called 'the judiciary') are responsible for interpreting the law and ensuring that trials are conducted fairly. The government cannot interfere with this.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts", "law"]}, {"q": "What happens if judges find that the government has acted illegally?", "a": "The government must either change its policies or ask Parliament to change the law. If a public body is not respecting someone's legal rights, judges can order it to change its practices and/or pay compensation.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts", "law"]}, {"q": "Which courts deal with most minor criminal cases in the UK?", "a": "In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, a Magistrates' Court; in Scotland, a Justice of the Peace Court.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Do magistrates need legal qualifications?", "a": "In England, Wales and Scotland, magistrates and Justices of the Peace are members of the local community who usually work unpaid and do not need legal qualifications; they receive training and are supported by a legal adviser.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Who hears minor criminal cases in Northern Ireland?", "a": "A District Judge or Deputy District Judge, who is legally qualified and paid.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Where are serious criminal offences tried in England, Wales and Northern Ireland?", "a": "In front of a judge and a jury in a Crown Court.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Where are serious criminal cases heard in Scotland?", "a": "In a Sheriff Court with either a sheriff or a sheriff with a jury. The most serious cases, such as murder, are heard at a High Court with a judge and jury.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How is a jury selected?", "a": "A jury is made up of members of the public chosen at random from the local electoral register.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How many members does a jury have in each part of the UK?", "a": "12 members in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; 15 members in Scotland.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Can you refuse jury service?", "a": "Everyone summoned must do jury service unless they are not eligible (for example, because they have a criminal conviction) or they provide a good reason to be excused, such as ill health.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts", "community"]}, {"q": "What verdicts can a jury reach?", "a": "'Guilty' or 'not guilty' based on the evidence heard. In Scotland, a third verdict of 'not proven' is also possible.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "Who decides the penalty if a jury finds a defendant guilty?", "a": "The judge.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How are accused people aged 10 to 17 dealt with in England, Wales and Northern Ireland?", "a": "The case is normally heard in a Youth Court in front of up to three specially trained magistrates or a District Judge. The most serious cases go to the Crown Court.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "What special rules apply to Youth Courts?", "a": "The parents or carers of the young person are expected to attend the hearing; members of the public are not allowed in; and the name or photographs of the accused young person cannot be published in newspapers or used by the media.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How does Scotland deal with children and young people who have committed an offence?", "a": "Through a system called the Children's Hearings System.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How does Northern Ireland decide how a child who has committed an offence should be dealt with?", "a": "Through a system of youth conferencing.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "What kinds of cases do County Courts deal with?", "a": "A wide range of civil disputes: getting back money owed, personal injury, family matters, breaches of contract, and divorce. In Scotland, most of these matters are dealt with in the Sheriff Court.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts", "law"]}, {"q": "Which courts deal with more serious civil cases, such as large compensation claims?", "a": "The High Court in England, Wales and Northern Ireland; in Scotland, the Court of Session in Edinburgh.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "What is the small claims procedure?", "a": "An informal way of helping people settle minor disputes without spending a lot of time and money using a lawyer. The hearing is held in front of a judge in an ordinary room, with people from both sides sitting around a table.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts", "law"]}, {"q": "What are the money limits for the small claims procedure?", "a": "Claims of less than £10,000 in England and Wales, and £5,000 in Scotland and Northern Ireland.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "How can small claims be issued online?", "a": "Through Money Claims Online (www.moneyclaim.gov.uk).", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 84, "tags": ["courts"]}, {"q": "What do solicitors do?", "a": "Solicitors are trained lawyers who give advice on legal matters, take action for their clients and represent their clients in court. Their charges are usually based on how much time they spend on a case.", "section": "5.5.1", "page": 85, "tags": ["law"]}, {"q": "Who is the Prime Minister?", "a": "The leader of the political party in power. He or she appoints the members of the cabinet and has control over many important public appointments.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What are the official residences of the Prime Minister?", "a": "The official home is 10 Downing Street, in central London, near the Houses of Parliament. The PM also has a country house outside London called Chequers.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "How can the Prime Minister be changed?", "a": "If the MPs in the governing party decide to do so, or if he or she wishes to resign. The Prime Minister usually resigns if his or her party loses a General Election.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the cabinet?", "a": "A committee of about 20 senior MPs appointed by the Prime Minister as ministers in charge of departments. It usually meets weekly and makes important decisions about government policy, many of which have to be debated or approved by Parliament.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the Chancellor of the Exchequer responsible for?", "a": "The economy.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the Home Secretary responsible for?", "a": "Crime, policing and immigration.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the Foreign Secretary responsible for?", "a": "Managing relationships with foreign countries.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "Besides cabinet ministers, what other ministers does each government department have?", "a": "Ministers of State and Parliamentary Under-Secretaries of State, who take charge of particular areas of the department's work.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the opposition?", "a": "The second-largest party in the House of Commons. Its leader usually becomes Prime Minister if his or her party wins the next General Election.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government", "parliament"]}, {"q": "When does Prime Minister's Questions take place?", "a": "Every week while Parliament is sitting — an important opportunity for the leader of the opposition to point out the government's failures and weaknesses.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government", "parliament"]}, {"q": "What is the shadow cabinet?", "a": "Senior opposition MPs appointed by the leader of the opposition as 'shadow ministers'. Their role is to challenge the government and put forward alternative policies.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What are the main political parties in the UK?", "a": "The Conservative Party, the Labour Party, the Liberal Democrats, and parties representing Scottish, Welsh or Northern Irish interests.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government", "elections"]}, {"q": "What are 'independent' MPs?", "a": "MPs who do not represent any of the main political parties; they usually represent an issue important to their constituency.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["parliament", "elections"]}, {"q": "What do pressure and lobby groups do? Give examples.", "a": "They try to influence government policy. Some are representative organisations such as the CBI (Confederation of British Industry), which represents British business; others campaign on particular topics, such as Greenpeace (the environment) or Liberty (human rights).", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What is the role of the civil service?", "a": "Civil servants support the government in developing and implementing its policies and deliver public services. They are accountable to ministers.", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "How are civil servants chosen, and what are their core values?", "a": "They are chosen on merit and are politically neutral — not political appointees. Core values are integrity, honesty, objectivity and impartiality (including being politically neutral).", "section": "5.6", "page": 86, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "How are towns, cities and rural areas in the UK governed?", "a": "By democratically elected councils, often called 'local authorities'. Some areas have both district and county councils with different functions; most large towns and cities have a single local authority.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "How are local authorities funded?", "a": "By money from central government and by local taxes.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["government", "taxes"]}, {"q": "What is the role of a mayor?", "a": "Many local authorities appoint a mayor, who is the ceremonial leader of the council. In some towns, a mayor is elected to be the effective leader of the administration.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "How is local government organised in London?", "a": "London has 33 local authorities, with the Greater London Authority and the Mayor of London coordinating policies across the capital.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "When are local elections for councillors held?", "a": "For most local authorities, in May every year. Many candidates stand as members of a political party.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["elections", "government"]}, {"q": "When did devolution begin, and when were the devolved bodies established?", "a": "Some powers have been devolved since 1997. There has been a Welsh Assembly and a Scottish Parliament since 1999. There is also a Northern Ireland Assembly, although it has been suspended on a few occasions.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "Which policy areas remain under central UK government control?", "a": "Defence, foreign affairs, immigration, taxation and social security. Many other public services, such as education, are controlled by the devolved administrations.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "Do the devolved administrations have their own civil service?", "a": "Yes — the devolved administrations each have their own civil service.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution", "government"]}, {"q": "Where are the Welsh government and National Assembly for Wales based?", "a": "In Cardiff, the capital city of Wales.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "How many members does the National Assembly for Wales have, and how are they elected?", "a": "60 Assembly members (AMs), with elections held every four years using a form of proportional representation. Members can speak in Welsh or English, and all Assembly publications are in both languages.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution", "elections"]}, {"q": "In how many areas can the National Assembly for Wales make laws?", "a": "20 areas, including education and training, health and social services, economic development, and housing. Since 2011 it has been able to pass laws on these topics without the agreement of the UK Parliament.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "When was the Scottish Parliament formed and where does it sit?", "a": "It was formed in 1999 and sits in Edinburgh, the capital city of Scotland.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "How many members does the Scottish Parliament have, and how are they elected?", "a": "129 members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs), elected by a form of proportional representation.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution", "elections"]}, {"q": "On which matters can the Scottish Parliament legislate?", "a": "All matters not specifically reserved to the UK Parliament, including civil and criminal law, health, education, planning, and additional tax-raising powers.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "What happened to the original Northern Ireland Parliament?", "a": "It was established in 1922, when Ireland was divided, but was abolished in 1972, shortly after the Troubles broke out in 1969.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "When was the Northern Ireland Assembly established?", "a": "Soon after the Belfast Agreement (or Good Friday Agreement) in 1998. There is a power-sharing agreement which distributes ministerial Offices amongst the main parties.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "How many members does the Northern Ireland Assembly have, and how are they elected?", "a": "90 elected members, known as MLAs (members of the Legislative Assembly), elected with a form of proportional representation.", "section": "5.6", "page": 87, "tags": ["devolution", "elections"]}, {"q": "On what issues can the Northern Ireland Assembly make decisions?", "a": "Issues such as education, agriculture, the environment, health and social services.", "section": "5.6", "page": 88, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "Can the UK government suspend the devolved assemblies?", "a": "Yes — the UK government has the power to suspend all devolved assemblies, and has used this power several times in Northern Ireland. However, the Assembly has been running successfully since 2007.", "section": "5.6", "page": 88, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "How are proceedings in Parliament recorded?", "a": "They are broadcast on television and published in official reports called Hansard. Written reports can be found in large libraries and at www.parliament.uk.", "section": "5.6", "page": 88, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "What does it mean that the UK has a free press?", "a": "What is written in newspapers is free from government control. Some newspaper owners and editors hold strong political opinions and run campaigns to try to influence government policy and public opinion.", "section": "5.6", "page": 88, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "What rules apply to radio and television coverage of political parties?", "a": "By law, coverage must be balanced, so equal time has to be given to rival viewpoints.", "section": "5.6", "page": 88, "tags": ["government"]}, {"q": "Since when has the UK had a fully democratic voting system?", "a": "Since 1928. The present voting age of 18 was set in 1969.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Who can vote in all UK public elections?", "a": "Adult citizens of the UK, and citizens of the Commonwealth and the Irish Republic who are resident in the UK.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "In which elections can resident citizens of other EU states vote?", "a": "Adult citizens of other EU states who are resident in the UK can vote in all elections except General Elections.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What must you do to be able to vote in a parliamentary, local or European election?", "a": "You must have your name on the electoral register.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "How do you register to vote?", "a": "By contacting your local council electoral registration Office (in Scotland it may be based elsewhere). You can find your local authority by entering your postcode at www.aboutmyvote.co.uk, where you can also download voter registration forms.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "When is the electoral register updated?", "a": "Every year in September or October. An electoral registration form is sent to every household and must be completed and returned with the names of everyone resident and eligible to vote.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "How does voter registration work in Northern Ireland?", "a": "A different system called 'individual registration' operates: all those entitled to vote must complete their own registration form. Once registered, people stay on the register provided their personal details do not change.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Can anyone view the electoral register?", "a": "Yes — by law each local authority must make its electoral register available for anyone to look at, although this has to be supervised. It is kept at each local electoral registration Office (or council Office in England and Wales) and can be seen at some public buildings such as libraries.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 88, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Where do people vote in elections?", "a": "At places called polling stations, or polling places in Scotland. Before the election you are sent a poll card telling you where your polling station or place is and when the election will take place.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What are the opening hours of polling stations on election day?", "a": "From 7.00 am until 10.00 pm.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What extra requirement applies to voters in Northern Ireland at the polling station?", "a": "They must show photographic identification, in addition to giving their name and address.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "What can you do if it is difficult for you to get to a polling station?", "a": "Register for a postal ballot. Your ballot paper is sent to your home before the election; you fill it in and post it back. You can choose this when you register to vote.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Who can stand for public Office in the UK?", "a": "Most citizens of the UK, the Irish Republic or the Commonwealth aged 18 or over.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections"]}, {"q": "Who cannot stand for public Office?", "a": "Exceptions include members of the armed forces, civil servants, and people found guilty of certain criminal offences. Members of the House of Lords may not stand for election to the House of Commons but are eligible for all other public Offices.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["elections", "parliament"]}, {"q": "How can the public listen to debates in the UK Parliament?", "a": "From public galleries in both the House of Commons and the House of Lords at the Palace of Westminster. You can write to your local MP in advance for tickets or queue on the day at the public entrance; entrance is free.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["parliament"]}, {"q": "Where do Northern Ireland's MLAs meet?", "a": "In the Northern Ireland Assembly at Stormont, in Belfast. Visits can be arranged through the Education Service or by contacting an MLA.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "Where do MSPs meet?", "a": "In the Scottish Parliament building at Holyrood in Edinburgh.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "Where do Welsh Assembly members (AMs) meet?", "a": "In the Welsh Assembly in the Senedd in Cardiff Bay. The Senedd is an open building where you can book guided tours or seats in the public galleries.", "section": "5.6.1", "page": 89, "tags": ["devolution"]}, {"q": "What is the Commonwealth?", "a": "An association of countries that support each other and work together towards shared goals in democracy and development. Most member states were once part of the British Empire, although a few countries which were not have also joined.", "section": "5.7", "page": 90, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "Who is the head of the Commonwealth?", "a": "The monarch (currently King Charles III) is the ceremonial head of the Commonwealth.", "section": "5.7", "page": 90, "tags": ["international", "monarchy"]}, {"q": "What power does the Commonwealth have over its members?", "a": "Membership is voluntary and the Commonwealth has no power over its members, although it can suspend membership.", "section": "5.7", "page": 90, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "What core values is the Commonwealth based on?", "a": "Democracy, good government and the rule of law.", "section": "5.7", "page": 90, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "Name some member states of the Commonwealth.", "a": "Examples include the United Kingdom, Australia, Canada, India, New Zealand, South Africa, Singapore, Pakistan, Jamaica, Cyprus and Malta.", "section": "5.7", "page": 90, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "What was the European Union originally called, and who founded it?", "a": "Originally the European Economic Community (EEC), set up by six western European countries — Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands — who signed the Treaty of Rome on 25 March 1957.", "section": "5.7", "page": 91, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "When did the UK join the EEC/EU?", "a": "The UK originally decided not to join and became a member in 1973.", "section": "5.7", "page": 91, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "When did Brexit officially take place?", "a": "The UK left the EU at 23:00 GMT on 31 January 2020, after the Brexit vote.", "section": "5.7", "page": 91, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "How many EU member states are there now?", "a": "27.", "section": "5.7", "page": 91, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "What are European laws called?", "a": "Directives, regulations or framework decisions. With effect from 2024, no general principle of EU law is part of UK law.", "section": "5.7", "page": 92, "tags": ["international", "law"]}, {"q": "What is the Council of Europe?", "a": "A body separate from the EU with 47 member countries, including the UK, responsible for the protection and promotion of human rights. It has no power to make laws but draws up conventions and charters, most notably the European Convention on Human Rights.", "section": "5.7", "page": 92, "tags": ["international", "rights"]}, {"q": "What is the United Nations and why was it set up?", "a": "An international organisation with more than 190 countries as members, of which the UK is one. It was set up after the Second World War and aims to prevent war and promote international peace and security.", "section": "5.7", "page": 92, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "How many members does the UN Security Council have, and what is the UK's position on it?", "a": "There are 15 members on the UN Security Council, which recommends action when there are international crises and threats to peace. The UK is one of five permanent members.", "section": "5.7", "page": 92, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "What is NATO?", "a": "A group of European and North American countries that have agreed to help each other if they come under attack; it also aims to maintain peace between all of its members. The UK is a member.", "section": "5.7", "page": 92, "tags": ["international"]}, {"q": "Name some of the shared values and responsibilities of living in the UK.", "a": "To obey and respect the law; be aware of and respect the rights of others; treat others with fairness; behave responsibly; help and protect your family; respect and preserve the environment; treat everyone equally regardless of sex, race, religion, age, disability, class or sexual orientation; work to provide for yourself and your family; help others; and vote in local and national government elections.", "section": "5.8", "page": 93, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "How can you be a good neighbour?", "a": "Introduce yourself when you move in; respect your neighbours' privacy and limit how much noise you make; keep your garden tidy; and only put refuse bags and bins on the street or in communal areas if they are due to be collected.", "section": "5.8", "page": 93, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Who can be asked to serve on a jury?", "a": "Anyone who is on the electoral register and is aged 18 to 70. People are randomly selected from the electoral register.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 93, "tags": ["community", "courts"]}, {"q": "How can parents help at their children's schools?", "a": "Parents can often help in classrooms, by supporting activities or listening to children read. They can also volunteer at fund-raising events (e.g. book sales, toy sales, bringing food to sell), sometimes organised by parent-teacher associations (PTAs).", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 93, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Who can become a school governor or school board member?", "a": "People from the local community who wish to make a positive contribution to children's education. They must be aged 18 or over at the date of their election or appointment; there is no upper age limit. (School boards are the Scottish equivalent of school governors.)", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "What are the three key roles of school governors and school boards?", "a": "Setting the strategic direction of the school; ensuring accountability; and monitoring and evaluating school performance.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "In England, what can parents and community groups apply to do regarding schools?", "a": "They can apply to open a free school in their local area (information from the Department for Education). In England you can also apply online to be a school governor at the School Governors' One-Stop Shop.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "What is 'canvassing'?", "a": "Party members working to persuade people to vote for their candidates at election times — for instance, by handing out leaflets in the street or by knocking on people's doors and asking for their support. You don't have to tell a canvasser how you intend to vote.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community", "elections"]}, {"q": "Which offices can British citizens stand for?", "a": "Local councillor, member of Parliament (or the devolved equivalents) or member of the European Parliament. Irish citizens, eligible Commonwealth citizens or citizens of another EU country may also be able to stand (except that EU citizens cannot stand to be an MP).", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community", "elections"]}, {"q": "How can you volunteer with the police or the courts?", "a": "You can volunteer with the police and become a special constable or a lay (non-police) representative. You can also apply to become a magistrate.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community", "police"]}, {"q": "How long does giving blood take?", "a": "Giving blood only takes about an hour to do.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Why register as an organ donor, and what can living people donate?", "a": "If you register to be an organ donor, it can make it easier for your family to decide whether to donate your organs when you die. Living people can also donate a kidney.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "What is volunteering and what are its benefits?", "a": "Volunteering is working for good causes without payment. Benefits include meeting new people, helping make your community a better place, a chance to practise your English or develop work skills that help you find a job or improve your CV.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Give examples of activities you can do as a volunteer.", "a": "Working with animals (e.g. at a rescue shelter), youth work, helping improve the environment (e.g. a litter pick-up), working with the homeless in a shelter, mentoring (e.g. supporting someone just out of prison), working in health and hospitals, and helping older people (e.g. at a residential care home).", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Match some UK charities to their causes.", "a": "Age UK — older people; NSPCC (National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children) — children; Crisis and Shelter — the homeless; Cancer Research UK — medical research; the National Trust and Friends of the Earth — the environment; PDSA (People's Dispensary for Sick Animals) — animals; the British Red Cross — British branch of an international organisation.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 94, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "What is the National Citizen Service?", "a": "A programme that gives 16- and 17-year-olds the opportunity to enjoy outdoor activities, develop their skills and take part in a community project.", "section": "5.8.1", "page": 95, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "Why is recycling important?", "a": "Using recycled materials to make new products uses less energy and means we do not need to extract more raw materials from the earth. It also means less rubbish is created, so the amount going into landfill is reduced.", "section": "5.8.2", "page": 95, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "How does shopping locally help?", "a": "It helps businesses and farmers in your area and in Britain, and reduces your carbon footprint because the products you buy will not have had to travel as far.", "section": "5.8.2", "page": 95, "tags": ["community"]}, {"q": "How does walking or using public transport help the environment?", "a": "You create less pollution than when you use a car.", "section": "5.8.2", "page": 95, "tags": ["community"]}]}, {"chapter": 6, "title": "Key facts & dates (quick revision)", "sections": [{"id": "6.2.1", "title": "Key acts", "summary": "- **Magna Carta (1215)** — reduced rights of the king and laid out basic rights of the people.\n- **Act for the Government of Wales (during the reign of Henry VIII, 1500s)** — formally united Wales with England. *(appendix misprints 'Henry VII')*\n- **Habeas Corpus Act (1679)** — forbid unlawful imprisonment.\n- **Bill of Rights (1689)** — confirmed the rights of Parliament and the limits of the king's power.\n- **Act of Union (1707)** — united the kingdoms of England and Scotland and created the Kingdom of GB.\n- **Reform Act (1832)** — abolished pocket and rotten boroughs and gave more parliamentary seats to towns and cities; increased the number of (male) voters.\n- **Emancipation Act (1833)** — abolished slavery throughout the British Empire. William Wilberforce was a leading abolitionist and Quakers set up the first anti-slavery groups. More than 2 million migrants came from India and China to replace the labour force.\n- **Women's suffrage** — 1918 (vote at 30+ yrs) and 1928 (vote at 21 yrs, same as men).\n- **Home Rule (1913)** — proposed in Ireland: a self-governing Ireland with its own parliament that still remained part of the UK. WWI postponed any changes; Irish nationalists didn't want to wait and the Easter Rising against the British in Dublin took place in 1916. Guerrilla war followed.\n- **Peace treaty (1921)** — signed in 1921; in 1922 Ireland became two countries. *(appendix says the 1921 treaty split Ireland in two)*", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "6.2.2", "title": "Eras", "summary": "- **Romans (43–410 AD)** — ruled Britain for approximately 400 years. Hadrian's wall was built on the orders of Roman Emperor Hadrian to keep out tribes (Picts) who lived in what is now Scotland.\n- **Middle Ages (1066–1485)** — period of constant war, including the Crusades and the Hundred Years' War.\n- **Elizabethan period (1500s)** — known for growing patriotism, expanded trade and rich poetry and drama.\n- **The Enlightenment (1700s)** — development of new ideas about politics, philosophy and science. Adam Smith (economics) and David Hume (philosopher) were influential Scottish thinkers.\n- **Industrial Revolution (mid-1700s to 1800s)** — Britain produced over half of the world's supplies of cotton cloth, coal and iron. Machinery and steam power developed.\n- **Victorian Age (1837–1901)** — Queen Victoria reigned; Britain increased power and influence abroad and became the largest empire in world history. The middle classes grew significantly and reformers improved conditions for the poor.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "6.2.3", "title": "Modern era", "summary": "- **1900s inventions and discoveries** — jet engine and radar invented; TV & World Wide Web (Tim Berners-Lee) invented; hovercraft invented (Sir Christopher Cockerell); penicillin discovered (Alexander Fleming); ATM invented; cloned sheep Dolly; Concorde (supersonic jet) developed with the French; insulin co-discovered and MRI co-invented; structure of the DNA molecule discovered; radio telescope at Jodrell Bank was for many years the world's largest; Harrier jump jet (takes off vertically); IVF therapy.\n- **Before WWI** — state retirement pension and free school meals introduced.\n- **1929** — Great Depression. Aviation and automobile industries developed; high unemployment, especially in \"heavy\" industries (e.g. shipbuilding).\n- **1942** — Beveridge Report (William Beveridge) set out ideas which led to the foundation of the modern welfare state.\n- **1944** — Education Act (R A Butler): free secondary education and a clear distinction between primary and secondary education.\n- **1945–1950** — NHS and social security system established.\n- **1947** — 9 colonies gained independence, including India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.\n- **1950s** — post-war labour shortages led to recruitment of workers from India, Pakistan, West Indies and Bangladesh.\n- **1960s** — increased wealth and liberalisation of social laws (e.g. abortion and divorce).\n- **1973** — UK joined the EEC.\n- **1998** — Good Friday Agreement led to the establishment of the Northern Ireland Assembly. *(appendix calls it a 'Northern Irish parliament')*\n- **1999** — Scottish parliament & Welsh assembly established.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "6.2.4", "title": "Battles and wars", "summary": "- **1066** — William of Normandy conquered England at the Battle of Hastings (Bayeux Tapestry).\n- **1314** — Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish King Robert the Bruce defeated the English.\n- **1455** — Wars of the Roses: civil war between the House of Lancaster (red rose) and the House of York (white rose) to determine who should be king of England. Ended at the Battle of Bosworth Field (1485); Henry Tudor of the House of Lancaster became King Henry VII and married Elizabeth of York, uniting the two families as the House of Tudor (red rose with a white rose inside).\n- **Mid-15th century** — last of the Welsh rebellions had been defeated.\n- **1588** — Spanish Armada was defeated under Elizabeth I.\n- **1642** — beginning of the English Civil War (Charles I recalled Parliament in 1640 to ask for funds): Parliament (supporters: Roundheads) vs the King (Cavaliers). Charles I introduced a revised Prayer Book; many in Parliament were Puritans who didn't back him. *(appendix dates the start of the war to 1640; the handbook says 1642)* The King's army was defeated at the Battles of Marston Moor and Naseby. King Charles I executed.\n- **1776** — American colonies declared independence over taxation.\n- **1805** — Battle of Trafalgar: Lord Horatio Nelson (of Nelson's Column) defeated the French (Napoleon) + Spanish fleet.\n- **1815** — Battle of Waterloo: Lord Wellington defeated Napoleon.\n- **1899–1902** — Boer War in South Africa. *(appendix misprints 1889–1902)*\n- **1916** — Battle of the Somme (WW1): British forces suffered 60,000 casualties on the first day.\n- **1918** — WWI ended at 11.00 on 11/11.\n- **1939** — German invasion of Poland led the UK and France to declare war on Germany.\n- **1940 (WWII)** — Evacuation of Dunkirk: rescue of 300,000 men by volunteers and small boats.\n- **1940 (WWII)** — Battle of Britain: German/British aerial battle.\n- **1982** — Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "6.2.5", "title": "Key events", "summary": "- **1348** — Black Death: killed one third of the population of England, with a similar proportion in Scotland and Wales. Fewer people meant less need for cereal crops as well as labour shortages, then increased wages. Movement into cities and towns; gentry (landowners of large plots) and middle class developed.\n- **1400** — English became the preferred language of courts and official documents.\n- **1660** — The Restoration (of the monarchy): Charles (King of Scotland) was invited to come back as King Charles II after Oliver Cromwell's death.\n- **1665** — Great Plague.\n- **Glorious Revolution (1688)** — English Protestants asked Mary's husband William of Orange (of the Netherlands) to proclaim himself king, as they didn't want a Catholic king. He faced no resistance.\n- **Queen Elizabeth I's reign** — English settlers began to move to the North American colonies.", "checkUnderstand": []}, {"id": "6.2.6", "title": "People", "summary": "- **Sir Robert Walpole** — first PM (1721–1742), as King George I (a German) relied heavily on ministers because of his poor English.\n- **Oliver Cromwell** — titled Lord Protector (circa 1640s–1650s) and led Britain whilst it was without a monarch.\n- **King Alfred the Great** — united the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of England and defeated the Vikings.\n- **Isambard Kingdom Brunel** — engineer (bridges, trains, tunnels, ships).\n- **Dylan Thomas** — Welsh poet (\"Under Milk Wood\" & \"Do Not Go Gentle into that Good Night\").\n- **Robert Burns** — Scottish poet (\"The Bard\"), Auld Lang Syne.\n- **Richard Arkwright** — efficient and profitable factory owner during the Industrial Revolution.\n- **Sake Dean Mahomet** — set up the first curry house in Britain and introduced shampooing.\n- **Florence Nightingale** — founder of modern nursing.\n- **Emmeline Pankhurst** — suffrage leader.\n- **Rudyard Kipling** — Indian-born author and poet; work reflected the idea that the British empire was a force for good.\n- **George and Robert Stephenson** — father and son who pioneered the railway engine. *(appendix misprints 'Stevenson')*\n- **St Columba & St Augustine** — St Columba was a missionary from Ireland who founded a monastery on Iona; St Augustine led missionaries from Rome and became the first Archbishop of Canterbury. *(appendix says both led missionaries from Rome)*\n- **Sir Francis Drake** — Elizabethan sailor who helped defeat the Spanish Armada and later sailed around the world.\n- **Huguenots** — French Protestant refugees fleeing persecution who came to England between 1680 and 1720. *(appendix misprints 'Hugunots' and says 'pre-1720')*\n- **Henry VIII** — famous for marrying 6 times and breaking away from the Church of Rome so he could get a divorce. Wales was united with England under his rule. Wives (in order): (1) Catherine of Aragon (2) Anne Boleyn (3) Jane Seymour (4) Anne of Cleves (5) Catherine Howard (6) Catherine Parr.\n- **Margaret Thatcher** — first female PM and the longest serving PM of the 20th century.\n- **Alexander Fleming** — Scottish doctor who discovered penicillin (1928).\n- **Clement Attlee** — Churchill's Deputy PM; became PM in 1945. Nationalised major industries and created the NHS.\n- **Mary Peters** — Olympic athlete who promoted sport and tourism in Northern Ireland.\n- **Roald Dahl** — Welsh author (\"Charlie and the Chocolate Factory\" & \"George's Marvellous Medicine\").\n- **Sir Arthur Conan Doyle** — Scottish author (\"Sherlock Holmes\").", "checkUnderstand": []}], "flashcards": [{"q": "What did Magna Carta (1215) do?", "a": "Reduced rights of the king and laid out basic rights of the people.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Act for the Government of Wales do?", "a": "Formally united Wales with England, during the reign of Henry VIII. *(the PDF's appendix misprints this as 'under King Henry VII' — the handbook text says Wales became formally united with England by this Act during the reign of Henry VIII)*", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Habeas Corpus Act (1679) do?", "a": "Forbid unlawful imprisonment.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Bill of Rights (1689) do?", "a": "Confirmed the rights of Parliament and the limits of the king's power.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Act of Union (1707) do?", "a": "United the kingdoms of England and Scotland and created the Kingdom of GB.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Reform Act (1832) do?", "a": "Abolished pocket and rotten boroughs, gave more parliamentary seats to towns and cities, and increased the number of (male) voters.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What did the Emancipation Act (1833) do?", "a": "Abolished slavery throughout the British Empire. William Wilberforce was a leading abolitionist; Quakers set up the first anti-slavery groups. Over 2 million migrants came from India and China to replace the labour force.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "When did women gain the vote?", "a": "1918 (vote at 30+ years) and 1928 (vote at 21 years, the same as men).", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What was Home Rule (proposed 1913)?", "a": "A self-governing Ireland with its own parliament that still remained part of the UK. WWI postponed changes; the Easter Rising against the British in Dublin took place in 1916, and guerrilla war followed.", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1921 regarding Ireland?", "a": "A peace treaty was signed; in 1922 Ireland became two countries. *(the PDF's appendix says the 1921 treaty split Ireland in two — the handbook text says the treaty was signed in 1921 and Ireland became two countries in 1922)*", "section": "6.2.1", "page": 97, "tags": ["acts"]}, {"q": "When did the Romans rule Britain?", "a": "43-410 AD (approximately 400 years).", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "Why was Hadrian's wall built?", "a": "On the orders of Roman Emperor Hadrian, to keep out tribes (Picts) who lived in what is now Scotland.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "What were the Middle Ages (1066-1485) known for?", "a": "A period of constant war, including the Crusades and the Hundred Years' War.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "What was the Elizabethan period (1500s) known for?", "a": "Growing patriotism, expanded trade and rich poetry and drama.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "What was the Enlightenment (1700s)?", "a": "Development of new ideas about politics, philosophy and science. Adam Smith (economics) and David Hume (philosopher) were influential Scottish thinkers.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "What happened during the Industrial Revolution (mid-1700s to 1800s)?", "a": "Britain produced over half of the world's supplies of cotton cloth, coal and iron; machinery and steam power developed.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "What characterised the Victorian Age (1837-1901)?", "a": "Queen Victoria reigned; Britain increased power and influence abroad and became the largest empire in world history. The middle classes grew significantly and reformers improved conditions for the poor.", "section": "6.2.2", "page": 97, "tags": ["eras"]}, {"q": "Who invented the World Wide Web?", "a": "Tim Berners-Lee.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "Who invented the hovercraft?", "a": "Sir Christopher Cockerell. *(the PDF's appendix misprints this as 'Cockrell' — the handbook text spells it Cockerell)*", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "Which supersonic jet did Britain develop with the French?", "a": "Concorde.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "Name British 1900s inventions and discoveries besides the WWW, hovercraft and Concorde.", "a": "Jet engine and radar; TV; penicillin discovered (Alexander Fleming); ATM; cloned sheep Dolly; insulin co-discovered; MRI co-invented; DNA molecule structure discovered; Harrier jump jet (takes off vertically); IVF therapy. The Jodrell Bank radio telescope was for many years the world's largest. *(the PDF's appendix misprints the discoverer of penicillin as 'Sir Alexander Flemming' — the handbook text spells it Alexander Fleming)*", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "When were the state retirement pension and free school meals introduced?", "a": "Before WWI.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1929?", "a": "The Great Depression. Aviation and automobile industries developed; high unemployment, especially in \"heavy\" industries (e.g. shipbuilding).", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What was the Beveridge Report (1942)?", "a": "A report by William Beveridge that set out ideas which led to the foundation of the modern welfare state.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What did the Education Act (1944) do, and who was behind it?", "a": "R A Butler; it introduced free secondary education and a clear distinction between primary and secondary education.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "When were the NHS and social security system established?", "a": "1945-1950.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1947?", "a": "9 colonies gained independence, including India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What happened in the 1950s regarding labour?", "a": "Post-war labour shortages led to recruitment of workers from India, Pakistan, West Indies and Bangladesh.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What characterised the 1960s?", "a": "Increased wealth and liberalisation of social laws (e.g. abortion and divorce).", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "When did the UK join the EEC?", "a": "1973.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What did the Good Friday Agreement (1998) lead to?", "a": "The establishment of the Northern Ireland Assembly. *(the PDF's appendix calls this a 'Northern Irish parliament' — the handbook text says the Northern Ireland Assembly was established soon after the Good Friday Agreement)*", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "When were the Scottish parliament and Welsh assembly established?", "a": "1999.", "section": "6.2.3", "page": 97, "tags": ["modern"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1066?", "a": "William of Normandy conquered England at the Battle of Hastings (depicted in the Bayeux Tapestry).", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 97, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who won the Battle of Bannockburn (1314)?", "a": "Scottish King Robert the Bruce defeated the English.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 97, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who fought in the Wars of the Roses (from 1455) and how did they end?", "a": "The House of Lancaster (red rose) vs the House of York (white rose), over who should be king of England. It ended at the Battle of Bosworth Field (1485): Henry Tudor of the House of Lancaster became King Henry VII and married Elizabeth of York, uniting the families as the House of Tudor (red rose with a white rose inside). *(the PDF's appendix misprints the name as 'War of the Roses' — the handbook text calls it the Wars of the Roses)*", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 97, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "By when had the last of the Welsh rebellions been defeated?", "a": "By the mid-15th century.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 97, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1588?", "a": "The Spanish Armada was defeated under Elizabeth I.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who fought in the English Civil War and what happened?", "a": "Parliament (supporters: Roundheads) vs the King (Cavaliers). Charles I introduced a revised Prayer Book; many in Parliament were Puritans who didn't back him. Charles recalled Parliament in 1640 to ask for funds, and the civil war began in 1642. The King's army was defeated at the Battles of Marston Moor and Naseby, and King Charles I was executed. *(the PDF's appendix dates the beginning of the war to 1640 — the handbook text says Charles recalled Parliament in 1640 and the civil war began in 1642)*", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1776?", "a": "American colonies declared independence over taxation.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who won the Battle of Trafalgar (1805)?", "a": "Lord Horatio Nelson (of Nelson's Column) defeated the French (Napoleon) + Spanish fleet.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Who won the Battle of Waterloo (1815)?", "a": "Lord Wellington defeated Napoleon.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "When and where was the Boer War?", "a": "1899-1902, in South Africa. *(the PDF's appendix misprints this as 1889-1902 — the handbook text says the Boer War of 1899 to 1902)*", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened at the Battle of the Somme (1916, WW1)?", "a": "British forces suffered 60,000 casualties on the first day.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "When did WWI end?", "a": "1918, at 11.00 on 11/11.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "Why did the UK and France declare war on Germany in 1939?", "a": "The German invasion of Poland.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Evacuation of Dunkirk (1940, WWII)?", "a": "The rescue of 300,000 men by volunteers and small boats.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Battle of Britain (1940, WWII)?", "a": "A German/British aerial battle.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What happened in 1982?", "a": "Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands.", "section": "6.2.4", "page": 98, "tags": ["battles"]}, {"q": "What was the Black Death (1348) and its effects?", "a": "It killed one third of the population of England, and a similar proportion in Scotland and Wales. *(the PDF's appendix says it killed 'over 1/3 of Britain' — the handbook text says one third of the population of England died, with a similar proportion in Scotland and Wales)* Fewer people meant less need for cereal crops and labour shortages, then increased wages; movement into cities and towns; gentry (landowners of large plots) and middle class developed.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "What happened around 1400 regarding the English language?", "a": "English became the preferred language of courts and official documents.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "What was the Restoration (1660)?", "a": "The restoration of the monarchy: Charles (King of Scotland) was invited to come back as King Charles II after Oliver Cromwell's death.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "When was the Great Plague?", "a": "1665.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "What was the Glorious Revolution (1688)?", "a": "English Protestants asked Mary's husband William of Orange (of the Netherlands) to proclaim himself king, as they didn't want a Catholic king. He faced no resistance.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "When did English settlers begin to move to the North American colonies?", "a": "During Queen Elizabeth I's reign.", "section": "6.2.5", "page": 98, "tags": ["events"]}, {"q": "Who was the first PM, and why did he hold so much power?", "a": "Sir Robert Walpole (PM 1721-1742), because King George I (a German) relied heavily on ministers due to his poor English.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Oliver Cromwell?", "a": "Titled Lord Protector (circa 1640s-1650s); led Britain whilst it was without a monarch.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What did King Alfred the Great do?", "a": "United the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of England and defeated the Vikings.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Isambard Kingdom Brunel?", "a": "An engineer (bridges, trains, tunnels, ships).", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Dylan Thomas?", "a": "Welsh poet (\"Under Milk Wood\" & \"Do Not Go Gentle into that Good Night\").", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Robert Burns?", "a": "Scottish poet (\"The Bard\"); wrote Auld Lang Syne.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Richard Arkwright?", "a": "An efficient and profitable factory owner during the Industrial Revolution.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Sake Dean Mahomet?", "a": "Set up the first curry house in Britain and introduced shampooing.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Florence Nightingale?", "a": "The founder of modern nursing.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Emmeline Pankhurst?", "a": "A suffrage leader.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Rudyard Kipling?", "a": "An Indian-born author and poet whose work reflected the idea that the British empire was a force for good.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who were George and Robert Stephenson?", "a": "Father and son who pioneered the railway engine. *(the PDF's appendix misprints the name as 'Stevenson' — the handbook text spells it Stephenson)*", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who were St Columba and St Augustine?", "a": "St Columba was one of the famous missionaries from Ireland who spread Christianity in the north, and founded a monastery on the island of Iona; St Augustine led missionaries from Rome, who spread Christianity in the south, and became the first Archbishop of Canterbury. *(the PDF's appendix says both 'led missionaries from Rome' — the handbook text says St Columba was a missionary from Ireland, while St Augustine led missionaries from Rome)*", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Sir Francis Drake?", "a": "An Elizabethan sailor who helped defeat the Spanish Armada and later sailed around the world.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who were the Huguenots?", "a": "French Protestant refugees fleeing persecution who came to England between 1680 and 1720. *(the PDF's appendix misprints the name as 'Hugunots' and says 'pre-1720' — the handbook text spells it Huguenots and says they came between 1680 and 1720)*", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "What is Henry VIII famous for?", "a": "Marrying 6 times and breaking away from the Church of Rome so he could get a divorce. Wales was united with England under his rule.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Name Henry VIII's six wives in order.", "a": "(1) Catherine of Aragon (2) Anne Boleyn (3) Jane Seymour (4) Anne of Cleves (5) Catherine Howard (6) Catherine Parr.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Margaret Thatcher?", "a": "The first female PM and the longest serving PM of the 20th century.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who discovered penicillin, and when?", "a": "Alexander Fleming, a Scottish doctor, in 1928.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Clement Attlee?", "a": "Churchill's Deputy PM who became PM in 1945; he nationalised major industries and created the NHS.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Mary Peters?", "a": "An Olympic athlete who promoted sport and tourism in Northern Ireland.", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Roald Dahl?", "a": "Welsh author (\"Charlie and the Chocolate Factory\" & \"George's Marvellous Medicine\").", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}, {"q": "Who was Sir Arthur Conan Doyle?", "a": "Scottish author (\"Sherlock Holmes\").", "section": "6.2.6", "page": 98, "tags": ["people"]}]}];
